const PRACTICE_POOL = [{"id":"phr01","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"A 9-year-old dog with protein-losing enteropathy (serum albumin 1.6 g/dL) receives a standard co-induction dose of midazolam and shows a markedly deeper and more prolonged effect than expected. Reduced binding of midazolam to which plasma protein best explains this exaggerated response?","options":["Alpha-1-acid glycoprotein","Globulin","Albumin","Fibrinogen"],"answer":2,"explain":"Midazolam is highly (~95%) protein bound, primarily to albumin. In hypoalbuminemia the free (active) fraction rises, so a standard dose produces a deeper, longer effect. Alpha-1-acid glycoprotein is the main binder of basic drugs such as lidocaine, not the primary binder of midazolam."},{"id":"phr02","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"Post-induction apnea after propofol is best characterized by which statement about what principally determines its likelihood and severity?","options":["The rate of injection alone, independent of the total dose given","Concurrent opioid administration, which is the sole cause","An IgE-mediated hypersensitivity reaction to the lipid emulsion vehicle","The rate of injection together with the total dose administered"],"answer":3,"explain":"Propofol-induced apnea is both rate- and dose-dependent: a rapid bolus produces a high peak plasma concentration that depresses central respiratory centers, and larger total doses deepen and prolong it. Rate alone is incomplete (dose also matters); opioids potentiate but are not the sole cause; true lipid hypersensitivity is rare and not the usual mechanism."},{"id":"phr03","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"A 4-year-old cat is premedicated with midazolam and then induced with alfaxalone; induction is remarkably smooth, with pronounced synergy between the two drugs. This synergy is best explained by a shared action at which receptor?","options":["NMDA receptor antagonism","GABA-A receptor potentiation","Mu-opioid receptor agonism","GABA-A receptor antagonism"],"answer":1,"explain":"Alfaxalone is a neuroactive steroid that potentiates the GABA-A receptor; benzodiazepines also potentiate GABA-A (at a distinct site). Because both enhance GABA-A-mediated inhibition, their combined effect is synergistic. NMDA antagonism is ketamine's mechanism, and GABA-A antagonism would be excitatory, the opposite of the observed effect."},{"id":"phr04","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"Ketamine's sympathomimetic effects (tachycardia and increased contractility with higher myocardial oxygen demand) are most likely to precipitate decompensation in a patient with which specific condition?","options":["Dilated cardiomyopathy with reduced contractile reserve","Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy with dynamic left ventricular outflow tract obstruction","Chronic compensated myxomatous mitral valve degeneration","Well-controlled hypoadrenocorticism on replacement therapy"],"answer":1,"explain":"In hypertrophic cardiomyopathy, increased contractility and heart rate worsen dynamic outflow obstruction and raise myocardial oxygen demand against a hypertrophied ventricle, risking decompensation. In dilated cardiomyopathy increased contractility would actually be desirable, which is why the 'increased contractility precipitates decompensation' description points specifically to HCM."},{"id":"phr05","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"A dog with pericardial effusion and early cardiac tamponade (fragile, preload-dependent hemodynamics) requires induction, and etomidate is selected. Which property is the primary reason for this choice?","options":["Reliable suppression of adrenocortical steroidogenesis, blunting the stress response","Marked cardiovascular stability, with minimal effect on heart rate, contractility, and blood pressure","Profound intrinsic analgesia allowing the opioid dose to be reduced","Bronchodilation that improves intraoperative oxygenation"],"answer":1,"explain":"Etomidate is chosen for hemodynamically fragile patients because it maintains heart rate, contractility, and blood pressure with minimal cardiovascular depression. Adrenocortical (11-beta-hydroxylase) suppression is a genuine etomidate effect but is a drawback, not a benefit, and it does not explain the choice; etomidate also lacks analgesia."},{"id":"phr06","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"In the first several minutes after an IV dexmedetomidine bolus, arterial blood pressure rises and heart rate falls sharply. The initial hypertension is mediated by which mechanism?","options":["Postsynaptic alpha-1 receptor activation on vascular smooth muscle causing vasoconstriction","Reduced central sympathetic outflow via presynaptic alpha-2A receptors","Postsynaptic alpha-2B receptor activation on vascular smooth muscle causing vasoconstriction","Direct stimulation of the vagal nucleus"],"answer":2,"explain":"Early hypertension is driven by peripheral postsynaptic alpha-2B receptor activation on vascular smooth muscle, causing vasoconstriction; the resulting baroreceptor reflex produces bradycardia. Central alpha-2A activation reduces sympathetic outflow but this is the later phase that lowers blood pressure, not the initial pressor response."},{"id":"phr07","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"A vaporizer is adjusted so the end-tidal isoflurane equals exactly 1.0 MAC. At this concentration, what is expected regarding gross purposeful movement in response to a supramaximal noxious stimulus?","options":["No patients (0%) will move","Approximately 5% of patients will move","Approximately 95% of patients will move","Approximately 50% of patients will still move"],"answer":3,"explain":"By definition, 1.0 MAC is the alveolar concentration that prevents gross purposeful movement to a supramaximal noxious stimulus in 50% of subjects, so about 50% will still move. A common error is to assume 1 MAC abolishes movement in all patients; surgical planes typically require roughly 1.2-1.5 MAC."},{"id":"phr08","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"Several physiologic states alter anesthetic requirement. Which one DECREASES MAC, allowing a lower vaporizer setting?","options":["Hyperthermia","Hypothermia","Hypernatremia","Youth (young age)"],"answer":1,"explain":"Hypothermia decreases MAC (less anesthetic needed). Hyperthermia, hypernatremia, and young age all INCREASE MAC. Other MAC-reducing factors include opioids, alpha-2 agonists, pregnancy, hyponatremia, severe hypotension, and old age. A frequent trap is reversing the sodium relationship: hyponatremia lowers MAC, hypernatremia raises it."},{"id":"phr09","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"To allow more rapid intraoperative adjustments in anesthetic depth for a brachycephalic dog, you choose sevoflurane (blood:gas ~0.65) over isoflurane (~1.4). What does the lower blood:gas partition coefficient predict for this patient?","options":["Slower induction but a faster recovery","Greater potency (a lower MAC)","More rapid induction, recovery, and changes in anesthetic depth","Slower equilibration between inspired and alveolar concentrations"],"answer":2,"explain":"A lower blood:gas partition coefficient means less agent dissolves in blood, so alveolar partial pressure rises (and falls) faster, giving quicker induction, recovery, and depth changes. Solubility governs speed, not potency; potency tracks the oil:gas coefficient (and MAC), a separate property."},{"id":"phr10","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"Which inhalant, in contact with desiccated strong-base CO2 absorbent at low fresh-gas flow, degrades to the potentially nephrotoxic haloalkene known as Compound A?","options":["Isoflurane","Sevoflurane","Desflurane","Nitrous oxide"],"answer":1,"explain":"Sevoflurane degrades to Compound A in contact with desiccated CO2 absorbents, especially at low fresh-gas flows; maintaining adequate flows mitigates this. Isoflurane and desflurane with desiccated absorbent instead generate carbon monoxide rather than Compound A, a distinct hazard."},{"id":"phr11","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"A cat received an opioid premedication about 4 hours ago. It is now mildly sedate and hypoventilating; a standard dose of naloxone produces only partial, short-lived improvement and must be repeated at higher doses. Which opioid best explains this naloxone-resistant picture?","options":["Hydromorphone","Fentanyl","Buprenorphine","Methadone"],"answer":2,"explain":"Buprenorphine is a partial mu-agonist with very high receptor affinity and slow dissociation, so it resists displacement by naloxone and often requires higher or repeated antagonist doses. Hydromorphone, fentanyl, and methadone are full mu-agonists that are readily reversed by standard naloxone dosing."},{"id":"phr12","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"Beyond mu-agonism, which additional mechanism gives methadone theoretical advantages against central sensitization ('wind-up') compared with a pure mu-agonist like hydromorphone?","options":["Agonism of NMDA receptors","Antagonism of peripheral alpha-2 receptors","Inhibition of cyclooxygenase (COX)","Antagonism of NMDA receptors"],"answer":3,"explain":"Methadone antagonizes NMDA receptors (and inhibits monoamine reuptake), which may blunt central sensitization and wind-up in addition to its mu-agonist analgesia. NMDA agonism would promote sensitization (the opposite), and methadone has no meaningful alpha-2 or COX activity."},{"id":"phr13","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"A dog is over-sedated and hypoventilating after hydromorphone, and you titrate naloxone to restore ventilation. What should you anticipate as an unavoidable consequence of giving enough naloxone to reverse the respiratory depression?","options":["Selective reversal of respiratory depression while analgesia is preserved","Reversal of sedation only, leaving both analgesia and ventilation unchanged","Reversal of analgesia along with the respiratory depression","Reversal of nausea and ileus without affecting analgesia"],"answer":2,"explain":"Naloxone is a non-selective competitive opioid antagonist; it cannot selectively spare analgesia, so reversing respiratory depression also reverses analgesia. Titrate slowly in small increments to restore ventilation while preserving as much analgesia as possible, and be ready to re-dose given naloxone's short duration."},{"id":"phr14","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"A novel opioid produces potent analgesia but also dose-dependent respiratory depression and bradycardia. Activation of which receptor is chiefly responsible for BOTH the potent analgesia and the respiratory depression?","options":["Kappa","Delta","Mu","Sigma"],"answer":2,"explain":"The mu-opioid receptor mediates the most potent analgesia and also respiratory depression, bradycardia, and euphoria/dysphoria. Kappa activation provides milder analgesia with comparatively less respiratory depression, which is the decisive difference; delta contributes modestly, and sigma is not a classic opioid receptor."},{"id":"phr15","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"During anesthesia a dog suddenly develops severe symptomatic bradycardia (HR 40) with hypotension. You reach for atropine rather than glycopyrrolate. The primary reason atropine is preferred in this acute crisis is that it:","options":["Has a longer duration of action than glycopyrrolate","Produces less profound tachycardia than glycopyrrolate","Cannot cross the blood-brain barrier","Has a more rapid onset of action"],"answer":3,"explain":"Atropine has a faster onset than glycopyrrolate, making it preferable in an acute symptomatic bradycardic crisis. Atropine is actually shorter-acting than glycopyrrolate, and it DOES cross the blood-brain barrier and placenta (glycopyrrolate does not) - so those statements are incorrect."},{"id":"phr16","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"A dog sedated with dexmedetomidine needs reversal, and atipamezole is chosen. Atipamezole works as a competitive antagonist at which receptor?","options":["Alpha-1 adrenergic receptors","Alpha-2 adrenergic receptors","Mu-opioid receptors","The GABA-A benzodiazepine site"],"answer":1,"explain":"Atipamezole is a specific alpha-2 adrenergic antagonist and reverses alpha-2 agonists such as dexmedetomidine, medetomidine, and xylazine. It should be given IM (not IV) to avoid acute hypotension and arousal. It has no meaningful alpha-1, opioid, or benzodiazepine activity."},{"id":"phr17","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"A dog co-induced with a benzodiazepine remains excessively sedate; flumazenil is administered with good effect, but sedation returns about 30 minutes later. Flumazenil specifically reversed which of the following?","options":["Ketamine","Midazolam","Acepromazine","Dexmedetomidine"],"answer":1,"explain":"Flumazenil is a specific benzodiazepine antagonist and reverses midazolam and diazepam. Its short duration explains the return of sedation when the benzodiazepine outlasts it. Dexmedetomidine is reversed by atipamezole, not flumazenil; ketamine and acepromazine have no specific antagonist."},{"id":"phr18","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"Acepromazine is avoided in a hypovolemic patient chiefly because it produces hypotension through which mechanism?","options":["Antagonism of peripheral alpha-2 adrenergic receptors causing vasodilation","Agonism of beta-2 receptors causing vasodilation","Massive histamine release causing vasodilation","Antagonism of peripheral alpha-1 adrenergic receptors causing vasodilation"],"answer":3,"explain":"Acepromazine, a phenothiazine, blocks peripheral alpha-1 adrenergic receptors, causing vasodilation and a fall in systemic vascular resistance and blood pressure - dangerous in hypovolemia or shock. It is not an alpha-2 antagonist or beta-2 agonist, and clinically significant hypotension is due to alpha-1 blockade rather than histamine release."},{"id":"phy01","domain":"Physiology","q":"A dog receiving an IV lidocaine CRI for ventricular tachycardia shows a slightly blunted, slowed upstroke of its ventricular action potentials. Lidocaine is a class Ib agent that acts on the channel responsible for phase 0 of the fast-response cardiac action potential. Which ion movement normally generates that phase 0 upstroke?","options":["Efflux of potassium through delayed-rectifier channels, the current that repolarizes the cell","Influx of calcium through L-type channels, the current that sustains the plateau","Rapid influx of sodium through fast voltage-gated channels, generating the steep upstroke","Slow influx of calcium through T-type channels, as occurs in pacemaker cells"],"answer":2,"explain":"Phase 0 (the steep upstroke) of the fast-response action potential in atrial, ventricular, and Purkinje cells is generated by rapid influx of Na+ through fast voltage-gated sodium channels; lidocaine (class Ib) blocks these channels, blunting the upstroke. L-type calcium influx drives the phase 2 plateau (and is the phase 0 current in slow SA/AV nodal cells, not fast-response myocytes), and delayed-rectifier K+ efflux mediates phase 3 repolarization."},{"id":"phy02","domain":"Physiology","q":"When cardiac output must be estimated from its components under anesthesia, it is calculated as heart rate multiplied by which single quantity?","options":["Systemic vascular resistance, the afterload the ventricle ejects against","End-diastolic volume, which represents ventricular preload","Ejection fraction, the proportion of end-diastolic volume ejected","Stroke volume, the end-diastolic minus end-systolic volume"],"answer":3,"explain":"Cardiac output = heart rate × stroke volume, where stroke volume equals end-diastolic minus end-systolic volume. End-diastolic volume alone is preload (a determinant of stroke volume, not stroke volume itself); ejection fraction is the fraction of end-diastolic volume ejected (a ratio, not a volume × rate); and systemic vascular resistance relates output to pressure (MAP ≈ CO × SVR), not to output itself."},{"id":"phy03","domain":"Physiology","q":"A 4 kg cat under isoflurane for a dental has a direct (invasive) arterial pressure of 85/40 mmHg. Using the standard estimate, what is this cat's mean arterial pressure?","options":["About 55 mmHg — below the ~60 mmHg generally required for organ perfusion","About 63 mmHg — the simple average of the systolic and diastolic values","About 70 mmHg — adding two-thirds (rather than one-third) of the pulse pressure to diastolic","About 45 mmHg — which is actually just the pulse pressure (systolic minus diastolic)"],"answer":0,"explain":"MAP ≈ diastolic + 1/3(systolic − diastolic) = 40 + 1/3(85−40) = 40 + 15 = 55 mmHg, reflecting that roughly two-thirds of the cardiac cycle is spent in diastole. This is below the ~60 mmHg needed for renal, cerebral, and coronary perfusion, so intervention is warranted. The arithmetic mean (≈63) overestimates MAP by ignoring the longer diastolic period, using two-thirds of the pulse pressure gives 70, and 45 mmHg is merely the pulse pressure."},{"id":"phy04","domain":"Physiology","q":"A fall in arterial pressure reduces stretch on the carotid sinus and aortic arch baroreceptors. Through which sequence does the baroreflex act to restore pressure?","options":["Increased baroreceptor firing that reflexly raises sympathetic vasoconstrictor tone","Decreased baroreceptor firing that disinhibits sympathetic outflow, producing arteriolar vasoconstriction","Decreased baroreceptor firing that raises vagal tone and slows the heart","Increased baroreceptor firing that triggers vasodilation and bradycardia"],"answer":1,"explain":"Baroreceptors are stretch receptors, so a fall in pressure reduces their afferent firing. This decreased input to the medullary cardiovascular centers disinhibits sympathetic outflow (and withdraws vagal tone), producing arteriolar vasoconstriction (raising SVR), tachycardia, and increased contractility to restore pressure. Increased firing occurs when pressure rises and instead causes vasodilation and bradycardia. Anesthetics blunt this reflex."},{"id":"phy05","domain":"Physiology","q":"A healthy dog is mechanically hyperventilated under anesthesia, lowering its PaCO2 to 22 mmHg. When ventilation is briefly paused, the dog remains apneic for a prolonged period despite a normal PaO2. Which mechanism best explains the delayed return of spontaneous breathing?","options":["The hypoxic drive was abolished because peripheral chemoreceptors no longer sensed a low PaO2","Isoflurane directly paralyzed the diaphragm, preventing inspiratory effort","PaCO2 — the primary drive, sensed by central chemoreceptors via CSF pH — was driven below the apneic threshold","Pulmonary stretch receptors triggered a prolonged Hering–Breuer inspiratory-inhibitory reflex"],"answer":2,"explain":"In a healthy patient the dominant stimulus to breathe is PaCO2, sensed by central chemoreceptors through changes in CSF/interstitial pH. Aggressive hyperventilation drops PaCO2 below the apneic threshold, removing this primary drive, so breathing resumes only once CO2 climbs back — even with a normal PaO2. The hypoxic drive (peripheral chemoreceptors sensing low PaO2) is a weak, secondary stimulus and is irrelevant here because oxygenation is adequate."},{"id":"phy06","domain":"Physiology","q":"Capnography shows a steady end-tidal CO2 of 65 mmHg in an anesthetized dog with normal lungs and a normal alveolar plateau. Accounting for the usual PaCO2–ETCO2 relationship, how should this be interpreted?","options":["Hypercapnia, but true PaCO2 is likely ~60 mmHg because end-tidal CO2 normally overestimates arterial CO2","Hypercapnia, and true PaCO2 is likely ~68–70 mmHg because end-tidal CO2 normally slightly underestimates arterial CO2","Normocapnia, since 65 mmHg falls within the expected end-tidal reference range","Hypocapnia, reflecting anesthetic-induced tachypnea"],"answer":1,"explain":"Normal ETCO2 is ~35–45 mmHg, so 65 mmHg is hypercapnia, nearly always from hypoventilation. In healthy lungs ETCO2 slightly underestimates PaCO2 (by ~2–5 mmHg) because of alveolar dead space, so the true PaCO2 is a few mmHg higher (~68–70), not lower. Management is assisted or controlled ventilation. The value is well above the normocapnic range and is certainly not hypocapnia."},{"id":"phy07","domain":"Physiology","q":"A dog with septic peritonitis is febrile (40.5°C), acidemic (pH 7.24), and hypercarbic. What is the expected effect on its oxyhemoglobin dissociation curve, and what does it mean for tissue oxygen?","options":["A leftward shift that increases hemoglobin–oxygen affinity and reduces tissue offloading","A rightward shift that increases hemoglobin–oxygen affinity, trapping oxygen on hemoglobin","A leftward shift that decreases hemoglobin–oxygen affinity and enhances tissue offloading","A rightward shift that decreases hemoglobin–oxygen affinity and enhances oxygen offloading to tissues"],"answer":3,"explain":"Acidosis (Bohr effect), hypercarbia, hyperthermia, and increased 2,3-DPG all shift the curve rightward, lowering hemoglobin's oxygen affinity and promoting O2 release to metabolically active tissues — so this septic patient has enhanced offloading. Options pairing a rightward shift with increased affinity, or a leftward shift with decreased affinity, are internally inconsistent: a right shift always means lower affinity and greater unloading, and a left shift the opposite."},{"id":"phy08","domain":"Physiology","q":"Under general anesthesia a dog hypoventilates and its PaCO2 rises from 40 to 65 mmHg over 20 minutes. Before any renal compensation can occur, which acid-base picture is expected?","options":["Respiratory acidosis with low pH, high PaCO2, and a nearly normal (only slightly elevated) bicarbonate","Respiratory acidosis with low pH, high PaCO2, and a markedly decreased bicarbonate","Metabolic acidosis with low pH, low bicarbonate, and a compensatory low PaCO2","Respiratory alkalosis with high pH and low PaCO2"],"answer":0,"explain":"Retained CO2 raises PaCO2 and lowers pH: respiratory acidosis, the most common intra-anesthetic acid-base disturbance. Acutely only tissue/plasma buffering operates, so bicarbonate is nearly normal (it rises only ~1 mmol/L per 10 mmHg rise in PaCO2); a markedly low bicarbonate would indicate a concurrent metabolic acidosis. Renal bicarbonate retention takes days and cannot occur within 20 minutes."},{"id":"phy09","domain":"Physiology","q":"A 13-year-old, 22 kg dog undergoing mass removal becomes hypotensive (MAP 55 mmHg) under isoflurane, and urine output falls. Given age-related cardiovascular changes, what is the principal reason renal blood flow is compromised?","options":["An anesthetic-induced rise in cardiac output shunts blood to skeletal muscle and away from the kidneys","Age-related aldosterone deficiency causes salt wasting and prerenal azotemia","Diminished cardiovascular reserve lowers cardiac output, reducing renal perfusion pressure and blood flow","Elevated atrial natriuretic peptide directly vasoconstricts the renal afferent arteriole"],"answer":2,"explain":"Geriatric patients have reduced cardiovascular reserve; under anesthesia their cardiac output falls readily, and because renal blood flow depends on adequate perfusion pressure and output, GFR and urine production decline. Support of blood pressure and cardiac output preserves renal perfusion. Anesthesia does not raise cardiac output, aldosterone deficiency is not the mechanism, and ANP is a natriuretic vasodilator, not a renal afferent vasoconstrictor."},{"id":"phy10","domain":"Physiology","q":"A dog with a portosystemic shunt and hypoalbuminemia needs anesthesia. Which pair of mechanisms best justifies reducing doses of highly protein-bound, hepatically metabolized anesthetics?","options":["Decreased albumin raises the free drug fraction, but induced hepatic enzymes accelerate clearance","Decreased albumin raises the free (active) drug fraction, and impaired hepatic metabolism prolongs drug effect","Increased albumin binds more drug, while reduced metabolism prolongs its effect","Portosystemic shunting increases first-pass hepatic extraction, lowering active drug levels"],"answer":1,"explain":"The liver synthesizes albumin and metabolizes many anesthetics. Disease lowers albumin, so a larger free (active) fraction of protein-bound drug circulates, and reduced biotransformation prolongs effect — both argue for lower, carefully titrated doses. Hepatic disease does not induce enzymes to speed clearance or raise albumin, and portosystemic shunting bypasses the liver, reducing first-pass extraction and further increasing systemic drug exposure."},{"id":"eq01","domain":"Equipment","q":"During a canine exploratory laparotomy the anesthetic plane suddenly lightens, and a new team member presses the oxygen flush valve several times expecting to deepen anesthesia. Regarding what the flush valve actually delivers to the breathing circuit, which statement is correct?","options":["It delivers 35-75 L/min of oxygen through the vaporizer, which is what deepens the plane","It delivers 35-75 L/min of pure oxygen that bypasses the vaporizer, so it actually dilutes the inspired anesthetic and can lighten the plane further","It raises the inspired anesthetic concentration by driving extra carrier gas through the vaporizer","It supplies the drive gas that powers the ventilator bellows, separate from what the patient breathes"],"answer":1,"explain":"The oxygen flush valve delivers 35-75 L/min of pure oxygen directly to the common gas outlet, bypassing the vaporizer. Because it carries NO anesthetic, using it dilutes the inspired agent and will not deepen the plane; with the pop-off closed and patient connected it also risks barotrauma. To deepen anesthesia you increase the vaporizer, not the flush."},{"id":"eq02","domain":"Equipment","q":"Non-rebreathing systems impose minimal resistance and dead space but require high fresh gas flows (about 2-3 times minute ventilation) and conserve little heat and moisture. Given this trade-off, they are the appropriate choice for patients weighing:","options":["Approximately under 5-7 kg","7-15 kg, where a circle system's resistance becomes prohibitive","15-30 kg, to offset the high fresh gas flows required","Any weight, as long as fresh gas flow is raised proportionally"],"answer":0,"explain":"The very feature that makes non-rebreathing systems attractive (low resistance, low dead space) comes at the cost of high fresh gas flow and poor heat/moisture conservation, so they are reserved for small patients, generally under ~5-7 kg. Larger patients are far better served by a circle system, which is economical and conserves heat and humidity."},{"id":"eq03","domain":"Equipment","q":"Ninety minutes into a circle-system anesthetic on a 30 kg dog, the capnograph's inspired (baseline) CO2 begins rising above zero, and the absorbent granules have turned violet and no longer generate their usual warmth. The specific function this canister is failing to perform is:","options":["Adsorbing waste anesthetic vapor before it reaches the scavenging system","Chemically neutralizing exhaled CO2 so it is not rebreathed","Filtering bacteria and particulate matter from the inspired gas","Removing exhaled nitrogen that would otherwise accumulate in the closed circuit"],"answer":1,"explain":"A rising inspired (baseline) CO2, violet color change, and loss of the normal exothermic warmth all mean the soda lime is exhausted. Its only job is to chemically neutralize exhaled CO2 so gas can be rebreathed without hypercapnia. It does not adsorb anesthetic agent, filter bacteria, or remove nitrogen."},{"id":"eq04","domain":"Equipment","q":"A precision, out-of-circuit (VOC) vaporizer receives only fresh gas from the flowmeter and must be temperature-, flow-, and pressure-compensated. Relative to the breathing circuit, it is located:","options":["Within the breathing circuit, in the inspiratory limb (a VIC design)","Downstream of the flowmeter and upstream of the common gas outlet, outside the breathing circuit","On the expiratory limb, so exhaled gas passes back through it","Between the common gas outlet and the reservoir bag, inside the circle"],"answer":1,"explain":"A precision out-of-circuit (VOC) vaporizer sits between the flowmeter and the common gas outlet, outside the breathing circuit, receiving only fresh gas. That position is why it can be precisely compensated. A vaporizer placed IN the circuit (VIC) is a different, non-precision design that the patient's ventilation drives."},{"id":"eq05","domain":"Equipment","q":"Preparing a circle system for a 4.5 kg cat's dental, you close the pop-off, occlude the Y-piece, and pressurize the circuit to 30 cmH2O to perform a low-pressure leak test. For the machine to be considered safe to use, the pressure must hold with a leak rate no greater than approximately:","options":["50 mL/min - the circuit must be essentially airtight","100-300 mL/min","500-750 mL/min","1 L/min, as long as fresh gas flow exceeds it"],"answer":1,"explain":"An acceptable low-pressure leak test holds pressure with a leak under roughly 100-300 mL/min. The circuit need not be perfectly airtight (<50 mL/min is unrealistic), but leaks of 500 mL/min or more make gas/anesthetic delivery unreliable and increase waste-gas pollution and must be corrected before use."},{"id":"eq06","domain":"Equipment","q":"A pop-off valve left closed during spontaneous ventilation is rapidly life-threatening. Which sequence correctly describes the most serious IMMEDIATE consequence?","options":["Rising airway pressure impedes venous return, dropping cardiac output toward collapse, with risk of pulmonary barotrauma","Rising intrathoracic pressure augments venous return, causing hypertension and reflex bradycardia","CO2 trapped behind the closed valve makes hypercapnia the primary immediate threat","Dilution of anesthetic gas lightens the plane, risking intraoperative awareness"],"answer":0,"explain":"A closed pop-off lets circuit and airway pressure climb rapidly. High intrathoracic pressure IMPEDES venous return, dropping cardiac output toward collapse, and can rupture alveoli (barotrauma/pneumothorax). It does not augment venous return or cause hypertension; hypercapnia and a light plane are not the immediate killers here."},{"id":"mon01","domain":"Monitoring","q":"During recovery, a 20 kg dog breathing room air has an SpO2 that reads a steady 90%. Using the oxyhemoglobin dissociation curve, what is the approximate PaO2, and why does this value matter clinically?","options":["~100 mmHg; normal, no concern","~80 mmHg; mild, monitor only","~60 mmHg; the threshold of hypoxemia, where further small saturation drops now reflect large PaO2 falls","~40 mmHg; severe hypoxemia but acceptable transiently in recovery"],"answer":2,"explain":"On the oxyhemoglobin dissociation curve, SpO2 ~90% corresponds to a PaO2 of roughly 60 mmHg - the threshold of hypoxemia and the steep part of the curve. Below this, small further saturation drops signal large PaO2 falls, so 90% warrants prompt attention rather than reassurance."},{"id":"mon02","domain":"Monitoring","q":"Capnography is said to reflect ventilation, perfusion, and metabolism. Strictly speaking, however, the parameter the capnometer directly measures is:","options":["Arterial CO2 (PaCO2), from which the end-tidal value is derived","The CO2 concentration in expired gas, reported as end-tidal CO2","Arterial oxygen tension, via infrared absorption","The alveolar-to-arterial CO2 gradient"],"answer":1,"explain":"The capnometer directly measures the CO2 concentration in expired gas, displayed as end-tidal CO2. PaCO2 is estimated from ETCO2 (normally sitting slightly above it) but is not measured by the device, and the a-A CO2 gradient is calculated, not measured. Oxygen tension is not measured by capnography at all."},{"id":"mon03","domain":"Monitoring","q":"Immediately after intubating a 25 kg dog and connecting the circuit, you deliver several manual breaths but the capnograph stays flat at zero, and auscultation reveals gurgling over the stomach. The most likely explanation is:","options":["Normal - capnography takes several minutes to begin registering after intubation","Esophageal intubation - no CO2 is reaching the sensor","Exhausted CO2 absorbent, which has made the waveform disappear","A low plateau from mild hyperventilation"],"answer":1,"explain":"A capnograph flat at zero after intubation means no CO2 is reaching the sensor; gurgling over the stomach points to esophageal placement. Capnography registers within the first breaths, not minutes; exhausted absorbent raises the baseline rather than flattening the trace; and this is far too low to be mere hyperventilation."},{"id":"mon04","domain":"Monitoring","q":"When using Doppler sphygmomanometry in cats, the value obtained at the first audible return of flow is best interpreted as:","options":["True diastolic pressure","Systolic pressure, though in cats it often underestimates true systolic and may approximate mean arterial pressure","Mean arterial pressure exactly, identically in dogs and cats","Central venous pressure, since the probe detects venous flow"],"answer":1,"explain":"The Doppler value is read as systolic pressure, but in cats it tends to underestimate true systolic and often correlates better with mean arterial pressure. It is not diastolic, not mean exactly, and not a venous measurement. Its strength is a continuous audible pulse signal in small or hypotensive patients."},{"id":"mon05","domain":"Monitoring","q":"While monitoring an anesthetized dog's ECG you note wide, bizarre complexes that are not preceded by P waves. Explaining the finding to a student, you note that the QRS complex normally represents which electrical event - the one occurring abnormally here?","options":["Atrial depolarization","Ventricular depolarization","Ventricular repolarization","Atrial repolarization"],"answer":1,"explain":"The QRS complex represents ventricular depolarization; the wide, bizarre, P-less complexes here are abnormal (ectopic) ventricular depolarizations. The P wave is atrial depolarization and the T wave is ventricular repolarization - the tempting near-miss - while atrial repolarization is usually buried within the QRS."},{"id":"mon06","domain":"Monitoring","q":"An arrhythmia is defined by a premature, wide and bizarre QRS complex that is not preceded by a related P wave and is often followed by a compensatory pause. This description is specific for:","options":["An atrial premature complex, its ectopic P wave simply hidden in the preceding T wave","A ventricular premature complex","First-degree AV block","Sinus arrhythmia"],"answer":1,"explain":"A premature, wide, bizarre QRS with no preceding related P wave (often with a compensatory pause) is a ventricular premature complex, arising from an ectopic ventricular focus. An atrial premature complex is premature but conducts through the normal pathway, so its QRS is narrow; first-degree AV block and sinus arrhythmia have normal QRS morphology."},{"id":"pn01","domain":"Pain Management","q":"A 6-year-old, 28-kg Labrador (ASA II) is scheduled for a TPLO. You plan a hydromorphone premedication, a combined femoral-sciatic nerve block, and carprofen once normal perfusion is confirmed. Which statement best explains why this plan exemplifies multimodal analgesia?","options":["It layers three agents so the opioid dose can be escalated safely if she remains painful","It interrupts nociception at several different points along the pain pathway using drugs of differing mechanisms","It combines agents from a single drug class to concentrate their effect at one site in the pathway","It adds a sedative so that a lighter inhalant plane can supply the analgesia"],"answer":1,"explain":"Multimodal (balanced) analgesia combines drugs from different classes acting at different points of the nociceptive pathway - here an opioid (central), a local block (transmission), and an NSAID (peripheral inflammation). Targeting multiple sites improves efficacy while lowering each drug's dose and side effects; it is not about escalating a single drug or stacking same-class agents at one site."},{"id":"pn02","domain":"Pain Management","q":"Central sensitization ('wind-up') is driven largely by NMDA-receptor activation in the dorsal horn during sustained nociceptive input. Which approach most effectively prevents its establishment?","options":["Delivering multimodal analgesia before tissue trauma begins","Waiting until hyperalgesia is evident, then administering an NMDA antagonist","Giving a single high-dose opioid bolus as surgery concludes","Titrating the vaporizer upward each time nociceptive movement occurs"],"answer":0,"explain":"Wind-up is amplification of dorsal-horn signaling from repeated noxious input. Pre-emptive analgesia - treating BEFORE the stimulus - blunts NMDA-mediated central sensitization and lowers overall analgesic requirements. An NMDA antagonist given only after hyperalgesia develops is too late, a single late opioid bolus does not prevent sensitization, and inhalants provide little analgesia."},{"id":"pn03","domain":"Pain Management","q":"A 30-kg dog is anesthetized for repair of blunt-trauma wounds. It remains 8% dehydrated with a MAP of 54 mmHg despite fluid resuscitation and is clearly painful. Which analgesic choice carries the greatest risk of acute kidney injury if given now?","options":["Methadone IV","A lidocaine line block infiltrated at the wound","A sub-anesthetic ketamine CRI","Carprofen SC"],"answer":3,"explain":"During hypovolemia and hypotension, renal perfusion becomes dependent on prostaglandin-mediated afferent vasodilation. NSAIDs such as carprofen inhibit those prostaglandins and can precipitate acute kidney injury in a hypoperfused patient, so they are withheld until perfusion is restored. Opioids, a local block, and ketamine do not share this renal-perfusion risk."},{"id":"pn04","domain":"Pain Management","q":"Which instrument is a validated tool specifically for assessing ACUTE pain in dogs?","options":["Canine Brief Pain Inventory (CBPI)","Glasgow Composite Measure Pain Scale - Short Form (CMPS-SF)","Helsinki Chronic Pain Index (HCPI)","ASA physical status classification"],"answer":1,"explain":"The Glasgow Composite Measure Pain Scale - Short Form is validated for acute pain in dogs and provides an intervention threshold to guide analgesia. The CBPI and Helsinki Chronic Pain Index are validated but for CHRONIC pain (e.g., osteoarthritis), and the ASA scale grades anesthetic risk, not pain."},{"id":"loc01","domain":"Local/Regional","q":"A 5-year-old dog is under general anesthesia for extraction of a fractured right maxillary canine (tooth 104). Which regional block will most appropriately desensitize the surgical site?","options":["Mental block","Inferior alveolar (mandibular) block","Infraorbital block","Auriculotemporal block"],"answer":2,"explain":"The infraorbital block anesthetizes the maxillary teeth rostral to the infraorbital foramen - the incisors and canine - so it covers the upper canine. The mental and inferior alveolar blocks serve the mandibular (lower) arcade, and the auriculotemporal block targets the ear, not the teeth."},{"id":"loc02","domain":"Local/Regional","q":"Bupivacaine has a markedly longer duration of action than lidocaine. Which physicochemical property is most responsible for this difference?","options":["Its high degree of protein binding","Its greater lipid solubility","Its higher pKa","Its rapid hydrolysis by plasma cholinesterases"],"answer":0,"explain":"Duration of action of a local anesthetic correlates chiefly with protein binding; bupivacaine is roughly 95% protein-bound, giving 4-6+ hours versus lidocaine's 1-2. Lipid solubility governs potency, pKa governs speed of onset, and plasma-cholinesterase hydrolysis applies to ester agents (bupivacaine is an amide) - none of these is the primary determinant of duration."},{"id":"loc03","domain":"Local/Regional","q":"While placing an intercostal block you aspirate before injecting bupivacaine and see a flash of blood in the hub. A student asks why bupivacaine, more than lidocaine, must never enter a vessel. The best answer is that bupivacaine:","options":["Is an ester that provokes anaphylaxis on intravascular exposure","Is destroyed by plasma esterases when given IV, so the block simply fails","Binds cardiac sodium channels avidly and releases them slowly, causing refractory ventricular arrhythmias","Blocks cardiac potassium channels, prolonging the QT interval without arrhythmia risk"],"answer":2,"explain":"Bupivacaine binds cardiac sodium channels avidly and dissociates slowly ('fast-in, slow-out'), so inadvertent IV injection can cause severe, refractory ventricular arrhythmias and cardiac arrest - the reason you aspirate and reposition on a positive aspirate. It is an amide (not an ester), it is not inactivated by plasma esterases, and its danger is sodium- not potassium-channel mediated."},{"id":"loc04","domain":"Local/Regional","q":"The stifle receives sensory innervation from branches of both the femoral and the sciatic nerves. Which single regional plan provides the most complete intraoperative analgesia for a TPLO?","options":["Femoral nerve block alone","Combined femoral and sciatic nerve blocks","Sciatic nerve block alone","Brachial plexus block"],"answer":1,"explain":"Because the stifle is innervated by both the femoral (via the saphenous, medially) and the sciatic nerves, blocking only one leaves part of the joint sensate. Combining femoral and sciatic blocks covers the whole stifle. A brachial plexus block anesthetizes the thoracic limb and is irrelevant here."},{"id":"loc05","domain":"Local/Regional","q":"Minutes after a large-volume bupivacaine infiltration in a 4-kg cat, the patient develops muscle twitching that progresses to a generalized seizure; the heart rhythm remains normal at this point. Which statement best explains this presentation?","options":["Cardiovascular collapse always precedes the neurologic signs of local anesthetic toxicity","In local anesthetic systemic toxicity, CNS excitation (twitching, seizures) typically appears before cardiovascular toxicity","These are cholinergic signs produced by the block itself, unrelated to systemic absorption","This is an anaphylactic reaction to an amide local anesthetic"],"answer":1,"explain":"Local anesthetic systemic toxicity (LAST) usually manifests in the CNS first - muscle twitching, tremors, and seizures - before cardiovascular collapse, and cats are especially susceptible, making dose miscalculation dangerous. Severe cases (particularly bupivacaine) are treated with IV lipid emulsion. The signs are neither cholinergic nor anaphylactic, and the cardiac stage generally follows rather than precedes the CNS stage."},{"id":"er01","domain":"Emergency/CPR","q":"A 28 kg Labrador arrests during a splenectomy. You begin external chest compressions in lateral recumbency and want to maximize coronary and cerebral perfusion. Per RECOVER, what compression rate should you target?","options":["80-100 compressions per minute","100-120 compressions per minute — the same target used for both dogs and cats","120-140 compressions per minute, faster for larger dogs to boost output","A rate matched to the dog's normal resting heart rate of about 70-90/min"],"answer":1,"explain":"RECOVER recommends 100-120 compressions/min for dogs and cats regardless of body size, compressing one-third to one-half the chest width with full recoil and minimal interruptions. Going faster (120-140) shortens diastolic filling and reduces output; matching the patient's normal heart rate under-doses the rate."},{"id":"er02","domain":"Emergency/CPR","q":"A dog in asystole is receiving high-quality CPR. Which drug and dose is the recommended first-line vasopressor, repeated no more often than every other BLS cycle?","options":["Atropine 0.04 mg/kg IV as the sole first agent","Low-dose epinephrine 0.01 mg/kg IV, repeated no more often than every other BLS cycle","High-dose epinephrine 0.1 mg/kg IV as the routine first choice","Vasopressin 0.8 U/kg IV used in place of epinephrine as the first-line agent"],"answer":1,"explain":"Low-dose epinephrine (0.01 mg/kg IV) every other 2-minute BLS cycle is the first-line vasopressor for asystole/PEA. High-dose epinephrine (0.1 mg/kg) is reserved for prolonged, refractory CPR. Atropine is an adjunct (added for vagally mediated arrest), not the sole first agent, and vasopressin is an alternative to — not the recommended replacement for — epinephrine."},{"id":"er03","domain":"Emergency/CPR","q":"A 5 kg cat is intubated and receiving CPR. Your assistant is delivering manual breaths at about 30/min. Per RECOVER, you should adjust the ventilation rate to approximately:","options":["6 breaths per minute (one every 10 seconds)","20 breaths per minute, paused and synchronized two-to-one with compressions","10 breaths per minute (one every 6 seconds)","Continue at 30 breaths per minute to maximize oxygen delivery"],"answer":2,"explain":"In an intubated patient, RECOVER recommends ~10 breaths/min (one every 6 seconds), delivered without interrupting compressions. Hyperventilation (20-30/min) raises intrathoracic pressure, which reduces venous return and coronary perfusion — it does not improve oxygen delivery. 6/min under-ventilates."},{"id":"er04","domain":"Emergency/CPR","q":"During closed-chest CPR of an intubated dog, the ETCO2 abruptly climbs from 12 to 38 mmHg with no change in the ventilation rate. The most likely explanation is:","options":["Compressor fatigue has reduced cardiac output","Improved ventilation is washing out CO2 despite the unchanged breath rate","A sudden rise in pulmonary blood flow, frequently the earliest sign of return of spontaneous circulation","The endotracheal tube has slipped into the esophagus"],"answer":2,"explain":"During CPR, ETCO2 is flow-dependent: it reflects pulmonary blood flow generated by compressions, not the ventilation rate. An abrupt rise (with ventilation unchanged) signals a marked increase in perfusion and is often the first sign of ROSC. Fatigue or esophageal intubation would cause ETCO2 to fall, not rise."},{"id":"calc01","domain":"Calculations","q":"A 44-lb healthy mixed-breed dog is premedicated with hydromorphone at 0.1 mg/kg IM. The vial on your tray reads 2 mg/mL. What volume do you draw up?","options":["0.5 mL","1.0 mL","2.2 mL","4.0 mL"],"answer":1,"explain":"First convert weight: 44 lb ÷ 2.2 = 20 kg. Dose = 20 kg × 0.1 mg/kg = 2 mg. Volume = 2 mg ÷ 2 mg/mL = 1.0 mL. Traps: 2.2 mL comes from dosing 44 as if it were kilograms; 4.0 mL from multiplying by the concentration instead of dividing; 0.5 mL from dividing by the wrong concentration. Always convert lb→kg before a controlled-drug calculation."},{"id":"calc02","domain":"Calculations","q":"A 22-lb dog is maintained on a fentanyl CRI at 5 mcg/kg/hr. How many micrograms are delivered per hour?","options":["5 mcg/hr","50 mcg/hr","110 mcg/hr","500 mcg/hr"],"answer":1,"explain":"Convert first: 22 lb ÷ 2.2 = 10 kg. Delivery = 5 mcg/kg/hr × 10 kg = 50 mcg/hr. The 110 mcg/hr trap comes from treating 22 lb as 22 kg; 5 and 500 are ten-fold decimal slips. Confirm whether the CRI is dosed per hour or per minute before programming the pump."},{"id":"calc03","domain":"Calculations","q":"A 55-lb Boxer under isoflurane develops sustained ventricular tachycardia. You prepare a lidocaine bolus at 2 mg/kg IV. What is the bolus dose in milligrams?","options":["25 mg","50 mg","100 mg","110 mg"],"answer":1,"explain":"Convert: 55 lb ÷ 2.2 = 25 kg. Dose = 25 kg × 2 mg/kg = 50 mg. The 110 mg trap treats 55 lb as 55 kg; 25 mg uses half the dose (1 mg/kg) and 100 mg doubles it. Lidocaine is first-line for ventricular arrhythmias in dogs; use with extreme caution or avoid in cats due to toxicity."},{"id":"calc04","domain":"Calculations","q":"For a healthy adult dog under inhalant anesthesia, which intraoperative crystalloid rate best reflects current conservative recommendations (moving away from older, higher rates)?","options":["1-2 mL/kg/hr","3-5 mL/kg/hr (with newer recommendations trending even lower)","5-10 mL/kg/hr","10-20 mL/kg/hr"],"answer":1,"explain":"Current AAHA/ACVAA-aligned guidance favors conservative intraoperative crystalloid rates around 3-5 mL/kg/hr in dogs (≈3 in cats), with a trend toward even lower rates to avoid volume overload. The 5-10 mL/kg/hr option is the older traditional anesthetic rate (the tempting near-twin); 10-20 mL/kg/hr is a replacement/bolus range; 1-2 mL/kg/hr is closer to true maintenance and is too low for the anesthetic standard. Rates are always titrated to blood pressure and losses."},{"id":"sp01","domain":"Species-Specific","q":"A 4-year-old, 14-kg English Bulldog is recovering from mandibular dental extractions. He is still lightly sedate with SpO2 96% on flow-by oxygen, and the technician is deciding when to remove the endotracheal tube. Compared with a mesaticephalic dog, which factor represents this patient's single greatest recovery-phase risk?","options":["Lower airway obstruction from dynamic bronchial collapse during expiration","Upper airway obstruction from stenotic nares, an elongated soft palate, and everted laryngeal saccules","Prolonged recovery due to slow redistribution of injectable induction agents","Rapid core heat loss from a high surface-area-to-mass ratio"],"answer":1,"explain":"Brachycephalic patients have stenotic nares, an elongated soft palate, and everted laryngeal saccules that predispose them to dynamic UPPER airway obstruction, which is greatest as sedation blunts airway tone during recovery. Keep them intubated as long as tolerated, extubate late, and monitor closely with oxygen available. Bronchial (lower airway) collapse is not the dominant issue here, and redistribution or heat loss are not the characteristic brachycephalic recovery hazard."},{"id":"sp02","domain":"Species-Specific","q":"During feline intubation the arytenoids are seen closing tightly with each attempt. This heightened tendency in cats (relative to dogs) is best explained and managed by which statement?","options":["Reflex laryngospasm from a sensitive larynx; apply topical lidocaine to the arytenoids and time tube passage to inspiration","Reflex bronchospasm from sensitive lower airways; give an inhaled bronchodilator before advancing the tube","Mechanical laryngeal collapse from weak cartilage; use a smaller tube with a rigid stylet","Vagally mediated apnea; deepen anesthesia and force the tube past the closed glottis"],"answer":0,"explain":"Cats have a highly sensitive larynx prone to reflex laryngospasm (active glottic closure) during intubation, far more so than dogs. Desensitize the arytenoids with a drop/spray of lidocaine, let it take effect, visualize the glottis, and pass the tube gently as the glottis opens on inspiration. The problem is not bronchospasm or cartilage collapse, and forcing a tube through a closed glottis causes trauma and worsens spasm."},{"id":"sp03","domain":"Species-Specific","q":"A 3-week-old, 0.6-kg kitten is anesthetized to repair a congenital defect after a 6-hour fast. Forty minutes in, it becomes bradycardic and weak. Which underlying physiologic feature best explains its vulnerability to the most likely metabolic derangement?","options":["Exaggerated insulin release from an immature, hyperactive pancreas","Reduced intestinal glucose absorption limiting enteral uptake","Limited hepatic glycogen reserves combined with a high metabolic rate","Limited hepatic glycogen reserves combined with a low metabolic rate"],"answer":2,"explain":"Neonates have minimal hepatic glycogen stores yet a high metabolic (and glucose) demand, so even a few hours of fasting cause hypoglycemia, here manifesting as bradycardia and weakness. Minimize fasting, monitor blood glucose, and supplement dextrose as needed. A LOW metabolic rate would be protective (wrong), the pancreas is not hypersecreting insulin, and impaired absorption is not the driver during anesthesia."},{"id":"cx01","domain":"Complications","q":"A 4-year-old cat on 3% isoflurane for a dental has a Doppler systolic pressure of 65 mmHg. The jaw is fully relaxed with no reflexes, and there has been no hemorrhage. The most likely mechanism of this hypotension is:","options":["Inhalant-induced vasoconstriction with increased myocardial contractility","Inhalant-induced vasodilation and myocardial depression from an excessively deep plane","Hypovolemia from inadequate intravenous fluid administration","Peripheral vasoconstriction caused by early hypothermia"],"answer":1,"explain":"Volatile inhalants cause dose-dependent vasodilation and myocardial depression; an excessively deep plane (signs of over-depth plus a high vaporizer setting) is the most common cause of anesthetic hypotension. The first corrective step is to lighten depth (lower the vaporizer). Inhalants do not cause vasoconstriction/increased contractility, and there is no evidence here for hypovolemia or hypothermia as the driver."},{"id":"cx02","domain":"Complications","q":"Which hemodynamic consequence is most characteristic of intermittent positive-pressure ventilation, particularly in a hypovolemic patient?","options":["Reduced cardiac output, because positive pressure directly depresses the myocardium","Increased cardiac output, because higher mean airway pressure improves oxygen delivery","Increased venous return, as lung inflation squeezes blood toward the heart","Reduced cardiac output, because raised intrathoracic pressure decreases venous return"],"answer":3,"explain":"IPPV raises intrathoracic pressure, which lowers the pressure gradient for venous return (preload), reducing cardiac output and blood pressure — pronounced in hypovolemic patients. The mechanism is decreased venous return, not direct myocardial depression, so use the lowest effective airway pressure. Spontaneous (negative-pressure) breathing, not IPPV, augments venous return."},{"id":"cx03","domain":"Complications","q":"An anesthetized pig undergoing an experimental procedure develops rapidly rising ETCO2, hyperthermia, and generalized muscle rigidity. Which combination of agents most classically triggers this hypermetabolic crisis?","options":["Propofol combined with an opioid","A volatile inhalant together with a nondepolarizing blocker such as rocuronium","A volatile inhalant together with succinylcholine","A benzodiazepine combined with ketamine"],"answer":2,"explain":"Malignant hyperthermia is a hypermetabolic crisis (classic in susceptible pigs) triggered by volatile inhalants and the depolarizing neuromuscular blocker succinylcholine, producing rising ETCO2, hyperthermia, and rigidity; dantrolene is the treatment. Nondepolarizing blockers (rocuronium) do not trigger MH — the near-twin distractor — and propofol, opioids, benzodiazepines, and ketamine are non-triggering."},{"id":"cx04","domain":"Complications","q":"A dog on a dexmedetomidine CRI becomes progressively bradycardic while maintaining an adequate arterial blood pressure. Why is giving atropine as the first response potentially harmful?","options":["It reverses the sedation and analgesia of dexmedetomidine, causing abrupt arousal","It can provoke a hypertensive surge and sharply raise myocardial oxygen demand by driving the heart rate up against the alpha-2-induced high vascular resistance","It potentiates the alpha-2 agonist and deepens the bradycardia","It has no cardiovascular effect because dexmedetomidine blocks muscarinic receptors"],"answer":1,"explain":"Alpha-2 agonist bradycardia is a baroreflex response to drug-induced vasoconstriction. Adding an anticholinergic increases heart rate while afterload remains high, which can precipitate marked hypertension and greatly increase myocardial oxygen demand. The correct first step is to reduce or stop the alpha-2 and reassess. Atropine does not reverse alpha-2 sedation (that is atipamezole), does not potentiate the alpha-2, and dexmedetomidine does not block muscarinic receptors."},{"id":"vf01","domain":"Ventilation/Fluids","q":"You are manually ventilating a healthy 20-kg dog with normal lungs under isoflurane. To provide an adequate tidal volume while minimizing barotrauma, what peak inspiratory pressure should you generally aim NOT to exceed on the manometer?","options":["About 2-5 cmH2O","About 30-40 cmH2O","About 20-25 cmH2O","About 10-15 cmH2O (up to ~20)"],"answer":3,"explain":"Healthy small-animal lungs are ventilated to a peak inspiratory pressure of roughly 10-15 cmH2O (some allow up to ~20). Sustained pressures above ~20-30 risk barotrauma/volutrauma. A brief higher pressure may be used for a deliberate recruitment maneuver, but as a routine ceiling 10-15 cmH2O is correct; 20-25 is already the caution zone and 30-40 is frankly hazardous for normal lungs."},{"id":"vf02","domain":"Ventilation/Fluids","q":"Regarding the distribution and clinical role of 5% dextrose in water (D5W), which statement is correct?","options":["Because it is initially iso-osmolar to plasma, it behaves as a durable intravascular volume expander","After the dextrose is metabolized it effectively delivers free water, so little remains intravascular, making it unsuitable for resuscitation","Its dextrose content provides meaningful caloric support sufficient to meet resting energy requirements","It is a hypertonic crystalloid that draws interstitial water into the vasculature"],"answer":1,"explain":"D5W is iso-osmolar in the bag only because of the dextrose; once that dextrose is metabolized, what remains is free water that distributes across all body compartments, leaving almost nothing in the vasculature. It is therefore a free-water/maintenance-type fluid (for free-water deficits or as a drug vehicle), NOT a resuscitation fluid. Its caloric content is trivial (~170 kcal/L, far below RER), and it is not hypertonic."},{"id":"vf03","domain":"Ventilation/Fluids","q":"A 25-kg dog in hemorrhagic shock has received two 20-mL/kg balanced-crystalloid boluses but remains hypotensive with poor perfusion. You want an agent that stays intravascular longer to sustain plasma volume. Which product is a SYNTHETIC colloid appropriate for that goal?","options":["Lactated Ringer's solution","0.9% sodium chloride","Hydroxyethyl starch (hetastarch)","Fresh frozen plasma"],"answer":2,"explain":"Hydroxyethyl starch (hetastarch) is a SYNTHETIC colloid whose large molecules remain intravascular longer, expanding plasma volume for a given volume infused. Fresh frozen plasma is also a colloid but a NATURAL one (and an inefficient, costly volume expander); LRS and 0.9% NaCl are crystalloids. Note hetastarch carries coagulation and acute-kidney-injury concerns, so it is used judiciously."},{"id":"vf04","domain":"Ventilation/Fluids","q":"A normothermic dog is defending its body temperature in a cold environment. Which of the following is NOT one of the dog's normal heat-production or heat-conservation mechanisms?","options":["Non-shivering (metabolic) thermogenesis","Cutaneous vasoconstriction to reduce peripheral heat loss","Shivering thermogenesis","Evaporative cooling through generalized cutaneous sweating"],"answer":3,"explain":"Dogs generate and conserve heat via shivering thermogenesis, non-shivering (metabolic) thermogenesis, peripheral vasoconstriction, and behavioral warmth-seeking. They do NOT thermoregulate by generalized cutaneous sweating; their few functional sweat glands (footpads) are negligible, and evaporative heat LOSS is achieved by panting, not sweating. Generalized sweating is the outlier and, in any case, is a cooling mechanism, not heat production/conservation."},{"id":"adv01","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"You run a fentanyl CRI for 6 hours and note recovery is far slower than after a 30-minute infusion. The parameter that captures this dependence of offset on infusion duration is the context-sensitive half-time, defined as:","options":["The time for plasma concentration to fall 50% after a single bolus, independent of infusion duration","The terminal elimination half-life measured at steady state","The time from stopping the infusion to peak analgesic effect","The time for plasma concentration to decline by 50% after stopping an infusion of a specified duration"],"answer":3,"explain":"Context-sensitive half-time is the time for plasma concentration to fall by 50% after stopping an infusion, and it depends on how long the infusion ran. Fentanyl accumulates in peripheral tissues, so its context-sensitive half-time lengthens with duration; remifentanil's stays nearly constant because of esterase metabolism."},{"id":"adv02","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"In a dog with severe combined hepatic and renal dysfunction, which opioid CRI offers an offset essentially independent of organ function and of infusion duration because it is cleared by nonspecific plasma and tissue esterases?","options":["Fentanyl","Morphine","Remifentanil","Methadone"],"answer":2,"explain":"Remifentanil is metabolized by nonspecific plasma and tissue esterases, so its clearance is independent of hepatic and renal function and its context-sensitive half-time stays very short regardless of infusion length. Fentanyl accumulates with prolonged infusion, and morphine and methadone depend on hepatic (and for morphine, renal) handling."},{"id":"adv03","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"A dog undergoing ovariohysterectomy receives maropitant. Beyond preventing perioperative vomiting, which additional benefit is attributed to its NK-1 (substance P) antagonism?","options":["Profound sedation reducing premedication requirements","Prokinetic gastric emptying via 5-HT4 receptor agonism","Visceral analgesia via NK-1 receptor agonism","Visceral antinociception with a possible modest reduction in inhalant requirement"],"answer":3,"explain":"By antagonizing NK-1 (substance P) receptors, maropitant provides visceral antinociception and may modestly reduce inhalant requirement during visceral surgery, in addition to its antiemetic effect. It works by NK-1 antagonism (not agonism), is not a sedative, and is not a 5-HT4 prokinetic like metoclopramide or cisapride."},{"id":"adv04","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"Which agent is a non-depolarizing (competitive) neuromuscular blocker whose blockade can be antagonized by an acetylcholinesterase inhibitor such as neostigmine?","options":["Succinylcholine","Atracurium","Guaifenesin","Dantrolene"],"answer":1,"explain":"Atracurium competitively blocks the nicotinic ACh receptor; neostigmine (given with an anticholinergic) raises synaptic acetylcholine to reverse it. Succinylcholine is a depolarizing blocker and is not reversed this way. Guaifenesin is a central-acting muscle relaxant, and dantrolene acts on the ryanodine receptor for malignant hyperthermia."},{"id":"adv05","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"A dog receiving atracurium for intraocular surgery is mechanically ventilated. Why is a peripheral nerve stimulator, combined with heightened vigilance for anesthetic depth, essential in this patient?","options":["The drug provides profound analgesia that must be objectively titrated with the stimulator","The drug lowers the inhalant requirement, creating a risk of relative overdose","The drug paralyzes but provides no anesthesia or analgesia, so movement can no longer signal a light plane, risking awareness","The drug can trigger malignant hyperthermia that the nerve stimulator detects"],"answer":2,"explain":"Neuromuscular blockers paralyze without any anesthesia or analgesia, so a patient cannot move to warn of an inadequate plane, creating a risk of awareness under paralysis. Depth must be ensured by other monitors, and the degree of blockade quantified by train-of-four. NMBAs do not provide analgesia, alter MAC, or let a stimulator diagnose malignant hyperthermia."},{"id":"adv06","domain":"Monitoring","q":"A hypotensive 8-year-old dog under anesthesia suddenly shows ETCO2 fall from 40 to 22 mmHg, yet an arterial blood gas drawn at the same moment shows PaCO2 of 46 mmHg. This widened ETCO2-to-PaCO2 gradient is best explained by:","options":["Alveolar hyperventilation blowing off CO2","Increased alveolar dead space - lung units ventilated but poorly perfused, as in low cardiac output or pulmonary thromboembolism","Increased CO2 production from a hypermetabolic state","Improved pulmonary perfusion after a fluid bolus"],"answer":1,"explain":"ETCO2 normally sits just below PaCO2. A low ETCO2 with a normal-to-high PaCO2 (a widened gradient) reflects increased alveolar dead space - lung ventilated but not perfused - as in low cardiac output, hypotension, or pulmonary thromboembolism. Hyperventilation would lower PaCO2 too; increased CO2 production or improved perfusion would not widen the gap."},{"id":"adv07","domain":"Monitoring","q":"A standard two-wavelength pulse oximeter can read a falsely NORMAL (high) SpO2 despite dangerously reduced oxygen-carrying capacity in which situation?","options":["Methemoglobinemia, which drives the reading toward ~85% regardless of true saturation","Carbon monoxide toxicity, because carboxyhemoglobin is read much like oxyhemoglobin","Hypothermic peripheral vasoconstriction, which prevents any reliable reading","Intravenous methylene blue, which transiently lowers the displayed SpO2"],"answer":1,"explain":"Standard two-wavelength oximeters read carboxyhemoglobin much like oxyhemoglobin, giving a falsely high SpO2 in CO toxicity; co-oximetry is required. Methemoglobinemia instead drives the reading toward ~85%, methylene blue causes transiently LOW readings, and hypothermic vasoconstriction yields a poor or absent signal - none of which is a falsely reassuring high value."},{"id":"adv08","domain":"Equipment","q":"You are setting up a machine that will run off a reserve oxygen E-cylinder because the room has no pipeline supply, and you want to estimate the volume remaining from the pressure gauge. A full oxygen E-cylinder reads approximately:","options":["~500 psi","~1100 psi","~2000-2200 psi","~5000 psi"],"answer":2,"explain":"A full oxygen E-cylinder reads about 2000-2200 psi. Oxygen is a compressed gas, so pressure falls linearly with volume remaining - a gauge near 1100 psi means roughly half remains. (Nitrous oxide, stored as a liquid, holds a near-constant pressure until nearly empty, so its gauge does not track volume.)"},{"id":"adv09","domain":"Equipment","q":"An anesthesia machine has two gas-specific safety systems. The Pin Index Safety System (PISS) specifically functions to:","options":["Prevent attaching a small cylinder to the wrong hanger yoke on the machine","Prevent connecting the wrong hose to a wall pipeline outlet (that is the DISS)","Regulate the flow rate of gas leaving the cylinder","Reduce high cylinder pressure to a usable working pressure"],"answer":0,"explain":"The Pin Index Safety System uses a gas-specific pin/hole arrangement so a small cylinder physically attaches only to its correct hanger yoke, preventing gas mix-ups. The analogous system for pipeline hoses and wall outlets is the Diameter Index Safety System (DISS). Flow is set by the flowmeter and pressure reduction is done by the regulator."},{"id":"adv10","domain":"Physiology","q":"In the capillaries of vigorously contracting skeletal muscle, local CO2 is high and pH is low. By the Bohr effect, how does this microenvironment affect hemoglobin arriving there?","options":["It raises hemoglobin's affinity for oxygen, so O2 is retained until systemic pH is restored","It increases hemoglobin's affinity for carbon dioxide — the mechanism by which deoxyhemoglobin loads CO2","It shifts the dissociation curve leftward, sparing oxygen for return to the lungs","It lowers hemoglobin's affinity for oxygen, enhancing O2 unloading exactly where demand is greatest"],"answer":3,"explain":"The Bohr effect: in acidic, high-CO2 tissue such as exercising muscle, hemoglobin's oxygen affinity falls (a rightward curve shift), promoting oxygen release where demand is highest. Option 2 describes the Haldane effect (deoxyhemoglobin's enhanced CO2 carriage) — a real but different phenomenon that does not answer how O2 affinity changes. A leftward shift/increased affinity is the opposite of the Bohr effect."},{"id":"adv11","domain":"Physiology","q":"General anesthesia and dorsal recumbency reduce functional residual capacity below closing capacity in the dependent lung. What is the direct consequence, and how does it impair oxygenation?","options":["Atelectasis and small-airway closure create low-V/Q units and shunt, causing hypoxemia","Small-airway closure enlarges alveolar dead space, producing high-V/Q units and hypercapnia","Alveolar recruitment raises lung compliance, improving both oxygenation and ventilation","Atelectasis raises the alveolar oxygen reservoir, improving oxygenation despite the low FRC"],"answer":0,"explain":"When FRC falls below closing capacity, dependent airways close and alveoli collapse (atelectasis). These perfused-but-unventilated units are low-V/Q and behave as right-to-left shunt — the dominant cause of intra-anesthetic hypoxemia. This is a shunt problem, not dead space (which is high-V/Q and impairs CO2 clearance). A low FRC reduces, never raises, the oxygen reservoir; preoxygenation, recruitment, and PEEP mitigate it."},{"id":"adv12","domain":"Physiology","q":"Before inducing a 5-year-old English Bulldog for airway surgery, you provide 3–5 minutes of mask oxygen. During the subsequent apnea of induction and intubation, what is the principal benefit this maneuver provided?","options":["It raised dissolved plasma oxygen enough to meet whole-body demand during the apnea","It prevented the rise in PaCO2 that occurs during the apneic period","It denitrogenated the FRC, building an alveolar oxygen reservoir that delays desaturation during apnea","It lowered the anesthetic MAC, producing a smoother and faster induction"],"answer":2,"explain":"Preoxygenation replaces nitrogen in the FRC with oxygen, creating an alveolar reservoir that continues oxygenating blood during the apnea of induction/intubation and delays desaturation — especially valuable in brachycephalic patients with difficult airways and reduced FRC. It does not meaningfully raise dissolved plasma oxygen, does not prevent the steady rise in PaCO2 during apnea, and has no effect on MAC."},{"id":"adv13","domain":"Pain Management","q":"A dog with a 2-day-old degloving injury remains painful and now flinches at light touch of the intact skin around the wound (allodynia) despite a fentanyl CRI. Adding a low-dose ketamine CRI is expected to help primarily because ketamine:","options":["Provides additional mu-opioid agonism on top of the fentanyl","Antagonizes NMDA receptors, counteracting the central sensitization that underlies the allodynia","Inhibits cyclooxygenase to reduce peripheral inflammation","Agonizes NMDA receptors to raise the pain threshold"],"answer":1,"explain":"Allodynia here reflects central sensitization (wind-up). Sub-anesthetic ketamine antagonizes NMDA receptors, blunting that sensitization and sparing opioids as part of a multimodal CRI. It is not an opioid agonist, has no COX activity, and is an NMDA antagonist - not an agonist."},{"id":"adv14","domain":"Pain Management","q":"In a canine morphine-lidocaine-ketamine (MLK) CRI, which set of effects is contributed specifically by the LIDOCAINE component?","options":["Systemic analgesia, class-Ib antiarrhythmic activity, and a reduction in inhalant MAC","Systemic analgesia and antiarrhythmic activity, but an INCREASE in inhalant MAC requirement","NMDA-receptor antagonism that prevents wind-up","Profound sedation that lowers the opioid requirement"],"answer":0,"explain":"A lidocaine CRI in dogs provides systemic analgesia, class-Ib antiarrhythmic activity, prokinetic effects, and a reduction in inhalant MAC (it does not raise it). NMDA antagonism is the ketamine component, and lidocaine is not a sedative. Lidocaine CRIs are used cautiously or avoided in cats due to a narrow toxic margin."},{"id":"adv15","domain":"Local/Regional","q":"Maximum local anesthetic doses (mg/kg) are set substantially lower for cats than for dogs. What is the primary reason?","options":["Cats clear amide anesthetics more rapidly, so doses must be cut to prevent accumulation","Cats are inherently more susceptible to local anesthetic systemic toxicity","Cats have a proportionally larger blood volume that elevates peak plasma levels","Cats require higher tissue concentrations per kilogram to achieve conduction blockade"],"answer":1,"explain":"Cats are markedly more sensitive to local anesthetic systemic toxicity, so maximum doses are lower and every source (all blocks plus any CRI) must be summed. Faster clearance would not mandate a lower ceiling, cats do not have a larger blood volume, and needing more drug per kilogram would raise - not lower - the maximum."},{"id":"adv16","domain":"Emergency/CPR","q":"A dog achieves ROSC after 8 minutes of CPR. It remains intubated on 100% oxygen, is normothermic, and has a mean arterial pressure of 70 mmHg. Which post-cardiac-arrest management goal is now most appropriate?","options":["Keep the patient on 100% inspired oxygen indefinitely to maximize PaO2","Titrate inspired oxygen to a normal SpO2/PaO2 and avoid both hyperoxia and hypercapnia while supporting perfusion","Deliberately induce mild hyperthermia to protect the brain","Hyperventilate to hold ETCO2 well below 20 mmHg"],"answer":1,"explain":"Post-ROSC care optimizes oxygenation and ventilation — titrating FiO2 to a normal PaO2/SpO2 to avoid hyperoxic reperfusion injury and avoiding hypercapnia — while supporting blood pressure/perfusion, controlling seizures, and preventing hyperthermia, which worsens neurologic injury. Indefinite 100% oxygen risks hyperoxia; deliberate hyperthermia is harmful; aggressive hyperventilation causes cerebral vasoconstriction."},{"id":"adv17","domain":"Complications","q":"During a prolonged anesthetic, a dog passively regurgitates a large volume of fluid into the pharynx. In addition to suctioning, which action best reduces the risk of esophagitis and later stricture?","options":["Deflate the endotracheal cuff so the fluid can drain past the tube","Place the patient in dorsal recumbency to keep the fluid pooled in the stomach","Stop suctioning and let the patient swallow the fluid","Lavage the esophagus with water and suction it, keeping the cuff inflated and the head lowered"],"answer":3,"explain":"Retained acidic regurgitant causes esophagitis and can lead to stricture. Keep the cuff inflated to protect the airway, suction the pharynx, lower the head to promote outward drainage, and lavage the esophagus with water (then suction) to dilute the acid. Deflating the cuff invites aspiration, dorsal recumbency and allowing the patient to swallow the acid both increase mucosal injury and aspiration risk."},{"id":"adv18","domain":"Complications","q":"A dog is maintained on isoflurane. Which combination of signs most specifically indicates an inadequately LIGHT plane of anesthesia?","options":["A ventromedially rotated globe with markedly reduced jaw tone","A centrally positioned globe with an absent palpebral reflex","Brisk palpebral reflex, increased jaw tone, and spontaneous purposeful movement","Widely dilated, fixed pupils with no reflex response"],"answer":2,"explain":"A light plane shows a brisk palpebral reflex, increased jaw/muscle tone, and spontaneous purposeful movement (often with tearing, nystagmus, and rising HR/RR/BP on stimulation). A ventromedially rotated globe with reduced jaw tone is the classic surgical (medium) plane; a central globe with absent palpebral, or widely dilated fixed pupils, indicate an excessively deep plane. Confirm and rule out hypercapnia before deepening."},{"id":"adv19","domain":"Anesthetic Principles","q":"A 9-year-old cat presents for dental treatment. It has hypertrophic cardiomyopathy that is well controlled on medication; it tires with vigorous play but is comfortable at rest with no signs of decompensation. Which ASA physical status classification best fits this patient?","options":["ASA III","ASA IV","ASA II","ASA V"],"answer":0,"explain":"ASA III is severe systemic disease that limits activity but is not a constant threat to life; this cat's managed HCM with reduced exercise tolerance yet stable rest status fits ASA III. ASA IV is reserved for severe disease that is a constant threat to life (e.g., decompensated/CHF), ASA II is mild disease, and ASA V is moribund. The III-versus-IV distinction hinges on whether the disease is a constant threat to life."},{"id":"adv20","domain":"Anesthetic Principles","q":"ACVAA monitoring guidelines are built around continuously evaluating three core physiologic functions (supplemented by temperature and a dedicated observer). Which trio names those three core functions?","options":["Blood pressure, urine output, and temperature","Circulation, oxygenation, and ventilation","Circulation, oxygenation, and temperature","Heart rate, respiratory rate, and capillary refill time"],"answer":1,"explain":"ACVAA guidelines frame minimum monitoring around three physiologic functions: circulation (pulse quality, blood pressure, ECG), oxygenation (mucous membranes, pulse oximetry), and ventilation (respiratory rate/character, capnography), with temperature and, critically, a dedicated anesthetist as additional pillars. Temperature matters but is NOT one of the three core function categories, so the near-twin that swaps ventilation for temperature is the classic trap."},{"id":"adv21","domain":"Anesthetic Principles","q":"A small practice is debating whether the surgeon can also manage anesthesia during a routine procedure to save labor. From an anesthetic-safety standpoint, what is the primary justification for assigning a dedicated anesthetist who is NOT scrubbed into surgery?","options":["Maintaining an accurate controlled-substance and anesthetic record for compliance","Reducing inhalant consumption by keeping the vaporizer precisely adjusted","Continuous, undistracted patient observation enabling early detection and rapid intervention","Operating the anesthetic machine and gas-scavenging system correctly"],"answer":2,"explain":"The single most important anesthetic-safety factor is a vigilant, dedicated anesthetist continuously watching the patient and monitors so complications are caught and corrected early, which is impossible if that person is also scrubbed in and focused on surgery. Accurate records, inhalant economy, and machine operation are real duties but secondary to uninterrupted vigilance and the ability to intervene immediately."},{"id":"adv22","domain":"Ventilation/Fluids","q":"A 30-kg dog in decompensated shock needs aggressive crystalloid resuscitation, and you recall the classic 'shock dose' approximates one blood volume. Which value best reflects the canine crystalloid shock dose, and how should it be given?","options":["≈50-60 mL/kg, given in titrated fractional boluses while reassessing perfusion","≈80-90 mL/kg, given in titrated fractional boluses (e.g., ¼ dose) while reassessing perfusion","≈20-30 mL/kg as a single rapid bolus with no reassessment","≈10 mL/kg as a slow constant-rate infusion over an hour"],"answer":1,"explain":"A dog's blood volume is ~80-90 mL/kg (cats ~50-60), and the crystalloid shock dose approximates one blood volume. It is not delivered all at once: give it in titrated fractions (commonly ~20 mL/kg quarter-doses) and reassess perfusion (HR, MM, pulse quality, lactate, BP) between boluses to avoid volume overload. 50-60 mL/kg is the feline figure, the classic species mix-up."},{"id":"np01","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"Even after a prolonged CRI, propofol generally permits a relatively smooth, prompt recovery. Which pharmacokinetic feature best accounts for this?","options":["Rapid redistribution but a low total body clearance","Sequestration in fat with slow, sustained release","Rapid redistribution combined with high total body clearance, including extrahepatic metabolism","Slow hepatic metabolism to inactive conjugates"],"answer":2,"explain":"Propofol redistributes rapidly from brain to peripheral tissues AND has high total body clearance (including significant extrahepatic metabolism), so plasma levels fall quickly when the infusion stops. High clearance is the decisive point; rapid redistribution with low clearance would allow accumulation and delayed recovery."},{"id":"np02","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"You need to give a benzodiazepine intramuscularly to a fractious patient and choose midazolam over diazepam. Which property of diazepam's propylene glycol vehicle drives this choice?","options":["It is painful but reliably and predictably absorbed IM, with problems only on rapid IV","It causes massive histamine release and anaphylaxis","It is directly neurotoxic and cannot contact peripheral nerves","It is painful and erratically absorbed after IM injection, and rapid IV can cause cardiovascular effects"],"answer":3,"explain":"Diazepam is formulated in propylene glycol, which is painful and unreliably absorbed when given IM and can cause hypotension or arrhythmias if injected rapidly IV. Midazolam is water-soluble, so it is well absorbed and non-irritating IM. IM diazepam is neither painless nor predictably absorbed."},{"id":"np03","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"Which opioid is most likely to cause clinically significant histamine release, with hypotension and urticaria, if administered as a rapid IV bolus?","options":["Fentanyl","Morphine","Methadone","Hydromorphone"],"answer":1,"explain":"Morphine can trigger histamine release with rapid IV injection, causing hypotension and urticaria; it should be given slowly or by the IM/SC route. Fentanyl, methadone, and hydromorphone cause minimal histamine release and are far less associated with this reaction."},{"id":"np04","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"A dog with osteoarthritis shows disappointing analgesia on oral tramadol despite appropriate dosing. Which pharmacologic fact best explains tramadol's inconsistent opioid efficacy in dogs?","options":["Dogs rapidly clear the active M1 metabolite before it can act","Dogs generate very little of the active M1 (O-desmethyltramadol) metabolite","It is excreted unchanged before any hepatic conversion occurs","Its very high protein binding leaves almost no free drug"],"answer":1,"explain":"Tramadol's opioid effect depends on the M1 metabolite (O-desmethyltramadol), and dogs produce very little of it, so mu-mediated analgesia is minimal and inconsistent; its serotonin/norepinephrine reuptake effects give only modest benefit. The key issue is low M1 PRODUCTION, not rapid clearance or protein binding."},{"id":"np05","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"The reconstituted product 'Telazol' pairs a dissociative anesthetic with a benzodiazepine. Which combination correctly identifies its two components?","options":["Ketamine and midazolam","Ketamine and zolazepam","Tiletamine and zolazepam","Tiletamine and diazepam"],"answer":2,"explain":"Telazol is a 1:1 combination of tiletamine (a dissociative like ketamine) and zolazepam (a benzodiazepine). The dissociative is tiletamine (not ketamine) and the benzodiazepine is zolazepam (not diazepam or midazolam). Recoveries can be rough and vary by species depending on which component outlasts the other."},{"id":"np06","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"An epileptic dog maintained on phenobarbital for two years requires higher-than-expected doses of several injectable anesthetics. The best explanation is that chronic phenobarbital:","options":["Inhibits hepatic microsomal enzymes, slowing drug clearance","Induces hepatic microsomal (cytochrome P450) enzymes, accelerating drug metabolism","Impairs gastrointestinal absorption of injectable drugs","Displaces drugs from plasma proteins, increasing clearance only"],"answer":1,"explain":"Phenobarbital is a potent inducer of hepatic cytochrome P450 enzymes, so chronic use accelerates metabolism of many co-administered drugs and higher or more frequent doses may be required. Enzyme inhibition would have the opposite effect, and GI absorption of injectables is irrelevant."},{"id":"np07","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"Adding preservative-free morphine to a local anesthetic for an epidural provides what principal advantage over the local anesthetic alone?","options":["Prolonged, enhanced analgesia but with markedly increased motor blockade","A faster onset of dense motor blockade","Shortening or reversal of the local anesthetic's sensory effect","Prolonged, enhanced segmental analgesia with minimal additional motor blockade"],"answer":3,"explain":"Epidural opioids act on spinal opioid receptors to give prolonged, enhanced segmental analgesia while largely sparing motor function, complementing the local anesthetic. They do not add substantial motor block, speed dense motor blockade, or shorten the local anesthetic's effect. Preservative-free formulations must be used."},{"id":"np08","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"For a healthy dog, you want the alpha-2 agonist with the highest alpha-2:alpha-1 selectivity to minimize alpha-1-mediated side effects. Which agent do you choose?","options":["Xylazine","Detomidine","Dexmedetomidine","Romifidine"],"answer":2,"explain":"Dexmedetomidine has the highest alpha-2:alpha-1 selectivity ratio (~1620:1), giving more predictable sedation and analgesia with fewer alpha-1-mediated effects. Xylazine is the least selective (~160:1), and detomidine and romifidine fall between, so dexmedetomidine best meets the requirement."},{"id":"np09","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"Gabapentin's perioperative benefit in neuropathic and chronic pain arises from its action at which molecular target?","options":["Voltage-gated sodium channels","The alpha-2-delta subunit of voltage-gated calcium channels","The GABA-B receptor, as an agonist","NMDA receptors, as an antagonist"],"answer":1,"explain":"Gabapentin binds the alpha-2-delta subunit of voltage-gated calcium channels, reducing excitatory neurotransmitter release, which helps neuropathic and chronic pain and adds mild anxiolysis/sedation. Despite its name it does not act on GABA receptors, and it is not a sodium-channel or NMDA drug."},{"id":"np10","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"A dog with severe degenerative mitral valve disease receives a fentanyl bolus at induction. Which cardiovascular response is most expected?","options":["Marked vasodilation and profound hypotension","Minimal direct myocardial depression, with reflex tachycardia","Minimal direct myocardial depression, with a tendency toward vagally-mediated bradycardia","Severe negative inotropy with collapse of cardiac output"],"answer":2,"explain":"Fentanyl provides excellent cardiovascular stability with minimal direct myocardial depression, which is why it is favored in cardiac patients; its main cardiovascular effect is vagally-mediated bradycardia, treatable with an anticholinergic. It does not cause reflex tachycardia, marked vasodilation, or contractile collapse at clinical doses."},{"id":"np11","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"What is the principal reason ketamine is not used as the sole anesthetic agent?","options":["It provides no somatic analgesia whatsoever when used alone","It abolishes protective airway reflexes, which is the reason a co-agent is required","It produces profound, unmanageable respiratory depression at clinical doses","It causes dissociative anesthesia with retained muscle tone and reflexes and rough recoveries, so a co-agent is needed"],"answer":3,"explain":"Ketamine produces dissociative anesthesia with retained muscle tone/rigidity and cranial nerve reflexes and a tendency toward rough, excitatory recoveries, so it is paired with a benzodiazepine or alpha-2 agonist. It actually provides good somatic analgesia and tends to PRESERVE airway reflexes, and respiratory drive is relatively maintained."},{"id":"np12","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"For a procedure requiring the most rapid moment-to-moment control of anesthetic depth, which inhalant's very low blood:gas partition coefficient (~0.42) makes it best suited?","options":["Isoflurane","Sevoflurane","Halothane","Desflurane"],"answer":3,"explain":"Desflurane has the lowest blood:gas solubility (~0.42), giving the fastest induction, recovery, and changes in depth. Sevoflurane (~0.65) is close but higher, and isoflurane (~1.4) and halothane (~2.4) are more soluble and slower. Desflurane's high vapor pressure requires a heated vaporizer and it is pungent (airway-irritating)."},{"id":"np13","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"The GI ulceration and renal risk of non-selective NSAIDs are best explained by inhibition of which enzyme, and why?","options":["Selective inhibition of COX-2 only, sparing all constitutive prostaglandin functions","Reversed roles, with COX-1 driving inflammation and COX-2 being protective","Inhibition of constitutive COX-1, which maintains GI mucosal defense and renal blood flow","Inhibition of the 5-lipoxygenase (leukotriene) pathway"],"answer":2,"explain":"Non-selective NSAIDs inhibit constitutive COX-1, which normally maintains GI mucosal protection and renal perfusion, along with inflammatory COX-2, explaining ulceration and renal risk. The classic protective role belongs to COX-1 (not COX-2), COX-2-preferential drugs aim to spare it, and the leukotriene pathway is a different system."},{"id":"np14","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"A dog reversed with naloxone after hydromorphone regains normal ventilation, but 45 minutes later becomes hypoventilating and sedate again. What best explains this and the appropriate response?","options":["A single naloxone dose is definitive, so this cannot be recurrence","Naloxone reversed only respiratory depression and never analgesia, so nothing has changed","Naloxone's shorter duration allowed opioid effects to return (re-narcotization); re-dose or start a CRI","Naloxone permanently reversed the opioid, so this must be an unrelated new problem"],"answer":2,"explain":"Naloxone's half-life is shorter than that of hydromorphone or morphine, so as it wears off the opioid's effects, including respiratory depression, can return (re-narcotization). Continued monitoring with repeat dosing or a naloxone CRI is required; a single dose is not definitive."},{"id":"np15","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"Ketamine causes muscle rigidity and hypertonus. Which co-administered agent reliably offsets this by providing central muscle relaxation, forming the basis of 'ket-val'/'ket-mid' inductions?","options":["An anticholinergic such as atropine","An anticholinergic such as glycopyrrolate","A mu-opioid such as hydromorphone","A benzodiazepine such as midazolam or diazepam"],"answer":3,"explain":"Benzodiazepines (midazolam, diazepam) provide central muscle relaxation that counters ketamine's rigidity, smoothing induction and reducing rough recoveries - the basis of 'ket-val'/'ket-mid' combinations. Anticholinergics and opioids do not supply skeletal muscle relaxation."},{"id":"np16","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"A dog is profoundly sedate and mildly hypotensive about 3 hours after an inadvertently high dose of acepromazine. Regarding the drug's duration and reversibility, which statement is correct?","options":["The effect is long-lasting but fully reversible with atipamezole","The effect is short (under 30 minutes) and will resolve almost immediately","The effect is long-lasting (often 4-8 hours) and there is no specific reversal agent","The effect is long-lasting but reversible with flumazenil"],"answer":2,"explain":"Acepromazine has a long duration (often 4-8 hours) and NO specific antagonist, so management of oversedation and hypotension is supportive (fluids, blood pressure support, time). It is not an alpha-2 agonist or benzodiazepine, so atipamezole and flumazenil do not reverse it."},{"id":"np17","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"What is the core rationale of a balanced (multimodal) anesthetic technique?","options":["Combining higher doses of several agents to guarantee adequate depth","Combining sub-maximal doses of several agents with different mechanisms to minimize each drug's dose-dependent side effects","Relying on a single agent at its maximum tolerated dose","Relying entirely on inhalant concentration to control every component of anesthesia"],"answer":1,"explain":"Balanced anesthesia combines several agents (premed, induction, inhalant, analgesics) at LOWER individual doses so the goals are met while the dose-dependent adverse effects of any single drug are minimized. Using higher doses or a single agent at maximum dose would increase, not reduce, side effects."},{"id":"np18","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"Nitrous oxide is added to an isoflurane anesthetic. Which statement about nitrous oxide is correct in this setting?","options":["It provides analgesia and MAC reduction but cannot be used alone because its MAC is very low","It is a complete anesthetic capable of producing surgical anesthesia by itself","It provides analgesia and reduces the primary inhalant's MAC, but cannot anesthetize alone because its own MAC exceeds 100%","It must be reversed at the end because it is metabolized to a toxic compound"],"answer":2,"explain":"Nitrous oxide has a MAC well over 100% in animals, so it cannot produce surgical anesthesia alone, but it does provide analgesia and reduces the MAC of the primary inhalant. A very low MAC would imply high potency, which is the opposite of reality; at discontinuation, supplement oxygen to prevent diffusion hypoxia."},{"id":"np19","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"The 'second gas effect' of nitrous oxide describes how:","options":["Rapid uptake of nitrous oxide slows the alveolar rise of the co-administered volatile agent","Nitrous oxide raises the MAC of the co-administered volatile agent","Nitrous oxide delays its own onset by diluting alveolar gas","Rapid, high-volume uptake of nitrous oxide accelerates the rise in alveolar concentration of a co-administered volatile agent"],"answer":3,"explain":"Rapid uptake of large volumes of nitrous oxide concentrates the remaining alveolar gases and augments inspired inflow, speeding the rise in alveolar concentration of the second (volatile) agent and hastening induction. It accelerates, not slows, that rise, and does not increase the volatile agent's MAC."},{"id":"np20","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"A healthy 3-year-old Labrador is anxious but hemodynamically stable before an elective neuter. Which premedication is most appropriate?","options":["High-dose acepromazine alone","A mu-opioid combined with a low dose of acepromazine or dexmedetomidine","High-dose dexmedetomidine alone","Ketamine alone, given IM"],"answer":1,"explain":"An opioid plus a low dose of a sedative (acepromazine or dexmedetomidine) provides sedation, anxiolysis, and pre-emptive analgesia while smoothing induction and reducing induction/inhalant requirements. High single-agent doses add cardiovascular risk without analgesia (acepromazine) or are excessive in a stable elective patient, and ketamine alone offers no anxiolysis and rough handling."},{"id":"np21","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"As systemic lidocaine concentrations climb toward toxicity in a dog, which manifestation typically appears FIRST?","options":["Ventricular tachycardia and arrhythmias as the earliest sign","Hypertension with reflex tachycardia","CNS signs - nausea, muscle twitching/tremors, progressing to seizures","Isolated hypersalivation and vomiting with no CNS involvement"],"answer":2,"explain":"Systemic lidocaine toxicity affects the CNS first, with nausea, muscle tremors, and seizures preceding cardiovascular depression, so cumulative dose limits across boluses, CRIs, and blocks must be respected. Early, prominent cardiotoxicity is more characteristic of bupivacaine, not lidocaine."},{"id":"np22","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"Before performing an epidural, you specifically draw up preservative-free morphine. Why is the preservative-free formulation mandatory for neuraxial use?","options":["Preservatives shorten the duration of epidural analgesia","Preservatives can be neurotoxic to neural and spinal tissue in the neuraxial space","Preservative-containing morphine is less potent milligram-for-milligram","Preservatives enhance analgesia, so removing them is only a cost-saving measure"],"answer":1,"explain":"Preservatives in standard morphine formulations (for example, formaldehyde-releasing agents or chlorobutanol) can be neurotoxic when placed in the epidural or intrathecal space, so only preservative-free solutions are used for neuraxial techniques. The concern is neurotoxicity, not potency or duration."},{"id":"nphy01","domain":"Physiology","q":"Which expression correctly defines global oxygen delivery (DO2), and what does it reveal about the contribution of PaO2?","options":["DO2 = cardiac output × PaO2, so arterial oxygen tension is the main driver of delivery","DO2 = cardiac output × arterial oxygen content, which is dominated by hemoglobin-bound O2, so PaO2 contributes little","DO2 = hemoglobin × SaO2, so cardiac output does not enter the calculation","DO2 = cardiac output × mixed venous oxygen content"],"answer":1,"explain":"Oxygen delivery = cardiac output × arterial oxygen content (CaO2), where CaO2 ≈ (1.34 × Hb × SaO2) + (0.003 × PaO2). Content is dominated by hemoglobin-bound oxygen, so dissolved O2 (PaO2) adds little to delivery. Anemia, low output, or desaturation all lower DO2. Substituting PaO2 for content, dropping cardiac output, or using mixed venous (rather than arterial) content all misstate delivery."},{"id":"nphy02","domain":"Physiology","q":"An anesthetized dog on 100% oxygen has a PaO2 of 500 mmHg, yet the dissolved fraction adds only ~1.5 mL O2/dL to arterial oxygen content. This illustrates that arterial oxygen is transported predominantly:","options":["Dissolved in plasma, which is why a high PaO2 greatly raises oxygen content","As bicarbonate ion within the plasma","Bound to plasma albumin","Bound to hemoglobin, which carries over 98% of arterial oxygen"],"answer":3,"explain":"Over 98% of arterial oxygen is carried bound to hemoglobin (1.34 mL O2 per gram of saturated Hb); only ~0.003 mL/dL/mmHg is dissolved, so even a PaO2 of 500 mmHg adds just ~1.5 mL/dL. That is why oxygen-carrying capacity depends far more on hemoglobin concentration than on PaO2. Bicarbonate is the main transport form of CO2, not O2, and oxygen is not carried on albumin."},{"id":"nphy03","domain":"Physiology","q":"By the Frank–Starling mechanism, stroke volume rises when a determinant increases resting sarcomere length at end-diastole. Which determinant is this, and what represents it?","options":["Preload — the end-diastolic ventricular volume/wall stretch, set largely by venous return","Afterload — the wall stress opposing ventricular filling","Contractility — the length-independent intrinsic inotropic state","Preload — the end-systolic ventricular volume remaining after ejection"],"answer":0,"explain":"Preload is the end-diastolic ventricular volume/stretch, determined largely by venous return; by Frank–Starling, greater end-diastolic sarcomere stretch increases stroke volume up to a point. Afterload is the resistance/wall stress the ventricle ejects against (not a filling variable), contractility is the length-independent inotropic state, and end-systolic volume is the residual after ejection — not preload."},{"id":"nphy04","domain":"Physiology","q":"A healthy young dog under light sedation (baroreflexes largely intact) acutely loses blood pressure after a vasodilating drug bolus. Which compensatory hemodynamic pattern would you expect?","options":["Tachycardia with peripheral vasodilation","Reflex bradycardia with vasoconstriction","Tachycardia with arteriolar vasoconstriction and increased contractility","Bradycardia with decreased contractility"],"answer":2,"explain":"Intact baroreflexes respond to a fall in pressure with increased sympathetic outflow and reduced vagal tone: tachycardia, increased contractility, and arteriolar vasoconstriction (raised SVR) to restore pressure. Vasodilation would worsen hypotension, and bradycardia is the response to a pressure rise. Deeper anesthesia blunts this reflex, which is why anesthetized patients tolerate hypotension poorly."},{"id":"nphy05","domain":"Physiology","q":"When setting manual or mechanical ventilation for a dog, which approximate tidal volume represents the normal physiologic estimate — above which volutrauma risk rises and below which hypoventilation occurs?","options":["3–5 mL/kg","10–15 mL/kg","18–22 mL/kg","25–30 mL/kg"],"answer":1,"explain":"Normal tidal volume in dogs and cats is approximately 10–15 mL/kg. Much larger volumes risk volutrauma/barotrauma, while much smaller ones (approaching the ~2–5 mL/kg anatomic dead space) cause ineffective alveolar ventilation and hypercapnia. Peak inspiratory pressures for healthy lungs are typically kept around 10–15 cmH2O and generally below ~20 to avoid overdistension."},{"id":"nphy06","domain":"Physiology","q":"During a laparotomy under isoflurane, a dog's ETCO2 climbs steadily from 40 to 60 mmHg over 8 minutes. The airway is patent, SpO2 is 99%, inspired CO2 reads zero with fresh absorbent, the plateau is normal, and anesthetic depth is appropriate. What is the most appropriate next step?","options":["Deepen anesthesia by increasing the isoflurane vaporizer setting","Increase fresh gas flow to flush accumulated CO2 from the breathing circuit","Reduce the ventilation rate to permit more complete exhalation","Begin assisted or controlled ventilation to raise minute ventilation and lower PaCO2"],"answer":3,"explain":"A steadily rising ETCO2 with a patent airway, zero inspired CO2, fresh absorbent, and a normal plateau indicates alveolar hypoventilation (anesthetic respiratory depression), not rebreathing. The direct correction is to assist or control ventilation, increasing minute ventilation to normalize PaCO2. Deepening anesthesia worsens the depression, increasing fresh gas flow does not fix inadequate alveolar ventilation when there is no rebreathing, and lowering the rate reduces minute ventilation, worsening hypercapnia."},{"id":"nphy07","domain":"Physiology","q":"In a dog with traumatic brain injury and raised intracranial pressure, which arterial parameter provides the most immediate, titratable control over cerebral blood flow and ICP through its effect on cerebral vessels?","options":["PaCO2 — hypercapnia dilates cerebral vessels raising CBF/ICP, while mild hypocapnia constricts them","PaO2 — cerebral vessels dilate progressively as arterial oxygen tension rises above normal","Blood glucose — hyperglycemia is the primary vasodilatory driver of cerebral blood flow","Core body temperature — the sole determinant of cerebral blood flow"],"answer":0,"explain":"PaCO2 is the most powerful and rapidly titratable determinant of cerebral blood flow: hypercapnia causes cerebral vasodilation, raising CBF and ICP, while controlled mild hypocapnia produces vasoconstriction that can acutely lower ICP (aggressive hypocapnia risks ischemia). PaO2 affects CBF mainly at low levels (hypoxemia below ~50–60 mmHg dilates vessels; hyperoxia mildly constricts), glucose is not a primary vasomotor driver, and temperature is not the sole determinant. Careful ventilation is central to neuroanesthesia."},{"id":"nphy08","domain":"Physiology","q":"A 45 kg obese dog is positioned in dorsal recumbency for exploratory laparotomy; 20 minutes in, SpO2 drifts from 99% to 93% on 100% oxygen despite a patent airway and stable ventilation. Which mechanism most likely explains the falling oxygenation?","options":["Enlarged anatomic dead space from the tracheal tube, raising PaCO2 and thereby lowering SpO2","Alveolar hyperinflation that raises lung compliance and V/Q scatter","Anesthesia, recumbency, obesity, and abdominal pressure lower FRC below closing capacity, causing dependent atelectasis and shunt","Anesthetic bronchodilation that increases dead-space ventilation"],"answer":2,"explain":"Anesthesia, dorsal recumbency, obesity, and cranial displacement of the diaphragm by abdominal contents all reduce FRC below closing capacity, collapsing dependent alveoli (atelectasis). These perfused-but-unventilated units act as shunt, causing hypoxemia even on 100% oxygen. Dead space raises CO2 rather than directly lowering SpO2, and hyperinflation or bronchodilation do not explain progressive desaturation. Recruitment maneuvers and PEEP are the mitigations."},{"id":"nphy09","domain":"Physiology","q":"An obstructed male cat's ECG shows tall, tented T waves, a widened QRS, absent P waves (atrial standstill), and bradycardia. Which electrolyte derangement most specifically produces this progression?","options":["Hypokalemia, which causes ST depression, U waves, and tachyarrhythmias","Hyperkalemia, which causes peaked T waves, widened QRS, atrial standstill, and bradycardia","Hypocalcemia, which prolongs the QT interval","Hypercalcemia, which shortens the QT interval"],"answer":1,"explain":"Hyperkalemia produces a characteristic progression: peaked/tented T waves, then P-wave flattening and prolonged PR, widened QRS, loss of P waves (atrial standstill) with bradycardia, and ultimately a sine-wave pattern and asystole — classic in urethral-obstructed cats and uroabdomen. Hypokalemia instead causes ST depression, U waves, and tachyarrhythmias, and calcium disorders alter the QT interval rather than causing peaked T waves and atrial standstill."},{"id":"nphy10","domain":"Physiology","q":"A 5 kg male cat with a 2-day urethral obstruction is bradycardic (HR 90) with K+ 8.2 mmol/L and blood pH 7.16. The clinician wants to anesthetize immediately to unblock. What is the best rationale for stabilizing first?","options":["The main danger is hypocalcemia, which must be corrected before induction","The derangements are hyperkalemia with metabolic alkalosis, correctable by fluids alone","The danger is hypernatremia with dehydration, so correcting sodium is the priority","Hyperkalemia and metabolic acidosis cause life-threatening bradyarrhythmias, so correcting them (fluids, calcium gluconate, dextrose ± insulin) plus decompression reduces anesthetic risk"],"answer":3,"explain":"Obstructed cats develop hyperkalemia and metabolic acidosis from impaired renal excretion, which together predispose to life-threatening bradyarrhythmias and myocardial instability — dangerous under anesthesia. Stabilization includes IV fluids, calcium gluconate (membrane cardioprotection), and dextrose ± insulin (or terbutaline) to drive K+ intracellularly, plus bladder decompression, before or alongside a minimal anesthetic. The disturbance is acidosis (not alkalosis), and the primary threat is potassium, not calcium or sodium."},{"id":"nphy11","domain":"Physiology","q":"Which receptors mediate the hypoxic ventilatory drive, and to precisely what stimulus do they respond?","options":["Peripheral chemoreceptors (carotid and aortic bodies) responding to a fall in arterial PaO2","Peripheral chemoreceptors responding to a fall in arterial oxygen content, as in anemia","Central medullary chemoreceptors responding to a low PaO2","Pulmonary J-receptors responding to interstitial edema"],"answer":0,"explain":"The hypoxic drive is mediated by peripheral chemoreceptors in the carotid and aortic bodies, which respond to arterial oxygen tension (PaO2), not oxygen content — so anemia (low content but normal PaO2) does not strongly stimulate them. This drive becomes dominant in chronic CO2 retainers, where high-flow oxygen must be given cautiously. Central chemoreceptors sense CSF pH/PaCO2, not O2, and J-receptors respond to pulmonary congestion."},{"id":"nphy12","domain":"Physiology","q":"You are planning anesthesia for an emergency cesarean in a term-pregnant bitch. Relative to a nonpregnant dog, how are her inhalant anesthetic requirements altered, and why does it matter?","options":["MAC is increased ~25–40%, requiring higher vaporizer settings","MAC is essentially unchanged, so standard settings apply","MAC is reduced ~25–40% (largely a progesterone effect), so less inhalant is needed","MAC is reduced only ~5–10%, a clinically negligible change"],"answer":2,"explain":"Pregnancy lowers MAC by roughly 25–40%, largely from progesterone's CNS effects, so inhalant requirements fall substantially. Combined with reduced FRC, increased aspiration risk, aortocaval compression, and the fact that inhalants cross the placenta to depress neonates, the anesthetist should reduce inhalant delivery and titrate carefully. The change is a clinically important decrease — not an increase, no change, or a trivial 5–10%."},{"id":"nphy13","domain":"Physiology","q":"Which combination shifts the oxyhemoglobin dissociation curve to the LEFT, increasing hemoglobin's oxygen affinity and impairing tissue offloading?","options":["Hyperthermia, acidosis, and hypercapnia","Hypothermia, alkalosis, hypocapnia, and decreased 2,3-DPG","Hypothermia, alkalosis, and increased 2,3-DPG","Acidosis with decreased 2,3-DPG"],"answer":1,"explain":"A left shift (higher O2 affinity, reduced tissue offloading) is produced by alkalosis, hypothermia, hypocapnia, and decreased 2,3-DPG (also carbon monoxide and fetal hemoglobin) — relevant in the hypothermic anesthetized patient whose tissues unload oxygen less readily. Increased 2,3-DPG, acidosis, hypercapnia, and hyperthermia all shift the curve rightward, so any option containing one of those does not describe a pure left shift."},{"id":"nphy14","domain":"Physiology","q":"Shortly after a term-pregnant bitch is positioned in dorsal recumbency for a cesarean, her blood pressure drops markedly though blood loss is minimal. What is the primary mechanism, and what maneuver best relieves it?","options":["Aortic compression raises afterload and thereby increases cardiac output; deepen anesthesia","Portal vein compression reduces hepatic flow and causes the hypotension; give a fluid bolus only","The caudal vena cava is compressed, increasing venous return and cardiac output; no repositioning is needed","The gravid uterus compresses the caudal vena cava, reducing venous return and cardiac output; tilting the patient off midline relieves it"],"answer":3,"explain":"In dorsal recumbency the gravid uterus compresses the caudal vena cava (and aorta) — aortocaval/supine hypotensive syndrome — reducing venous return, cardiac output, and uteroplacental perfusion despite minimal blood loss. Tilting the patient ~15° off midline (or manually displacing the uterus) restores venous return. Caval compression decreases, not increases, venous return; aortic compression raises afterload without raising output; and portal compression is not the mechanism."},{"id":"neq01","domain":"Equipment","q":"A veterinary technician who is pregnant is concerned about chronic exposure to inhalant anesthetic in the surgery suite. The single machine component whose primary job is to protect her from that exposure is the:","options":["CO2 absorbent canister, which removes exhaled gases","Scavenging system, which collects waste anesthetic from the pop-off and ventilator and vents it out of the room","Pop-off (APL) valve, which vents excess circuit pressure","Oxygen flush valve, which dilutes room anesthetic"],"answer":1,"explain":"The scavenging system collects waste anesthetic gas leaving the pop-off valve and ventilator and vents it out of the room, reducing chronic occupational exposure - the relevant protection for staff. The pop-off is merely where gas exits the circuit (into the scavenger); the CO2 absorbent and flush valve serve unrelated functions."},{"id":"neq02","domain":"Equipment","q":"The primary reason to inflate an endotracheal tube cuff - the function that justifies accepting the small risk of mucosal pressure injury - is to:","options":["Anchor the tube so it cannot be coughed or pulled out","Seal the airway to prevent aspiration of fluid and leakage of anesthetic gas","Hold the trachea open and prevent dynamic collapse","Reduce mechanical dead space within the airway"],"answer":1,"explain":"The cuff's primary purpose is to seal the trachea, preventing aspiration of fluid or material into the lungs and leakage of anesthetic gas around the tube. It is not primarily an anchor, does not stent the trachea open, and does not reduce dead space. Inflate only to a minimal leak-free seal to avoid mucosal injury."},{"id":"neq03","domain":"Equipment","q":"A cat is turned from dorsal to sternal recumbency during a dental without disconnecting the breathing circuit, and its over-inflated endotracheal tube twists in the trachea. Several days later it develops subcutaneous emphysema. The mechanism you failed to prevent was:","options":["Improved sealing with no mucosal consequence","Tracheal mucosal ischemia, necrosis, or frank tracheal rupture from excessive cuff pressure","Reduced airway resistance that made ventilation too easy","Loss of the cuff seal from overdistension, leading to aspiration"],"answer":1,"explain":"Excessive cuff pressure compresses the tracheal mucosa, causing ischemia, necrosis, or frank tracheal rupture. Cats are especially prone, and turning a patient without disconnecting the circuit lets an over-inflated tube twist and tear the trachea - producing subcutaneous emphysema. Use a minimal occlusive volume and disconnect before repositioning."},{"id":"neq04","domain":"Equipment","q":"An anesthetist notes that a nitrous oxide cylinder's gauge has read a nearly constant ~745 psi for hours of use, whereas the oxygen cylinder's gauge falls steadily. The correct explanation for the N2O behavior is that:","options":["A pressure-reducing regulator clamps the cylinder gauge reading at a fixed value","N2O is stored as a liquid in equilibrium with its vapor, so gauge (vapor) pressure stays constant until nearly all the liquid is gone","N2O is far more compressible than oxygen, so its pressure declines very slowly","The cylinder is continuously topped up from a manifold reserve"],"answer":1,"explain":"Nitrous oxide is stored as a liquid in equilibrium with its vapor; the gauge reflects vapor pressure (~745 psi), which stays nearly constant until almost all the liquid is consumed, then falls quickly. Because pressure does not track volume, remaining N2O is judged by cylinder WEIGHT, not the gauge. The regulator reduces downstream working pressure, not the cylinder gauge."},{"id":"neq05","domain":"Equipment","q":"During the pre-anesthetic check you close the pop-off, occlude the Y-piece, and fill the circle with the flush until the manometer reads 30 cmH2O - but the reservoir bag steadily deflates and the needle falls. Before using the machine, the first conclusion is that:","options":["Fresh gas flow is set too high and is overfilling the bag","There is a leak in the breathing system that must be located and corrected","The CO2 absorbent canister is correctly seated","The reservoir bag is too large for the patient"],"answer":1,"explain":"If the circuit cannot hold pressure with the pop-off closed and the Y-piece occluded, there is a leak - check hose connections, the reservoir bag, the ET tube/cuff, and the absorber canister seals before use. High fresh gas flow would inflate (not deflate) the bag, and a proper canister seat or bag size would not cause deflation."},{"id":"neq06","domain":"Equipment","q":"In a circle system, if one unidirectional (one-way) valve becomes stuck open, the resulting problem reveals the valves' true purpose, which is to:","options":["Vent excess circuit pressure to the scavenger","Enforce one-way flow so inhaled gas comes from the inspiratory limb and exhaled gas is routed through the CO2 absorber, preventing rebreathing","Regulate the volume of fresh gas entering the circuit","Vaporize liquid anesthetic into the gas stream"],"answer":1,"explain":"The inspiratory and expiratory one-way valves force gas around the circle in a single direction, so inhaled gas comes from the fresh/absorbed side and exhaled gas passes through the CO2 absorber. A valve stuck open breaks this pattern and causes CO2 rebreathing - which is exactly what their unidirectional action exists to prevent. Pressure relief, flow, and vaporization are other components' jobs."},{"id":"neq07","domain":"Equipment","q":"You are about to intubate a 4-year-old English Bulldog for airway surgery. Weight-based estimation suggests a 9.0 mm tube, but you also open 7.0 and 8.0 mm tubes. The best rationale for having the smaller sizes ready is that:","options":["A fresh sterile tube is required for every intubation attempt","Brachycephalic airways and tracheal hypoplasia often make the true lumen far smaller than weight predicts, and forcing an oversized tube is traumatic","The largest tube that will pass should always be used to minimize resistance","Tube size should be chosen by the patient's age rather than airway anatomy"],"answer":1,"explain":"Weight-based sizing is only an estimate, and brachycephalic breeds such as Bulldogs frequently have tracheal hypoplasia, so the true lumen is smaller than predicted. Having a size down (and up) ready allows an atraumatic, well-sealed fit; forcing an oversized tube injures the airway. Choosing 'the largest that fits' or sizing by age is incorrect."},{"id":"neq08","domain":"Equipment","q":"Several machine displays are easily confused. The flowmeter (rotameter) specifically indicates:","options":["The percent of anesthetic agent added to the carrier gas","The rate of fresh carrier gas (usually oxygen) delivered, in L/min","The pressure of gas remaining in the cylinder","The pressure within the patient's breathing circuit"],"answer":1,"explain":"The flowmeter (rotameter) meters and displays fresh carrier-gas flow, usually oxygen, in L/min. The vaporizer dial sets agent concentration, the cylinder gauge shows tank pressure, and the manometer shows circuit pressure. Adequate flow is essential for non-rebreathing systems and for preoxygenation/denitrogenation."},{"id":"neq09","domain":"Equipment","q":"Three hours into a circle-system anesthetic, the capnograph's inspired baseline has climbed to 8 mmHg, ETCO2 is 60 mmHg, and the patient is tachycardic; the soda lime was not changed after yesterday's heavy caseload. The acid-base and gas consequence of this exhausted absorbent is:","options":["A steady fall in the inspired oxygen concentration","Rebreathing of CO2 causing hypercapnia and respiratory acidosis","Rebreathing of CO2 causing hypercapnia and respiratory alkalosis","A progressive lightening of the anesthetic plane"],"answer":1,"explain":"Spent soda lime no longer absorbs CO2, so the patient rebreathes exhaled CO2, producing hypercapnia and - because CO2 is an acid - respiratory ACIDOSIS, not alkalosis. A rising inspired baseline, high ETCO2, and tachycardia fit. Absorbent status does not change FiO2 or anesthetic depth directly."},{"id":"neq10","domain":"Equipment","q":"Which approach MOST reliably confirms that an endotracheal tube is in the trachea and not the esophagus?","options":["Direct visualization of the tube passing between the arytenoids, corroborated by a sustained capnograph waveform","Palpating a single firm tube-like structure in the ventral neck","Observing the reservoir bag move with each spontaneous breath","Waiting for the return of a swallowing reflex"],"answer":0,"explain":"The most reliable confirmation of tracheal (not esophageal) placement is direct visualization of the tube passing between the arytenoids plus a sustained capnograph waveform - the strongest single objective sign. Palpating a neck tube, watching bag movement, or awaiting a swallow reflex can all occur with esophageal placement or are unrelated to tube position."},{"id":"neq11","domain":"Equipment","q":"You have just given a 20 kg dog two manual sigh breaths by closing the pop-off valve and squeezing the bag. As the patient resumes spontaneous breathing, the correct position for the pop-off valve is:","options":["Fully closed, to maintain positive circuit pressure","Open - and it should be reopened the instant the manual breaths are finished","Closed until the patient is extubated at the end of the case","Half-closed throughout, to conserve anesthetic gas"],"answer":1,"explain":"The pop-off (APL) valve stays open during spontaneous ventilation to vent excess gas and prevent pressure buildup. It is closed only momentarily to deliver a manual breath and must be reopened immediately afterward. Leaving it closed - or even half-closed - allows a dangerous pressure rise and barotrauma."},{"id":"neq12","domain":"Equipment","q":"During manual (bag) ventilation of a healthy dog, the anesthetist watches the circuit manometer to avoid exceeding roughly 20 cmH2O. The manometer makes this possible because it:","options":["Measures the delivered anesthetic agent concentration","Displays breathing-circuit (airway) pressure, allowing peak pressure to be limited to avoid barotrauma","Quantifies the volume of waste gas sent to the scavenger","Controls the rate of oxygen flow into the circuit"],"answer":1,"explain":"The manometer displays breathing-circuit (airway) pressure, letting the operator keep peak inspiratory pressure low (around 20 cmH2O in healthy lungs) to avoid barotrauma, and confirm a sealed circuit during leak checks. It does not measure agent concentration, scavenged volume, or oxygen flow."},{"id":"nmon01","domain":"Monitoring","q":"You notice the capnograph's low point between breaths - the inspired baseline - no longer returns to zero but sits at 6-9 mmHg, while the peak ETCO2 is only mildly raised. This specific pattern (elevated baseline rather than elevated peak) indicates:","options":["Hypoventilation, which raises the peak (end-tidal) value but not the baseline","Rebreathing of CO2, typically from exhausted absorbent or an incompetent one-way valve","Esophageal intubation","Apnea"],"answer":1,"explain":"An inspired (baseline) CO2 that fails to return to zero means the patient is rebreathing CO2 - typically from exhausted soda lime, an incompetent one-way valve, or inadequate fresh gas flow in a non-rebreathing system. Hypoventilation instead raises the PEAK (end-tidal) value, and esophageal intubation or apnea flatten the trace toward zero."},{"id":"nmon02","domain":"Monitoring","q":"A well-preoxygenated, apneic patient can maintain SpO2 near 100% for several minutes even as PaCO2 climbs steadily. The best physiologic explanation is that:","options":["The pulse oximeter automatically corrects its reading for the rising CO2","Oxygenation and CO2 elimination are separate; a large alveolar oxygen reservoir sustains saturation while apnea still lets CO2 accumulate (apneic oxygenation)","High oxygen flow physically flushes CO2 out of the alveoli","Hypercapnia causes vasodilation that improves oximeter accuracy"],"answer":1,"explain":"Oxygenation and CO2 elimination are distinct processes. After preoxygenation, a large alveolar oxygen reservoir keeps hemoglobin saturated (SpO2 near 100%) for minutes even during apnea, while PaCO2 climbs because ventilation - the process that removes CO2 - has stopped. Oximeters do not correct for CO2, and high flow does not flush alveolar CO2."},{"id":"nmon03","domain":"Monitoring","q":"An over-sedated 30 kg dog on 100% oxygen is breathing only 4 times per minute, yet the pulse oximeter reads a reassuring 99% while the ETCO2 is 68 mmHg. Which statement best explains why the SpO2 is falsely reassuring here?","options":["Oxygenation and ventilation are independent - a high FiO2 keeps hemoglobin fully saturated even as hypoventilation lets CO2 accumulate","The high oxygen flow is flushing CO2 from the alveoli, so the ETCO2 reading must be artifact","Rising CO2 shifts the dissociation curve and artificially inflates the displayed SpO2","Peripheral vasoconstriction is concentrating oxygenated hemoglobin under the probe"],"answer":0,"explain":"Oxygenation and ventilation are independent: a high inspired oxygen fraction keeps hemoglobin fully saturated (normal SpO2) even when hypoventilation lets CO2 accumulate. That is why an ETCO2 of 68 with SpO2 99% is dangerous and why capnography is essential alongside pulse oximetry. High O2 flow does not flush alveolar CO2, and the reading is not artifact."},{"id":"nmon04","domain":"Monitoring","q":"A transmittance pulse oximeter probe needs tissue that is thin, non-pigmented, and well perfused so light can pass from emitter to detector. Which set of sites best satisfies these requirements?","options":["Only thick, heavily pigmented footpads","Tongue, lip, ear margin, toe web, prepuce, or vulva","Haired skin over the dorsum or flank","Directly over a large muscle belly such as the quadriceps"],"answer":1,"explain":"Transmittance probes require thin, non-pigmented, well-perfused tissue: the tongue (most common), lip, ear margin, toe web, prepuce, or vulva. Reflectance probes can be placed rectally. Thick or pigmented pads, haired skin, and muscle bellies block light transmission or lack an accessible pulsatile signal."},{"id":"nmon05","domain":"Monitoring","q":"During a prolonged feline nephrectomy the oscillometric mean arterial pressure has trended from 75 to 52 mmHg over 15 minutes and the palpable metatarsal pulse feels weaker; the vaporizer is at 2% isoflurane. The most appropriate next step is to:","options":["Increase the vaporizer to 3% to stabilize the monitor reading","Recognize developing hypotension - assess anesthetic depth, fluids, and perfusion, and notify the veterinarian","Switch to a larger cuff and take no other action","Record the value and plan to recheck only at the end of surgery"],"answer":1,"explain":"Trends matter more than single values: a falling MAP (75 to 52 mmHg) with a weakening pulse signals developing hypotension. The correct response is to assess anesthetic depth, fluids, and perfusion and alert the veterinarian to intervene early - not to deepen anesthesia (which worsens hypotension), merely change the cuff, or defer rechecking."},{"id":"nmon06","domain":"Monitoring","q":"Which best reflects adequate tissue PERFUSION (as opposed to blood oxygenation) during anesthesia?","options":["A single systolic blood pressure reading within the normal range","The integrated trend of blood pressure, capillary refill time, pulse quality, and mucous membrane color over time","The pulse oximeter SpO2 value","The end-tidal CO2 value in isolation"],"answer":1,"explain":"Perfusion is best judged by integrating trends - blood pressure, capillary refill time, pulse quality, mucous membrane color (plus ETCO2 and temperature) - over time, not from any single number. A lone systolic value, the SpO2 (which reflects blood oxygenation, not flow), or an isolated ETCO2 cannot capture tissue perfusion."},{"id":"nmon07","domain":"Monitoring","q":"During enucleation of a dog's eye, as the surgeon applies traction to the globe, the ECG shows a sudden ~4-second pause with no P waves and no QRS complexes, after which normal sinus rhythm resumes. This is most consistent with:","options":["Ventricular tachycardia","Vagally mediated sinus arrest/block","Atrial fibrillation","Third-degree (complete) AV block"],"answer":1,"explain":"A sudden pause with NO P waves and no QRS, then resumption, is sinus arrest/block - here vagally mediated via the oculocardiac reflex from ocular traction. Key discriminator: in third-degree AV block the atria keep firing, so P waves CONTINUE independently of the QRS; their absence here rules it out. Treat the cause; anticholinergics may be indicated."},{"id":"nmon08","domain":"Monitoring","q":"Direct (invasive) arterial blood pressure monitoring is considered the gold standard primarily because it:","options":["Is quicker and simpler to set up than an oscillometric cuff","Provides continuous, beat-to-beat accurate pressure and permits arterial blood-gas sampling","Simultaneously and directly measures cardiac output and central venous pressure","Needs no transducer, tubing, or zeroing/calibration"],"answer":1,"explain":"A transduced arterial catheter gives continuous, beat-to-beat accurate pressure and allows arterial blood-gas sampling, which is why it is the gold standard. It does NOT directly measure cardiac output or CVP, is more (not less) involved to set up, and does require a transducer, tubing, and proper zeroing/calibration."},{"id":"nmon09","domain":"Monitoring","q":"A 2 kg kitten anesthetized for 90 minutes now has an esophageal temperature of 34.5°C (94°F). Which set of changes should you anticipate as a direct consequence of this hypothermia?","options":["Increased anesthetic requirement (higher MAC), needing a higher vaporizer setting","Bradycardia, a decreased MAC (risk of relative overdose), prolonged recovery, and unreliable pulse oximetry","Tachycardia with increased cardiac output","Peripheral vasodilation with warm, well-perfused extremities"],"answer":1,"explain":"Hypothermia lowers MAC (risking relative anesthetic overdose), slows heart rate and metabolism, prolongs drug effects and recovery, impairs coagulation, and - through peripheral vasoconstriction - makes pulse oximetry unreliable. It does NOT raise MAC or cause tachycardia/vasodilation. Active warming and temperature monitoring are essential, especially in tiny patients."},{"id":"nmon10","domain":"Monitoring","q":"Capnography is valuable during CPR for two reasons. At the moment of cardiac arrest, and then during effective chest compressions, how does ETCO2 behave?","options":["It rises at arrest from CO2 accumulation, then falls with compressions","It falls abruptly toward zero at arrest (loss of pulmonary blood flow), then rises with effective compressions/ROSC","It shows a steadily rising inspired baseline throughout","It remains an unchanged normal plateau, so it is not useful in arrest"],"answer":1,"explain":"At cardiac arrest, pulmonary blood flow stops, so CO2 is no longer delivered to the lungs and ETCO2 falls abruptly toward zero. During CPR, a rising ETCO2 indicates effective compressions or return of spontaneous circulation. The change is not a rise at arrest, a shifting baseline, or an unchanged plateau."},{"id":"nmon11","domain":"Monitoring","q":"An oscillometric monitor repeatedly errors out or returns implausible values on a hypotensive 2.5 kg cat with an irregular rhythm. Which is the best explanation and response?","options":["Oscillometric devices give continuous beat-to-beat data like an arterial line, so the machine is simply broken","Oscillometric accuracy degrades in very small patients, with arrhythmias, and at low pressures - Doppler or an arterial line is more dependable here","Oscillometric readings require an arterial catheter, which is missing","Oscillometric devices become more accurate as pressure falls, so the low values are trustworthy"],"answer":1,"explain":"Oscillometric monitors lose accuracy in very small patients, with motion or arrhythmias, and at low blood pressures - exactly this cat. Doppler (or a direct arterial line) is more dependable here. They are not continuous like an arterial line, do not require an arterial catheter, and become LESS reliable, not more, as pressure falls."},{"id":"nmon12","domain":"Monitoring","q":"A blood pressure cuff whose width is too NARROW for the limb (well under the recommended ~40% of circumference) will tend to bias the reading:","options":["Falsely low, the same direction as a cuff that is too wide","Falsely high","Not at all - cuff width does not influence the reading","Randomly erratic beat-to-beat but centered on the true value"],"answer":1,"explain":"A cuff too narrow (or too tight) for the limb requires extra pressure to occlude the artery, biasing the reading falsely HIGH; a cuff too wide reads falsely low. Cuff width should be about 40% of limb circumference. Width does affect readings, and the error is a directional bias, not random scatter."},{"id":"npn01","domain":"Pain Management","q":"A dog is at a stable surgical plane with unchanged jaw tone and eye position. As the surgeon incises, heart rate rises from 90 to 140, Doppler pressure from 90 to 130 mmHg, and respiratory rate from 8 to 22. Which interpretation best guides your response?","options":["The patient is arousing to a light plane, and the only appropriate action is to increase the vaporizer","This is a sympathetic response to nociception, and the best action is to add analgesia (opioid, local block, or CRI)","The changes reflect hypercapnia and will resolve without any analgesic intervention","This is expected anticholinergic-induced tachycardia and needs no response"],"answer":1,"explain":"Rising heart rate, blood pressure, and respiratory rate on surgical stimulation - with unchanged depth signs - indicate a sympathetic response to nociception, calling for additional analgesia rather than simply deepening the inhalant. Deepening alone worsens cardiovascular depression, and the pattern is not explained by hypercapnia or anticholinergic tachycardia."},{"id":"npn02","domain":"Pain Management","q":"During an intraoperative nociceptive surge, why is escalating the inhalant a poor substitute for adding an analgesic?","options":["Inhalants are potent analgesics, but their analgesic effect plateaus quickly","Volatile agents provide little intrinsic analgesia and cause dose-dependent cardiovascular depression","Higher inhalant concentrations raise sympathetic tone and worsen surgical bleeding","A deeper inhalant plane delivers pre-emptive analgesia that prevents wind-up"],"answer":1,"explain":"Volatile agents supply minimal true analgesia; pushing the vaporizer to blunt nociception mainly deepens dose-dependent cardiovascular and respiratory depression. Adding an analgesic (opioid, local block, or CRI) is safer and more effective. Inhalants do not raise sympathetic tone or provide pre-emptive analgesia."},{"id":"npn03","domain":"Pain Management","q":"Before an ovariohysterectomy, the surgeon suggests withholding analgesics and 'seeing if she is painful in recovery.' You recommend giving analgesia before incision instead. The strongest rationale is that pre-incisional analgesia:","options":["Lets you withhold drugs until postoperative pain reveals the true dose needed","Blunts the establishment of central sensitization, lowering total postoperative analgesic requirements","Allows a local anesthetic alone to carry the entire procedure without systemic drugs","Can be replaced by simply deepening the inhalant just before incision"],"answer":1,"explain":"Pre-emptive analgesia given before tissue injury blunts the development of central sensitization ('wind-up'), reducing pain intensity and the total analgesic requirement afterward. Waiting for postoperative pain permits sensitization to establish, a single local block rarely covers an entire laparotomy, and deepening the inhalant is not analgesia."},{"id":"npn04","domain":"Pain Management","q":"Compared with intermittent IV boluses, a properly loaded analgesic constant rate infusion (CRI) is preferred chiefly because it:","options":["Achieves higher peak plasma concentrations for a faster onset","Permits a larger total drug dose to be given safely","Sustains steady plasma concentrations, avoiding the troughs (breakthrough pain) and peaks (side effects) of bolus dosing","Removes the need for any loading dose to reach effect"],"answer":2,"explain":"A CRI maintains a stable steady-state plasma level, giving consistent analgesia without the breakthrough pain of troughs or the side effects of peaks seen with intermittent boluses. Boluses - not CRIs - produce the higher peaks, and a loading dose is still usually required to reach effect quickly."},{"id":"npn05","domain":"Pain Management","q":"Twelve hours after a fracture repair, a cat sits hunched at the back of its cage, has not groomed or eaten, and turns its face to the wall. A colleague says it is 'just stressed.' Which interpretation is most appropriate?","options":["These are benign stress behaviors, and analgesia is unlikely to help","Hunched posture, reduced grooming, inappetence, and facial changes are classic feline pain signs that warrant analgesic reassessment","Loud, continuous purring would be the reliable indicator of pain, and its absence rules pain out","Increased approach and affiliative behavior at the cage front would be the expected response to pain"],"answer":1,"explain":"Cats commonly mask pain; hiding, a hunched/tucked posture, decreased grooming and appetite, reluctance to move, and altered facial expression (Feline Grimace Scale) are recognized pain behaviors that should prompt analgesic reassessment. Purring is not a reliable sign of comfort, and painful cats typically withdraw rather than seek interaction."},{"id":"npn06","domain":"Pain Management","q":"Which combination interrupts the greatest number of distinct points in the nociceptive pathway?","options":["Opioid + benzodiazepine + inhalant","Opioid + NSAID + local/regional block, with an alpha-2 agonist or ketamine added","Opioid + benzodiazepine + local/regional block, with an alpha-2 agonist or ketamine added","High-dose opioid + an increased inhalant concentration"],"answer":1,"explain":"An opioid (central modulation), an NSAID (peripheral transduction/inflammation), a local/regional block (transmission), and an alpha-2 or NMDA antagonist (modulation) together cover the most sites. Swapping the NSAID for a benzodiazepine removes a true analgesic arm - benzodiazepines are not analgesics - and inhalant depth is not analgesia."},{"id":"npn07","domain":"Pain Management","q":"A 3-year-old cat is being pain-scored 18 hours after ovariohysterectomy using the Feline Grimace Scale. Which set of features are the validated action units this tool grades?","options":["Pupil size, nostril flare, and tongue protrusion","Ear position, orbital tightening, muzzle tension, whisker change, and head position","Response to gentle palpation of the surgical incision","Overall posture, gait, and activity level"],"answer":1,"explain":"The validated Feline Grimace Scale grades five facial action units - ear position, orbital tightening, muzzle tension, whisker position, and head position - giving an objective, repeatable pain score. Palpation response and posture/gait are useful clinical observations but are not the FGS action units."},{"id":"npn08","domain":"Pain Management","q":"In which patient is a perioperative NSAID an appropriate analgesic choice?","options":["Any patient, as long as an opioid is co-administered","A hypotensive patient, once inhalant anesthesia has 'stabilized' the blood pressure","A normovolemic, normotensive patient with normal renal function and no GI, coagulation, or corticosteroid contraindications","A patient already receiving prednisone, for an additive anti-inflammatory effect"],"answer":2,"explain":"NSAIDs are appropriate when the patient is well-perfused with normal renal function and free of GI, coagulation, or concurrent-steroid contraindications. Co-administering an opioid does not offset the renal risk, hypotension is a contraindication, and combining an NSAID with a corticosteroid markedly increases the risk of GI ulceration."},{"id":"nloc01","domain":"Local/Regional","q":"A dog is anesthetized for extraction of a fractured left mandibular first molar (tooth 309). Which block and landmark are correct for this tooth?","options":["Infraorbital block at the infraorbital foramen","Inferior alveolar (mandibular) block at the mandibular foramen on the lingual aspect of the ramus","Maxillary block near the pterygopalatine region","Middle mental block at the middle mental foramen"],"answer":1,"explain":"The inferior alveolar (mandibular) block anesthetizes the entire lower arcade by targeting the inferior alveolar nerve as it enters the mandibular foramen on the lingual aspect of the ramus, so it reaches the caudally located first molar. Infraorbital and maxillary blocks serve the upper arcade, and a mental block covers only the rostral mandible - it will not reliably desensitize a molar."},{"id":"nloc02","domain":"Local/Regional","q":"Epinephrine is added to a lidocaine solution for a peripheral block. Which statement pairs the correct effect with the correct caveat?","options":["It causes vasodilation that speeds systemic uptake and shortens the block","It causes vasoconstriction that prolongs the block, and it is safe to use on extremities and digits","It buffers the solution to raise pH and quicken onset, independent of blood flow","It causes vasoconstriction that prolongs the block and lowers peak plasma levels, but must be avoided at end-arterial sites such as the digits or pinna"],"answer":3,"explain":"Epinephrine produces local vasoconstriction that slows systemic absorption, prolonging the block and lowering peak plasma concentration (reduced toxicity), but it must be avoided where perfusion is end-arterial (digits, pinna, penis) to prevent ischemic necrosis. It does not cause vasodilation, is not safe on digits, and pH-buffering to speed onset is the role of bicarbonate, not epinephrine."},{"id":"nloc03","domain":"Local/Regional","q":"While placing a bupivacaine inferior alveolar block, you aspirate and see blood enter the hub. What is the most appropriate action and rationale?","options":["Inject anyway, because the mandibular vessels are too small to cause systemic toxicity","Reposition the needle and re-aspirate before injecting, because intravascular bupivacaine can cause systemic toxicity","Abandon regional anesthesia entirely, because a positive aspirate contraindicates any block at this site","Inject the full volume as a deliberate test dose to confirm placement by its effect"],"answer":1,"explain":"A positive aspirate means the needle tip is intravascular; injecting bupivacaine there risks seizures and refractory cardiac toxicity. The correct step is to reposition and re-aspirate until no blood returns, then inject. A positive aspirate does not force you to abandon the technique, and deliberately injecting a full intravascular dose is exactly what must be avoided."},{"id":"nloc04","domain":"Local/Regional","q":"A thoracic-limb orthopedic procedure is planned. Which regional technique is appropriate to desensitize this limb?","options":["Femoral nerve block","Brachial plexus block or RUMM (radial-ulnar-median-musculocutaneous) block","Lumbosacral epidural","Sciatic nerve block"],"answer":1,"explain":"The thoracic limb is anesthetized with a brachial plexus block (proximal) or a RUMM block (distal antebrachium and paw). Femoral and sciatic blocks and the lumbosacral epidural all target the pelvic limb, not the forelimb."},{"id":"nloc05","domain":"Local/Regional","q":"In a 4-kg cat you plan both an intercostal block and an incisional line block, each using bupivacaine. Why must the volumes from both blocks be summed against a single low maximum dose?","options":["Because bupivacaine is less potent, so a larger volume is needed and toxicity is unlikely","Because bupivacaine is more potent and more cardiotoxic than lidocaine, with a narrow margin, and cumulative dose from all sites drives toxicity","Because only the first block counts toward the maximum; the second contributes negligibly","Because bupivacaine is metabolized so quickly that timing between blocks, not total dose, determines safety"],"answer":1,"explain":"Bupivacaine is more potent and notably more cardiotoxic than lidocaine, with a narrower safety margin, so its maximum cumulative dose is low - especially in a small cat. Toxicity depends on total drug from ALL sources, so every block (plus any splash or line block) must be added together and kept under the limit."},{"id":"nloc06","domain":"Local/Regional","q":"A dog develops refractory ventricular arrhythmias and cardiovascular collapse minutes after a bupivacaine block, unresponsive to standard CPR. Which specific adjunctive therapy is indicated?","options":["Intravenous lipid emulsion, which acts as a lipid 'sink' and supports myocardial function alongside continued CPR","Flumazenil to reverse central nervous system depression","Naloxone to reverse the anesthetic's receptor binding","An intravenous lidocaine bolus to suppress the ventricular arrhythmias"],"answer":0,"explain":"Intravenous lipid emulsion ('lipid rescue') is the specific therapy for severe local anesthetic systemic toxicity, particularly bupivacaine - it sequesters the lipophilic drug and improves cardiac function during ongoing CPR. Flumazenil and naloxone reverse benzodiazepines and opioids respectively, and giving lidocaine would add another local anesthetic and worsen the toxicity."},{"id":"nloc07","domain":"Local/Regional","q":"Before incision during a canine castration, you inject lidocaine into each testis. This reduces intraoperative nociception primarily because the drug:","options":["Blocks the pudendal nerve as it exits the pelvis","Diffuses along the spermatic cord to block the testicular/spermatic plexus, reducing nociceptive input and inhalant requirement","Anesthetizes only the scrotal skin at the incision site","Is absorbed into the circulation to provide systemic analgesia"],"answer":1,"explain":"Intratesticular local anesthetic diffuses proximally along the spermatic cord and blocks the spermatic (testicular) plexus, blunting nociception from cord traction and lowering inhalant requirements - a simple, effective multimodal addition for castration. It does not act on the pudendal nerve, does not merely numb scrotal skin, and does not work through systemic absorption."},{"id":"ner01","domain":"Emergency/CPR","q":"The instant cardiopulmonary arrest is recognized in an anesthetized patient, RECOVER guidelines direct you to prioritize:","options":["Immediately beginning high-quality chest compressions and providing ventilation","Obtaining an ECG to identify the arrest rhythm before starting compressions","Securing IV access and drawing up epinephrine before starting compressions","Confirming the arrest with a 30-second pulse and Doppler check first"],"answer":0,"explain":"Basic Life Support — early, minimally-interrupted chest compressions with ventilation — is the highest priority and is started immediately on recognizing arrest. Diagnostics (ECG), drug preparation, IV access, and prolonged pulse checks must not delay compressions; a brief assessment (seconds) is all that precedes starting BLS."},{"id":"ner02","domain":"Emergency/CPR","q":"You are performing CPR on a 30 kg German Shepherd in lateral recumbency. For a dog of this typical (moderate) conformation, hand placement for external compressions should be:","options":["Directly over the heart at the point of maximal impulse, as done in cats and keel-chested dogs","Over the widest part of the lateral thoracic wall, using the thoracic-pump mechanism","Over the caudal sternum near the xiphoid process","Cranial to the forelimbs over the manubrium"],"answer":1,"explain":"In most dogs of moderate conformation, compressions are delivered over the widest portion of the lateral chest, driving forward flow via the thoracic-pump mechanism. The direct-over-the-heart (cardiac-pump) technique is reserved for cats, small dogs, and keel-chested (deep, narrow-chested) dogs — not a Shepherd. Compress one-third to one-half chest width with full recoil."},{"id":"ner03","domain":"Emergency/CPR","q":"RECOVER recommends rotating the person performing chest compressions every 2 minutes primarily because:","options":["The switch gives the ventricles two minutes to refill between cycles","It is the interval needed to alternate thoracic-pump and cardiac-pump techniques","It lowers the risk of rib fractures by sharing the workload","Rescuer fatigue degrades compression depth and rate within about two minutes, reducing perfusion"],"answer":3,"explain":"Compression quality (depth and rate) declines measurably with fatigue within about two minutes. Rotating compressors each cycle — timed with the rhythm check — sustains effective compressions and coronary/cerebral perfusion. Ventricular refilling occurs between individual compressions via full recoil, not during a rotation, and the rotation is not about switching techniques or preventing fractures."},{"id":"ner04","domain":"Emergency/CPR","q":"Midway through CPR of a dog, you pause for a rhythm check. The ECG shows a chaotic, irregular waveform with no organized QRS complexes and no palpable pulse. The most appropriate next action is to:","options":["Deliver a defibrillation shock — this is ventricular fibrillation","Resume compressions and give epinephrine, since this non-shockable rhythm needs a vasopressor","Give atropine, as this represents vagally-mediated asystole","Withhold any shock, because the absent pulse makes this pulseless electrical activity"],"answer":0,"explain":"A chaotic waveform with no organized QRS is ventricular fibrillation, a shockable rhythm — immediately defibrillate, then resume compressions. Asystole shows a flat line and PEA shows organized complexes without a pulse; neither is present here, so the epinephrine/atropine (non-shockable) pathway does not apply."},{"id":"ner05","domain":"Emergency/CPR","q":"Atropine provides the clearest benefit during CPR when the arrest is:","options":["Caused by ventricular fibrillation","Due to pulseless ventricular tachycardia","Precipitated by high vagal tone (ocular, visceral, or airway stimulation) or bradyarrhythmic in origin","Secondary to severe hyperkalemia"],"answer":2,"explain":"Atropine counters excessive vagal tone and is indicated for vagally mediated or bradyarrhythmic arrest (e.g., from ocular, visceral, or airway manipulation), given with epinephrine in asystole/PEA. VF and pulseless VT are treated with defibrillation, and severe hyperkalemia requires calcium and measures to shift/lower potassium — not atropine."},{"id":"ner06","domain":"Emergency/CPR","q":"During CPR of a cat, your capnograph reads a persistent ETCO2 of 6 mmHg despite ongoing compressions. Beyond confirming the tube is in the trachea, this value most usefully tells you that:","options":["The patient has already reached ROSC and compressions can stop","Pulmonary blood flow produced by the compressions is inadequate — improve compression quality","The arterial oxygen saturation is dangerously low","The anesthetic plane is too deep"],"answer":1,"explain":"ETCO2 during CPR reflects pulmonary blood flow generated by compressions. A persistently low value (well under ~10-15 mmHg) indicates poor perfusion/ineffective compressions — optimize hand position, depth, rate, and full recoil, and rotate the compressor. ROSC is signaled by an abrupt rise, not a low value; ETCO2 does not measure oxygen saturation or anesthetic depth."},{"id":"ner07","domain":"Emergency/CPR","q":"Which situation most appropriately justifies giving naloxone during resuscitation?","options":["A patient oversedated on dexmedetomidine","A patient with suspected bupivacaine (local anesthetic) cardiotoxicity","A patient with benzodiazepine-induced apnea","A patient that arrested after a high-dose pure mu-opioid, with opioid-induced respiratory depression suspected as a contributor"],"answer":3,"explain":"Naloxone specifically reverses opioids, so it is appropriate when an opioid contributed to respiratory depression and arrest. Reversal agents must be matched to the drug: atipamezole for alpha-2 agonists (dexmedetomidine), lipid emulsion for local anesthetic (bupivacaine) toxicity, and flumazenil for benzodiazepines."},{"id":"ner08","domain":"Emergency/CPR","q":"Partway through a laparotomy, an anesthetized dog on 2.5% isoflurane suddenly becomes profoundly bradycardic and hypotensive. Before targeting a specific cause, your single most important immediate action is to:","options":["Turn the vaporizer off (or well down) and ensure 100% oxygen with effective ventilation while calling for help","Increase the isoflurane to eliminate any chance of intraoperative awareness","Give an IV fluid bolus before touching the vaporizer","Administer epinephrine immediately"],"answer":0,"explain":"When an anesthetized patient acutely deteriorates, the highest-yield first action is to lighten the anesthetic — turn the vaporizer off or well down — while ensuring 100% oxygen, effective ventilation, and summoning help, then treat the specific cause. Increasing the inhalant worsens cardiovascular depression; a fluid bolus is a later step, not the priority; and epinephrine is premature in a patient who has not arrested."},{"id":"ner09","domain":"Emergency/CPR","q":"Which finding confirms return of spontaneous circulation (ROSC) rather than a transient or misleading sign?","options":["Organized electrical complexes on the ECG, whether or not a pulse is present","A single pulse felt during one pause in compressions","A sustained, palpable pulse with a spontaneous, perfusing cardiac rhythm","A rising ETCO2 measured while chest compressions continue"],"answer":2,"explain":"ROSC is the return of a sustained, spontaneous, palpable pulse with a perfusing cardiac rhythm, marking the transition to post-cardiac-arrest care. Organized ECG complexes without a pulse are pulseless electrical activity, not ROSC; a single felt pulse or a rising ETCO2 during ongoing compressions are suggestive but do not confirm sustained spontaneous circulation."},{"id":"ncalc01","domain":"Calculations","q":"A 4 kg cat receives ketamine at 5 mg/kg IM as part of premedication. The only vial available is 100 mg/mL, and you draw it up in a low-dead-space syringe. What volume is administered?","options":["0.1 mL","0.2 mL","0.4 mL","2.0 mL"],"answer":1,"explain":"Dose = 4 kg × 5 mg/kg = 20 mg. Volume = 20 mg ÷ 100 mg/mL = 0.2 mL. The 0.4 mL trap uses a 50 mg/mL concentration; 2.0 mL is a ten-fold slip (or a 10 mg/mL misread); 0.1 mL halves the dose. Small feline volumes demand an appropriately sized syringe and a double-check."},{"id":"ncalc02","domain":"Calculations","q":"A 66-lb dog under anesthesia is placed on crystalloids at 5 mL/kg/hr. What hourly infusion rate should the pump be set to?","options":["15 mL/hr","150 mL/hr","330 mL/hr","1500 mL/hr"],"answer":1,"explain":"Convert: 66 lb ÷ 2.2 = 30 kg. Rate = 30 kg × 5 mL/kg/hr = 150 mL/hr. The 330 mL/hr trap treats 66 lb as 66 kg; 15 and 1500 are decimal slips. Titrate to blood pressure and blood loss and avoid volume overload."},{"id":"ncalc03","domain":"Calculations","q":"A fentanyl order for a CRI is written as \"0.5 mg,\" but your infusion worksheet and syringe pump require the total dose entered in micrograms. How many micrograms should you enter?","options":["5 mcg","50 mcg","500 mcg","5000 mcg"],"answer":2,"explain":"1 mg = 1000 mcg, so 0.5 mg = 500 mcg. Every distractor here is a decimal-shift error (×10, ×100, ×10,000). With potent opioids like fentanyl a single misplaced decimal is a tenfold dosing error, so confirm mg vs mcg deliberately."},{"id":"ncalc04","domain":"Calculations","q":"You must run fentanyl at 5 mcg/kg/hr for a 20 kg dog. The stock is labeled \"250 mcg per 5 mL.\" What pump rate in mL/hr do you set?","options":["0.4 mL/hr","2 mL/hr","4 mL/hr","20 mL/hr"],"answer":1,"explain":"Derive the concentration first: 250 mcg ÷ 5 mL = 50 mcg/mL. Dose = 5 mcg/kg/hr × 20 kg = 100 mcg/hr. Rate = 100 mcg/hr ÷ 50 mcg/mL = 2 mL/hr. The 0.4 mL/hr trap divides by the total vial content (250) instead of the concentration; 4 mL/hr assumes 25 mcg/mL; 20 mL/hr is a tenfold slip. Always compute the actual mcg/mL before programming."},{"id":"ncalc05","domain":"Calculations","q":"A 10 kg dog becomes acutely hypotensive under anesthesia. You elect to give one-quarter of a 90 mL/kg canine shock dose as an initial rapid bolus and then reassess perfusion. What is that bolus volume?","options":["90 mL","225 mL","450 mL","900 mL"],"answer":1,"explain":"Full shock dose = 10 kg × 90 mL/kg = 900 mL. One-quarter = 900 ÷ 4 = 225 mL, given over ~15 minutes with reassessment between boluses. The 900 mL trap forgets to take the quarter; 450 mL takes half; 90 mL takes a tenth (or uses 9 mL/kg). Incremental boluses avoid overshooting into volume overload."},{"id":"ncalc06","domain":"Calculations","q":"A sedative is supplied as a 0.1% solution and is dosed at 0.2 mg/kg. For a 25 kg dog, what volume is required?","options":["0.5 mL","2.5 mL","5 mL","50 mL"],"answer":2,"explain":"A 0.1% solution = 1 mg/mL (1% = 10 mg/mL). Dose = 25 kg × 0.2 mg/kg = 5 mg. Volume = 5 mg ÷ 1 mg/mL = 5 mL. The 50 mL trap misreads 0.1% as 0.1 mg/mL; 0.5 mL misreads it as 10 mg/mL; 2.5 mL uses half the dose. Convert percent-strength to mg/mL before dividing."},{"id":"ncalc07","domain":"Calculations","q":"To compound a fentanyl CRI, you inject 5 mL of a 50 mcg/mL fentanyl solution into an empty bag and dilute to a final concentration of 2 mcg/mL. What final bag volume achieves this?","options":["62.5 mL","125 mL","250 mL","500 mL"],"answer":1,"explain":"Total drug = 5 mL × 50 mcg/mL = 250 mcg. Final volume = total drug ÷ desired concentration = 250 mcg ÷ 2 mcg/mL = 125 mL. The 500 mL trap multiplies by 2 instead of dividing; 250 mL forgets the divide-by-2 (uses 1 mcg/mL); 62.5 mL divides by 4. Verify the final concentration after compounding any CRI."},{"id":"ncalc08","domain":"Calculations","q":"A 110-lb dog is placed on a lidocaine CRI dosed at 50 mcg/kg/min. How many mcg/min are delivered?","options":["250 mcg/min","2500 mcg/min","5500 mcg/min","25000 mcg/min"],"answer":1,"explain":"Convert: 110 lb ÷ 2.2 = 50 kg. Delivery = 50 mcg/kg/min × 50 kg = 2500 mcg/min (2.5 mg/min). The 5500 mcg/min trap treats 110 lb as 110 kg; 250 and 25,000 are decimal slips. Note that lidocaine CRIs are commonly dosed per minute, unlike fentanyl per hour—read the time unit carefully."},{"id":"nsp01","domain":"Species-Specific","q":"Endotracheal intubation is technically difficult in rabbits. Which combination of anatomic features is the principal reason direct laryngoscopic visualization of the glottis is so challenging?","options":["A small oral opening, a small tongue, and a long narrow oropharynx with a caudally placed glottis","An elongated soft palate draping over the glottis, as in brachycephalic dogs","Complete cartilaginous tracheal rings that collapse under the laryngoscope","A small oral opening, a large tongue, and a long narrow oropharynx with a caudally placed glottis"],"answer":3,"explain":"Rabbits have a small mouth opening, a relatively LARGE tongue, and a long, narrow oropharynx with a caudally positioned glottis, so the larynx cannot be seen directly. Techniques include blind, endoscope-guided, or supraglottic-airway intubation, and the larynx is prone to spasm. A small tongue would make it easier (wrong), the elongated-soft-palate description belongs to brachycephalic dogs, and tracheal-ring collapse is not the issue."},{"id":"nsp02","domain":"Species-Specific","q":"A client asks how long to withhold food from their pet rabbit before a neuter. Compared with a dog, why is a prolonged preoperative fast specifically discouraged in this species?","options":["Rabbits cannot vomit, so a long fast adds little aspiration protection while risking GI stasis and hypoglycemia","Rabbits cannot vomit, so a long fast is still advised because it further lowers aspiration risk","A long fast empties the stomach and greatly raises the risk of gastric dilatation-volvulus","Fasting rapidly precipitates life-threatening hyperkalemia in lagomorphs"],"answer":0,"explain":"Rabbits are unable to vomit, so a prolonged fast does little to reduce aspiration risk yet readily triggers GI stasis (ileus) and hypoglycemia, both dangerous in this species. Only brief fasting to clear food from the mouth is used. The 'still fast them longer' option shares the true premise but reaches the wrong conclusion, and GDV and fasting-induced hyperkalemia are not lagomorph concerns."},{"id":"nsp03","domain":"Species-Specific","q":"A Greyhound is scheduled for anesthesia. Which statement most accurately captures the breed-related pharmacologic concern and its mechanism?","options":["High body fat sequesters lipophilic agents, prolonging their duration of action","Low body fat and reduced hepatic metabolism prolong recovery from redistribution-dependent thiobarbiturates","An MDR1 (ABCB1) mutation causes marked opioid and ivermectin sensitivity","A ryanodine-receptor defect makes all inhalants trigger malignant hyperthermia"],"answer":1,"explain":"Sighthounds (e.g., Greyhounds) have very low body fat and reduced hepatic microsomal metabolism (notably of thiobarbiturates), so drugs that terminate by redistribution into fat and rely on hepatic clearance produce markedly prolonged, rough recoveries; propofol/alfaxalone with careful titration are preferred. They do not have high fat, the MDR1 mutation is characteristic of herding breeds (e.g., Collies), and malignant hyperthermia is not a breed hallmark here."},{"id":"nsp04","domain":"Species-Specific","q":"A 550-kg adult horse is anesthetized in lateral recumbency for an orthopedic procedure. Equine anesthetic mortality far exceeds that of dogs and cats. Which cluster of factors best accounts for this elevated risk?","options":["A high incidence of vomiting and aspiration during induction and recovery","Induction-phase injuries during the attempt to stand, positioning-related myopathy/neuropathy, and cardiovascular strain","Recovery-phase injuries during the attempt to stand, positioning-related myopathy/neuropathy, and cardiovascular/ventilatory strain from their size","Extreme inhalant sensitivity causing rapid, unpredictable anesthetic overdose"],"answer":2,"explain":"Equine anesthetic mortality is driven largely by body mass: violent RECOVERIES (fractures/injury while trying to stand), positioning-related myopathy and neuropathy from prolonged recumbency on heavy muscle, and major cardiovascular/ventilatory compromise. The dangerous standing/injury phase is recovery, not induction (the near-twin trap). Horses cannot vomit, and they are not uniquely inhalant-oversensitive."},{"id":"nsp05","domain":"Species-Specific","q":"Avian patients ventilate very differently from mammals. Which description correctly characterizes the functional avian respiratory anatomy relevant to anesthesia?","options":["Air sacs plus rigid parabronchial lungs producing unidirectional, flow-through gas exchange, with no functional diaphragm","Air sacs plus expansile alveolar lungs producing bidirectional tidal gas exchange","A muscular diaphragm and highly compliant alveoli, essentially as in mammals","Blind-ended alveolar sacs ventilated by large bellows-like lung expansion"],"answer":0,"explain":"Birds have air sacs and rigid, non-expansile parabronchial lungs through which gas moves unidirectionally (flow-through) over two respiratory cycles, giving highly efficient exchange; they lack a functional diaphragm and depend on body-wall/keel movement to ventilate. Restraint that limits sternal/keel excursion rapidly causes hypoventilation. The lungs do not expand like mammalian alveoli, and airflow is not bidirectional/tidal."},{"id":"nsp06","domain":"Species-Specific","q":"A markedly obese cat (body condition score 9/10) is anesthetized in dorsal recumbency for imaging. Which physiologic and dosing concern is the greatest anesthetic risk related specifically to the obesity?","options":["Increased functional residual capacity with hypoventilation, plus overdosing if drugs are dosed to total body weight","Reduced functional residual capacity with hypoventilation/atelectasis, plus overdosing if drugs are dosed to total body weight","Increased chest-wall compliance producing dangerously large spontaneous tidal volumes","Rapid, unpredictable redistribution that causes anesthetic underdosing"],"answer":1,"explain":"Obesity REDUCES functional residual capacity and chest-wall compliance (promoting hypoventilation and atelectasis, worsened by dorsal recumbency), and many drugs must be dosed to LEAN body weight to avoid overdose because fat is relatively underperfused. FRC is decreased (not increased), chest-wall compliance falls, and the risk is over-, not under-, dosing."},{"id":"nsp07","domain":"Species-Specific","q":"Neonatal and pediatric patients lose body heat rapidly under anesthesia. Which pairing of factors is the principal reason?","options":["A low surface-area-to-body-mass ratio together with immature thermoregulation","A very low metabolic rate that generates almost no metabolic heat","A high surface-area-to-body-mass ratio together with immature central thermoregulation and scant insulating fat","Excessive body-fat insulation driving compensatory peripheral vasodilation"],"answer":2,"explain":"Neonates/pediatrics have a HIGH surface-area-to-mass ratio, minimal insulating body fat, and immature hypothalamic thermoregulation, so they shed heat quickly and cannot compensate; active warming, warmed fluids, and minimizing exposure are essential (plus glucose monitoring). A low SA:mass ratio would protect against heat loss (wrong), and neonates actually have a HIGH metabolic rate, not a low one."},{"id":"ncx01","domain":"Complications","q":"An anesthetized dog on a circle system shows ETCO2 climbing from 40 to 68 mmHg, a rising esophageal temperature, and sinus tachycardia over 15 minutes. Which is the most appropriate initial concern and action?","options":["Shivering from hypothermia — begin active warming","A hypermetabolic state (e.g., malignant hyperthermia) or CO2 rebreathing/hypoventilation — check ventilation and the CO2 absorbent and consider stopping triggering agents","A light plane alone — turn the vaporizer up","Anaphylaxis — give an antihistamine and stop the fluids"],"answer":1,"explain":"Rising ETCO2 with hyperthermia and tachycardia points to a hypermetabolic crisis (e.g., malignant hyperthermia) or severe hypoventilation/rebreathing from an exhausted absorbent or stuck valve. Verify ventilation and the CO2 absorbent, discontinue triggering agents, cool actively, and treat. Temperature is rising (not hypothermia); a light plane alone would not raise temperature, and increasing a volatile could worsen MH; anaphylaxis presents with hypotension, edema, and bronchospasm."},{"id":"ncx02","domain":"Complications","q":"After confirming an excessive anesthetic plane in a hypotensive patient, the most appropriate ordered response is to:","options":["Lighten the anesthetic depth, give a crystalloid bolus, then add an inotrope such as dobutamine if pressure stays low","Start a phenylephrine infusion before reducing the anesthetic depth","Give atropine to raise the blood pressure","Administer furosemide to improve renal perfusion"],"answer":0,"explain":"Excessive inhalant depth is the leading cause of anesthetic hypotension, so first reduce the vaporizer, then give a crystalloid bolus; if pressure remains low, add an inotrope (dobutamine) or an appropriate vasopressor. Starting a vasopressor before lightening depth only masks the cause; atropine raises heart rate but not directly blood pressure; furosemide causes diuresis and would worsen hypotension."},{"id":"ncx03","domain":"Complications","q":"A 6-year-old dog receiving a dexmedetomidine CRI has a heart rate of 42 bpm, pink mucous membranes, and a Doppler blood pressure of 160 mmHg. The most appropriate management of the bradycardia is to:","options":["Give atropine immediately to normalize the heart rate","Administer glycopyrrolate to raise the heart rate","Reduce or stop the dexmedetomidine and reassess, since the bradycardia is a baroreflex response to drug-induced vasoconstriction","Give a rapid crystalloid bolus to correct the bradycardia"],"answer":2,"explain":"The bradycardia is a baroreflex response to alpha-2-induced vasoconstriction and hypertension (BP 160), so the correct step is to reduce or stop the dexmedetomidine and reassess. Giving an anticholinergic (atropine or glycopyrrolate) while afterload is high increases myocardial work and can cause a dangerous hypertensive surge; a fluid bolus does not address a reflex-mediated bradycardia."},{"id":"ncx04","domain":"Complications","q":"Which set of measures best reduces the risk of regurgitation and subsequent aspiration during anesthesia?","options":["Fasting for at least 24 hours to guarantee an empty stomach","Appropriate (not prolonged) fasting, a properly inflated endotracheal cuff, and head positioning that lets any regurgitant drain outward","Positioning in dorsal recumbency immediately after induction","Extubating while still deeply anesthetized to prevent coughing"],"answer":1,"explain":"Aspiration prevention combines appropriate (not excessive) fasting, a properly inflated ET cuff, head-down positioning and suctioning if regurgitation occurs, and delayed extubation until protective airway reflexes return. Prolonged 24-hour fasting can increase gastric acidity and reflux; dorsal recumbency and deep-plane extubation both increase aspiration risk."},{"id":"ncx05","domain":"Complications","q":"Two dogs are recovering from anesthesia and both are breathing spontaneously: a healthy Labrador that has begun to swallow and chew the tube, and a brachycephalic Bulldog at the same stage. What is the most appropriate extubation approach?","options":["Extubate both as soon as spontaneous breathing resumes","Extubate both the instant any voluntary limb movement appears","Extubate both immediately when the procedure ends to speed recovery","Extubate the healthy Labrador once it swallows and regains airway protection, but keep the brachycephalic Bulldog intubated as long as it tolerates the tube"],"answer":3,"explain":"Extubate when the patient swallows and can protect its airway. The healthy Labrador meets that threshold; the brachycephalic Bulldog is an airway/aspiration-risk patient and should stay intubated as long as it tolerates the tube. Extubating at the return of breathing or of limb movement, or right when surgery ends, is premature and risks obstruction or aspiration."},{"id":"ncx06","domain":"Complications","q":"An anesthetized dog has an ETCO2 of 62 mmHg with a slow, shallow spontaneous breathing pattern and a normal SpO2. The most appropriate management is to:","options":["Provide assisted or controlled ventilation to normalize CO2, and reassess the anesthetic depth","Give doxapram to stimulate breathing as the first-line treatment","Raise the fresh gas oxygen flow to wash CO2 out of the alveoli","Deepen the anesthetic plane to relax the patient"],"answer":0,"explain":"Anesthetic-induced hypoventilation (rising ETCO2) is corrected by assisting or controlling ventilation to normalize CO2, while reassessing anesthetic depth and confirming a patent airway. Doxapram is not first-line, increasing fresh gas flow does not fix patient hypoventilation, and deepening the plane worsens respiratory depression."},{"id":"ncx07","domain":"Complications","q":"Midway through a procedure on a draped, out-of-view patient, the pulse oximeter signal and the ETCO2 waveform both disappear at the same moment. Your first action should be to:","options":["Replace the pulse oximeter probe and check the capnograph tubing first","Assume motion artifact from the surgeon and keep watching","Immediately assess the patient — check for a pulse, airway disconnection, and chest movement — rather than assume both monitors failed at once","Deepen the anesthesia, since the patient is probably too light"],"answer":2,"explain":"Simultaneous loss of both SpO2 and ETCO2 demands immediate patient assessment: rule out cardiac arrest, airway disconnection or obstruction, esophageal intubation, or a severe low-perfusion state before assuming equipment failure. Troubleshooting monitors first, dismissing it as artifact, or deepening anesthesia could fatally delay recognition of arrest."},{"id":"ncx08","domain":"Complications","q":"Which is the safest and most effective approach to intraoperative hypothermia?","options":["An electric heating pad placed in direct contact with the skin","Forced warm-air blankets, warmed IV and lavage fluids, and minimizing surface exposure and wet fur","Rapidly infusing room-temperature crystalloid fluids","Raising the oxygen flow rate to warm the inspired gas"],"answer":1,"explain":"Active warming — forced warm-air blankets, warmed IV and lavage fluids, insulation, and limiting surface exposure and wet fur — safely counteracts hypothermia, which prolongs recovery and impairs coagulation and drug clearance. Electric pads in direct skin contact risk thermal burns in anesthetized, poorly perfused patients; room-temperature fluids and increased gas flow do not effectively warm the patient."},{"id":"nvf01","domain":"Ventilation/Fluids","q":"Which single set of circumstances constitutes a correct, complete list of standard indications for instituting controlled (positive-pressure) ventilation?","options":["Significant hypoventilation, apnea, open-chest (thoracotomy) surgery, and neuromuscular blockade","Significant hyperventilation, apnea, open-chest surgery, and neuromuscular blockade","Any time end-tidal CO2 drops below 20 mmHg","Only when SpO2 stays above 95% breathing room air"],"answer":0,"explain":"Controlled/positive-pressure ventilation is indicated when spontaneous ventilation is inadequate or abolished: significant hypoventilation (hypercapnia), apnea, open-chest surgery (loss of negative intrapleural pressure collapses the lungs), and neuromuscular blockade (paralyzed respiratory muscles). Hyperventilation is not an indication to take over ventilation, a low ETCO2 reflects over-ventilation, and an adequate SpO2 on room air argues against needing support."},{"id":"nvf02","domain":"Ventilation/Fluids","q":"You are choosing a routine intraoperative fluid for a healthy 15-kg dog undergoing an elective mass removal, and you want a balanced isotonic crystalloid whose electrolyte profile approximates plasma and that contains a bicarbonate precursor. Which fluid fits?","options":["0.9% sodium chloride","5% dextrose in water (D5W)","7.2% hypertonic saline","Lactated Ringer's solution"],"answer":3,"explain":"Lactated Ringer's (like Plasma-Lyte/Normosol) is a BALANCED isotonic replacement crystalloid: electrolytes near plasma plus a buffer (lactate, a bicarbonate precursor), ideal for routine intraoperative use. 0.9% NaCl is isotonic but UNbalanced (supraphysiologic chloride, no buffer, risking hyperchloremic acidosis), D5W is essentially free water, and 7.2% saline is hypertonic for small-volume resuscitation."},{"id":"nvf03","domain":"Ventilation/Fluids","q":"Hypertonic saline (e.g., 7.2%) has a specific hemodynamic role in shock resuscitation. Which statement most precisely describes its mechanism AND its limitation?","options":["It osmotically shifts interstitial/intracellular water into the vasculature for rapid small-volume expansion, but the effect is transient and must be followed by crystalloids","It osmotically shifts water into the vasculature and, because of its high sodium, provides sustained long-lasting volume expansion","It expands volume by acting as a large-molecular-weight synthetic colloid","It corrects metabolic acidosis via a lactate/bicarbonate buffer it contains"],"answer":0,"explain":"Hypertonic saline creates a steep osmotic gradient that pulls interstitial and intracellular water into the intravascular space, giving rapid resuscitation with a small infused volume (useful in shock and head trauma). The catch is that the effect is TRANSIENT as sodium redistributes, so it must be followed by isotonic crystalloids (± colloid). It is not a colloid and contains no buffer, so the 'sustained' and 'corrects acidosis' options are wrong."},{"id":"nvf04","domain":"Ventilation/Fluids","q":"A 6-kg cat with chronic kidney disease and a heart murmur is anesthetized for dental work, and the pump is set to a high 'traditional' rate of 10 mL/kg/hr. Why is this patient at particular risk from that rate?","options":["Young, healthy patients are the ones most prone to fluid-overload edema, so the concern here is minimal","Compromised cardiac and renal reserve makes it prone to volume overload and pulmonary edema","Rapid redistribution of the fluid to tissues will cause rebound dehydration","The infusion will cause severe hypernatremia and hyperchloremia in this patient"],"answer":1,"explain":"Patients with cardiac or renal disease have limited ability to handle a volume load, so aggressive rates can precipitate volume overload and pulmonary edema; this cat with CKD and a murmur is exactly that patient. Modern guidance favors conservative rates (~3-5 mL/kg/hr) titrated to blood pressure and perfusion. Healthy young patients tolerate fluids better (so that option is backwards), and the danger is overload/edema, not rebound dehydration or an electrolyte derangement."},{"id":"nvf05","domain":"Ventilation/Fluids","q":"When manually delivering a breath ('bagging') to an anesthetized healthy dog on a rebreathing circuit, which technique is correct?","options":["Deliver rapid shallow breaths at 40-60/min to maximize minute oxygen delivery","Give a smooth breath to a peak of ~10-15 cmH2O, but leave the pop-off valve closed between breaths to preserve circuit volume","Give a smooth breath to a peak of ~10-15 cmH2O at a physiologic rate while watching the manometer, then reopen the pop-off valve","Inflate to 30-40 cmH2O each breath to fully recruit the lungs"],"answer":2,"explain":"Deliver a smooth breath to a normal tidal volume/peak pressure (~10-15 cmH2O in healthy lungs) at a physiologic rate, watching chest rise and the manometer, THEN immediately reopen the pop-off (APL) valve. Leaving the pop-off closed is the classic lethal error: pressure builds, causing barotrauma and impaired venous return/cardiac arrest. Rapid shallow breaths are inefficient (dead-space ventilation), and 30-40 cmH2O routinely risks barotrauma."},{"id":"nvf06","domain":"Ventilation/Fluids","q":"During mechanical ventilation of a dog, the airway-pressure manometer is climbing toward 35 cmH2O with each delivered breath. Monitoring and limiting peak inspiratory pressure matters primarily to prevent which complication?","options":["Barotrauma/volutrauma (e.g., pneumothorax, lung injury) and impaired venous return","Hypoxemia from an inadequate delivered tidal volume","Miscalculation of the required fresh-gas flow rate","An inability to judge anesthetic depth"],"answer":0,"explain":"The reason to watch and cap peak inspiratory pressure is to avoid delivering excessive airway pressure/volume, which causes barotrauma/volutrauma (alveolar rupture, pneumothorax, lung injury) and reduces venous return and cardiac output. A manometer rising toward 35 cmH2O is a warning to reduce delivered volume/pressure. Low, not high, pressures would risk inadequate ventilation, and PIP is unrelated to fresh-gas-flow calculation or depth assessment."},{"id":"nap01","domain":"Anesthetic Principles","q":"Which patient is most correctly classified as ASA physical status I?","options":["A healthy 2-year-old cat with normal history, exam, and bloodwork presenting for an elective neuter","A 2-year-old cat with mild, well-controlled asthma, otherwise thriving, presenting for an elective neuter","A 6-year-old cat with early, compensated chronic kidney disease presenting for a dental","A geriatric cat that is bright and active but has a grade II/VI heart murmur of undetermined cause"],"answer":0,"explain":"ASA I is a normal, healthy patient with NO identifiable systemic disease (a young animal with normal history, exam, and bloodwork for an elective procedure). Any mild systemic disease, even well-controlled asthma, early compensated kidney disease, or an undetermined heart murmur, moves the patient to ASA II. The trap is that 'well-controlled' or 'bright and active' still counts as disease, so those are ASA II, not I."},{"id":"nap02","domain":"Anesthetic Principles","q":"A 12-year-old, 30-kg dog is scheduled for a mass removal, and your clinic performs a full preanesthetic workup (history, physical exam, and bloodwork). Which statement best captures the primary purpose of doing this?","options":["To detect patient-specific risk factors and then apply the clinic's single standardized protocol to every patient","To calculate the patient's exact minimum alveolar concentration ahead of time","To satisfy legal and insurance documentation requirements","To detect patient-specific risk factors and customize the anesthetic plan to that individual"],"answer":3,"explain":"The core purpose of preanesthetic evaluation is to uncover conditions (cardiac, renal, hepatic, hydration, age-related) that change anesthetic risk and drug selection so the plan can be INDIVIDUALIZED and complications anticipated. Identifying risks only to then apply one identical protocol to everyone defeats the purpose (the near-twin trap). A workup does not yield a numeric MAC, and documentation, while real, is not the primary aim."},{"id":"nap03","domain":"Anesthetic Principles","q":"The classic (Guedel) four stages of general anesthesia describe a physiologic progression. Which statement correctly characterizes that progression and its endpoint?","options":["Progressive CNS depression through Stage II excitement and Stage III surgical anesthesia, ending in Stage IV emergence/recovery","Progressive CNS depression through Stage II excitement and Stage III surgical anesthesia, ending in Stage IV medullary depression (anesthetic overdose)","The procedural sequence of premedication, induction, maintenance, and recovery","Analgesia, then surgical anesthesia, then recovery, then extubation"],"answer":1,"explain":"The Guedel stages track deepening CNS depression: Stage I (analgesia/disorientation), Stage II (involuntary EXCITEMENT/delirium), Stage III (surgical anesthesia, subdivided into planes), and Stage IV (medullary depression = anesthetic OVERDOSE with cardiorespiratory collapse). The endpoint is overdose, not recovery/emergence (the near-twin trap). These physiologic depth stages are distinct from the procedural phases premed→induction→maintenance→recovery."},{"id":"nap04","domain":"Anesthetic Principles","q":"A healthy dog premedicated with an opioid and sedative is being induced with IV propofol. Which approach best minimizes the risks associated with Stage II (the involuntary excitement stage)?","options":["Adequate premedication plus a deliberately slow, gradual IV induction to ease gently through Stage II","Withholding premedication so the excitement stage can be recognized and monitored","Mask induction with inhalant in all patients to titrate depth slowly","Adequate premedication plus a rapid, smooth IV induction to move quickly through Stage II"],"answer":3,"explain":"Stage II features involuntary excitement, exaggerated reflexes, and risk of injury/arrhythmia, so the goal is to spend as LITTLE time in it as possible. Good premedication (calming the patient, smoothing induction) plus a RAPID, smooth IV induction achieves that. A slow induction prolongs Stage II (the trap), omitting premedication worsens excitement, and mask inductions notoriously drag the patient through a prolonged excitement phase."},{"id":"nap05","domain":"Anesthetic Principles","q":"Which description most precisely defines Stage III (surgical anesthesia)?","options":["Unconsciousness with progressive, plane-dependent loss of reflexes and muscle relaxation adequate for surgery","Unconsciousness with abrupt, complete loss of all reflexes and flaccid paralysis from the outset","Involuntary excitement with breath-holding and exaggerated reflexes","Medullary depression with cardiovascular and respiratory collapse"],"answer":0,"explain":"Stage III (surgical anesthesia) is unconsciousness with muscle relaxation and analgesia sufficient for surgery, subdivided into PLANES defined by the progressive, graded loss of reflexes and eye/pupil changes, not an abrupt, all-at-once loss. Involuntary excitement with exaggerated reflexes is Stage II, and medullary/cardiorespiratory collapse is Stage IV (overdose). The 'abrupt, complete' wording is the trap."},{"id":"nap06","domain":"Anesthetic Principles","q":"A 25-kg dog under isoflurane is being assessed for depth before an abdominal procedure. Which combination of ocular signs most reliably indicates an adequate surgical plane with an inhalant?","options":["Central eye position with a brisk palpebral reflex","Eye rotated dorsomedially with a diminished palpebral reflex","Eye rotated ventromedially with a diminished palpebral reflex","Central, fixed eye with a widely dilated pupil and absent reflexes"],"answer":2,"explain":"With most inhalants, an adequate surgical plane is signaled by ventromedial ('rolled-down') rotation of the globe and a diminished palpebral reflex. A central eye with a brisk palpebral reflex indicates a light plane, while a central, fixed eye with a dilated pupil warns of an excessively deep plane. The rotation is ventromedial, not dorsomedial (the trap). Note that dissociatives like ketamine keep the eyes central and open, so this sign does not apply to them."},{"id":"nap07","domain":"Anesthetic Principles","q":"Despite advances in monitoring technology, which 'monitor' is considered the single most valuable during general anesthesia, and why?","options":["A multiparameter monitor with ECG and invasive blood pressure, because it captures the most numeric data continuously","Capnography, because end-tidal CO2 is the earliest indicator of every anesthetic complication","Pulse oximetry, because oxygen saturation is the definitive measure of adequate ventilation","A trained, attentive anesthetist, because continuous human observation integrates all findings and enables immediate intervention"],"answer":3,"explain":"Instruments supplement but never replace a vigilant, trained anesthetist who continuously observes the patient, integrates all monitor data in context, and intervenes immediately, the foundation of anesthetic safety. A multiparameter monitor provides data but not clinical judgment, capnography is valuable but not the earliest sign of EVERY problem, and pulse oximetry reflects oxygenation, not ventilation (a common conceptual error)."},{"id":"fp01","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"A dog premedicated with acepromazine becomes hypotensive after induction. Which mechanism most directly explains this?","options":["Peripheral alpha-2 adrenergic antagonism causing vasodilation","Muscarinic (anticholinergic) receptor blockade","Peripheral alpha-1 adrenergic antagonism causing vasodilation and reduced systemic vascular resistance","Direct beta-1 negative inotropy"],"answer":2,"explain":"Acepromazine antagonizes peripheral alpha-1 receptors, producing vasodilation and a fall in systemic vascular resistance; combined with anesthetic-induced depression this can cause clinically significant hypotension, so it is avoided in unstable patients. It is not an alpha-2 or muscarinic antagonist and does not act via direct beta-1 negative inotropy."},{"id":"fp02","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"During a painful exploratory laparotomy with rapidly fluctuating surgical stimulation, you need an analgesic you can titrate minute-to-minute. Which is most appropriate as an intraoperative analgesic infusion?","options":["A butorphanol CRI","A fentanyl CRI","A buprenorphine bolus","A maropitant CRI"],"answer":1,"explain":"Fentanyl is a potent, short-acting pure mu-agonist with rapid onset and offset, ideal for a titratable intraoperative CRI during painful visceral surgery, with minimal cardiovascular depression aside from vagally-mediated bradycardia. Butorphanol is a weak analgesic with a ceiling, buprenorphine is slow-onset and long-acting (not titratable), and maropitant is only an adjunct."},{"id":"fp03","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"A cat with hypertrophic cardiomyopathy needs sedation. Which choice is generally the LEAST appropriate?","options":["Butorphanol","Midazolam","Ketamine, because it raises heart rate, contractility, and myocardial oxygen demand and worsens dynamic outflow obstruction","A low-dose pure mu-opioid with careful monitoring"],"answer":2,"explain":"Ketamine increases heart rate, contractility, and myocardial oxygen demand and worsens dynamic left ventricular outflow obstruction in HCM cats, so it is generally avoided. Opioid-based protocols with a benzodiazepine such as midazolam are cardiovascularly sparing and preferred in these patients."},{"id":"fp04","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"A brachycephalic dog at high aspiration risk needs a potent premedication opioid, and you choose methadone over morphine. Which pairing of properties justifies this choice?","options":["It causes less vomiting than morphine and adds NMDA-receptor agonism","It is a partial mu-agonist with a ceiling effect, making it inherently safer","It directly blocks the chemoreceptor trigger zone to prevent vomiting","It causes less vomiting than morphine and adds NMDA-receptor antagonism"],"answer":3,"explain":"Methadone tends to cause less nausea and vomiting than morphine (valuable when aspiration is a concern) and adds analgesia through NMDA-receptor ANTAGONISM. It is a full mu-agonist (not a partial agonist with a ceiling), and NMDA agonism would be counterproductive; its antiemetic edge is not due to directly blocking the CRTZ."},{"id":"fp05","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"A patient received both midazolam and hydromorphone and is over-sedate. You wish to reverse ONLY the benzodiazepine component. Which agent is appropriate?","options":["Naloxone","Atipamezole","Flumazenil","Neostigmine"],"answer":2,"explain":"Flumazenil is the specific benzodiazepine antagonist and reverses midazolam without affecting the opioid. Naloxone would reverse the hydromorphone instead, atipamezole reverses alpha-2 agonists, and neostigmine reverses non-depolarizing neuromuscular blockers - none of which selectively targets the benzodiazepine."},{"id":"fp06","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"You add a mu-agonist opioid to a dog's premedication. Beyond patient comfort, what is the principal anesthetic advantage during maintenance?","options":["Analgesia but with a MAC-increasing effect that raises inhalant requirement","Pre-emptive analgesia with a MAC-sparing effect that lowers inhalant requirement","Reliable skeletal muscle relaxation for surgical access","Sufficient hypnosis and amnesia to permit surgery without an inhalant"],"answer":1,"explain":"Mu-agonist opioids provide pre-emptive analgesia and are MAC-sparing, reducing the inhalant concentration needed and improving cardiovascular stability. They increase, not decrease, anesthetic economy; they do not supply skeletal muscle relaxation, and alone they do not produce surgical hypnosis/amnesia."},{"id":"fp07","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"Alfaxalone is titrated slowly to effect at induction chiefly to avoid which rate-dependent adverse effects?","options":["Rate-dependent apnea accompanied by cardiovascular stimulation and hypertension","Precipitation of the steroid within the vein on rapid injection","Rate-dependent apnea and cardiovascular (hypotensive) depression","A requirement for a slow 10-minute infusion for any effect to occur"],"answer":2,"explain":"Like propofol, alfaxalone can cause dose- and rate-dependent apnea and cardiovascular depression (hypotension) if given too quickly, so it is titrated slowly to effect. It does not cause cardiovascular stimulation, does not precipitate in the vein, and is effective on titrated bolus rather than needing a prolonged infusion."},{"id":"fp08","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"A dog maintained on a fentanyl CRI for 8 hours recovers far more slowly than a similar dog given a 30-minute infusion. The best explanation is:","options":["Fentanyl is cleared only by the kidneys, which fail over time","An active hepatic metabolite accumulates and prolongs the effect","Prolonged infusion converts fentanyl into a long-acting metabolite in the liver","Progressive tissue accumulation lengthens fentanyl's context-sensitive half-time as infusion duration increases"],"answer":3,"explain":"Fentanyl accumulates in peripheral tissues during long infusions, so its context-sensitive half-time lengthens and plasma levels fall more slowly when the infusion stops, prolonging recovery relative to a brief infusion. Fentanyl is hepatically metabolized without a clinically important active metabolite, so renal clearance or an accumulating active metabolite does not explain it."},{"id":"fphy01","domain":"Physiology","q":"A dog's stroke volume falls 25% but its heart rate rises enough to keep cardiac output constant. Which statement about this compensation is most accurate?","options":["It follows CO = HR × SV, but the tachycardia raises myocardial oxygen demand and shortens diastolic filling and coronary perfusion time, so it is limited","It follows MAP = CO × SVR, so blood pressure is guaranteed to remain normal","Because CO = HR ÷ SV, a higher heart rate mathematically lowers cardiac output","Heart rate and stroke volume are independent, so cardiac output cannot be preserved this way"],"answer":0,"explain":"Cardiac output = heart rate × stroke volume, so a rise in rate can offset a fall in stroke volume to keep output constant. But the compensation is limited: tachycardia increases myocardial oxygen demand while shortening diastole, reducing both filling time (eventually lowering stroke volume further) and coronary perfusion time. Output is a product, not a quotient, of HR and SV, and a preserved output does not guarantee a normal pressure, which also depends on SVR."},{"id":"fphy02","domain":"Physiology","q":"A dog with immune-mediated hemolytic anemia (PCV 12%) is anesthetized with SpO2 100% and PaO2 480 mmHg on oxygen, yet its lactate is rising, suggesting inadequate tissue oxygen delivery. Which explanation is most accurate?","options":["A normal SpO2 guarantees adequate oxygen delivery regardless of hemoglobin","The high PaO2 means dissolved oxygen alone is meeting tissue demand","Because nearly all oxygen is hemoglobin-bound, the low hemoglobin markedly lowers arterial oxygen content and delivery despite the high PaO2/SpO2","The low hemoglobin lowers the PaO2, which is the real cause of poor delivery"],"answer":2,"explain":"Arterial oxygen content ≈ (1.34 × Hb × SaO2) + (0.003 × PaO2) and is dominated by hemoglobin-bound oxygen. With a PCV of 12% the hemoglobin — and thus content and delivery (DO2 = CO × CaO2) — is very low even though SaO2 and PaO2 are maximal, so tissues are oxygen-starved (rising lactate). A normal SpO2 only reflects saturation of the little hemoglobin present, dissolved O2 is trivial, and hemoglobin concentration does not set PaO2."},{"id":"fphy03","domain":"Physiology","q":"Aggressive controlled ventilation lowers a dog's PaCO2 to 22 mmHg. Which primary acid-base change occurs, and which physiologic consequence accompanies it?","options":["Respiratory acidosis; the lowered pH causes cerebral vasodilation","Respiratory alkalosis; the raised pH causes cerebral vasoconstriction and a leftward oxyhemoglobin shift","Metabolic alkalosis from bicarbonate retention","Respiratory alkalosis; the raised pH increases ionized calcium and shifts the curve rightward"],"answer":1,"explain":"Hyperventilation lowers PaCO2 (hypocapnia), raising pH: acute respiratory alkalosis. Consequences include cerebral vasoconstriction (reduced CBF — sometimes used briefly to lower ICP), a leftward shift of the oxyhemoglobin curve (impaired tissue offloading), and a fall in ionized calcium from increased protein binding. It is a respiratory, not metabolic, process, and alkalosis lowers — not raises — ionized calcium. Normocapnia is the usual target."},{"id":"fphy04","domain":"Physiology","q":"A small dog on a long procedure becomes hypothermic (34.5°C) and develops diffuse capillary oozing at the surgical site, yet a platelet count and coagulation panel (run at 37°C in the lab) are normal. What best explains the bleeding?","options":["Cold-induced vasodilation at the surgical site raises local blood flow and causes the oozing","Reduced blood viscosity at low temperature promotes the bleeding","Impaired clotting enzymes with fully preserved platelet function","Hypothermia impairs both the enzymatic clotting cascade and platelet function in vivo, while lab assays warmed to 37°C read normal"],"answer":3,"explain":"Hypothermia causes a functional coagulopathy by slowing the temperature-dependent enzymatic clotting cascade AND impairing platelet activation/adhesion. Because standard coagulation assays are warmed to 37°C, they can read normal while the patient bleeds at 34.5°C — so the fix is active rewarming, not more testing. Cold causes vasoconstriction (not vasodilation), viscosity actually rises when cold, and the coagulopathy involves both enzymes and platelets, not enzymes alone."},{"id":"fphy05","domain":"Physiology","q":"In a patient with chronic CO2 retention, why can administering high-flow oxygen paradoxically worsen hypoventilation and drive PaCO2 even higher?","options":["Chronic hypercapnia blunts the central CO2 response, so ventilation relies on the hypoxic drive; correcting the hypoxemia with high-flow O2 removes that stimulus and reduces ventilation","Central chemoreceptors become hypersensitive to CO2, and oxygen directly suppresses them","Supplemental oxygen normally stimulates the hypoxic drive, thereby increasing ventilation","The patient depends on a high PaCO2 itself to trigger each breath, which oxygen removes"],"answer":0,"explain":"In chronic CO2 retention the central chemoreceptor response to CO2 is blunted (reset), so a greater share of respiratory drive comes from the peripheral hypoxic drive (low PaO2 sensed by the carotid and aortic bodies). High-flow oxygen abolishes that hypoxemic stimulus, reducing ventilation and allowing PaCO2 to climb further, so oxygen is titrated to a modest target with ventilation monitoring. These patients are not driven by high CO2 itself, their central CO2 sensitivity is decreased rather than increased, and oxygen does not stimulate ventilation here."},{"id":"feq01","domain":"Equipment","q":"A technician is tempted to skip the pre-anesthetic low-pressure leak test because the machine ran fine an hour ago. The strongest reason not to skip it is that the test specifically confirms:","options":["The vaporizer output concentration is accurately calibrated","The breathing system is intact and holds pressure, so anesthetic/oxygen delivery and positive-pressure ventilation will be reliable","The CO2 absorbent is fresh and chemically active","The oxygen cylinder contains adequate pressure and volume"],"answer":1,"explain":"The low-pressure leak test confirms the breathing system is intact and holds pressure, so oxygen/anesthetic delivery and positive-pressure ventilation are reliable and waste-gas leakage is minimal - reason enough never to skip it, since a connection can loosen between cases. It does not calibrate vaporizer output, verify absorbent freshness, or check cylinder supply; those are separate checks."},{"id":"feq02","domain":"Equipment","q":"For a 35 kg Labrador, the most appropriate breathing system - and the reason - is:","options":["A non-rebreathing Bain circuit, to minimize resistance","A rebreathing (circle) system, which handles large tidal volumes at low fresh gas flow while conserving heat and moisture","An Ayre's T-piece with high fresh gas flow","A Jackson-Rees modified T-piece"],"answer":1,"explain":"A 35 kg dog is best managed on a rebreathing (circle) system, which handles large tidal volumes efficiently at low fresh gas flow and conserves heat and humidity. Non-rebreathing systems (Bain, Ayre's T-piece, Jackson-Rees) are reserved for small patients (~<7 kg) because they demand high fresh gas flows and conserve little heat."},{"id":"feq03","domain":"Equipment","q":"On a circle system, the capnograph's inspired baseline is riding at 7 mmHg instead of returning to zero, and you have already ruled out a water-clogged sampling line. The fault is now most likely located in:","options":["Condensed water occluding the capnograph sampling line","The CO2 absorbent (exhausted) or a malfunctioning unidirectional valve, allowing CO2 rebreathing","A cracked or leaking endotracheal tube cuff","A miscalibrated pulse oximeter"],"answer":1,"explain":"An inspired baseline that fails to return to zero means CO2 rebreathing; with a sampling-line clog already excluded, the fault lies in the CO2 absorbent (exhausted) or a malfunctioning unidirectional valve. A leaking cuff produces a low or leaky capnogram, not a raised baseline, and the pulse oximeter is an unrelated device."},{"id":"feq04","domain":"Equipment","q":"The single most important reason to reopen the pop-off (APL) valve the instant a manual breath is finished is to:","options":["Let the reservoir bag refill with fresh gas for the next breath","Prevent continued pressure buildup in the circuit and lungs, which causes barotrauma and impairs venous return","Restore the correct fresh gas flow rate through the flowmeter","Allow exhaled CO2 to reach the soda-lime absorbent"],"answer":1,"explain":"Leaving the pop-off closed after a manual breath lets circuit and airway pressure keep climbing, causing barotrauma and impairing venous return - the critical, life-threatening reason to reopen it immediately. Refilling the bag is a real but non-critical function; the pop-off does not set fresh gas flow, and exhaled CO2 reaches the absorber via the one-way valves regardless."},{"id":"fmon01","domain":"Monitoring","q":"A 12 kg dog under injectable anesthesia (not intubated, breathing room air) has an SpO2 that reads a stable 88%. Matching this to the oxyhemoglobin dissociation curve and choosing the correct response, you conclude:","options":["PaO2 ~100 mmHg; within normal limits, continue monitoring","PaO2 ~60 mmHg; the threshold of hypoxemia - secure the airway/oxygen and support ventilation","PaO2 ~75 mmHg; mild desaturation, no action required","PaO2 ~40 mmHg; severe but an expected finding on room air"],"answer":1,"explain":"SpO2 ~88% corresponds to a PaO2 near 60 mmHg - the threshold of hypoxemia. In a non-intubated patient on room air this warrants intervention: secure the airway, provide supplemental oxygen, and support ventilation. It is neither normal (~100 mmHg) nor a 'no action' mild finding, and a PaO2 of 40 mmHg (severe) is never acceptable."},{"id":"fmon02","domain":"Monitoring","q":"Of these intra-anesthetic ECG findings, which warrants the MOST immediate concern and possible antiarrhythmic intervention?","options":["Respiratory sinus arrhythmia (rate varying with ventilation)","Sustained runs of wide, bizarre QRS complexes (ventricular tachycardia)","An occasional isolated atrial premature complex","First-degree AV block, with every P wave conducting"],"answer":1,"explain":"Sustained runs of wide, bizarre QRS complexes indicate ventricular tachycardia, which can compromise cardiac output and degenerate into ventricular fibrillation - the most urgent finding here, potentially needing an antiarrhythmic (e.g., lidocaine in dogs). Sinus arrhythmia, an occasional atrial premature complex, and first-degree AV block are usually benign."},{"id":"fmon03","domain":"Monitoring","q":"During a canine splenectomy with ongoing hemorrhage, the mean arterial pressure has fallen from 80 to 55 mmHg while the heart rate has climbed from 90 to 150 bpm. This combination most likely represents:","options":["A lightening anesthetic plane with otherwise stable perfusion","Developing hypovolemia/hypotension driving a compensatory, baroreceptor-mediated tachycardia","An expected, benign response to intravenous fluid loading","Hypothermia slowing the metabolic rate"],"answer":1,"explain":"A falling MAP (80 to 55 mmHg) with a rising heart rate (90 to 150 bpm) during active hemorrhage is developing hypovolemia/hypotension driving a baroreceptor-mediated compensatory tachycardia. The cause must be identified and corrected (control bleeding, fluids/blood, reduce depth). A lightening plane would not drop BP this way, and this is not benign fluid loading or hypothermia (which slows the heart)."},{"id":"fpn01","domain":"Pain Management","q":"A 4-year-old, normovolemic dog (ASA II) is anesthetized for ORIF of a mid-shaft femoral fracture. Which analgesic plan best embodies multimodal analgesia?","options":["A high-dose fentanyl CRI as the sole analgesic","Methadone premedication + femoral and sciatic nerve blocks + carprofen once perfusion is confirmed","Methadone premedication + femoral and sciatic nerve blocks + midazolam once the patient is stable","Raising the isoflurane concentration to control intraoperative pain"],"answer":1,"explain":"Multimodal analgesia combines drugs acting at different points of the pain pathway: an opioid (central), regional nerve blocks (transmission), and an NSAID (peripheral inflammation). Substituting midazolam for the NSAID removes a genuine analgesic arm - benzodiazepines are not analgesics - a single CRI is unimodal, and inhalant depth is not analgesia."},{"id":"fpn02","domain":"Pain Management","q":"After giving rescue analgesia to a painful postoperative dog, why is re-scoring with a validated pain tool essential?","options":["It documents the record but rarely changes the treatment plan","It objectively verifies whether the intervention worked and directs whether more or different analgesia is needed","It confirms that an adequate surgical anesthetic depth was maintained","It is unnecessary once a weight-appropriate dose has been calculated"],"answer":1,"explain":"Pain management is iterative: re-scoring with a validated tool after an intervention objectively confirms efficacy and guides whether additional or alternative analgesia is required. It is not mere paperwork, it does not measure anesthetic depth, and calculating a correct dose does not guarantee the individual patient's response."},{"id":"floc01","domain":"Local/Regional","q":"The specific purpose of aspirating before injecting a peripheral nerve block is to detect:","options":["Intravascular needle placement, to prevent systemic local-anesthetic toxicity","Intraneural needle placement, to prevent mechanical nerve injury","Air entrainment that could cause a venous embolism","Cerebrospinal fluid indicating inadvertent subarachnoid spread"],"answer":0,"explain":"Aspiration checks that the needle tip is not within a blood vessel; a negative aspirate reduces the risk of intravascular injection and the systemic toxicity (seizures, cardiac arrest) that especially follows IV bupivacaine. Aspiration does not reliably detect intraneural placement (guarded against by injection pressure and patient response), and CSF return is a concern for neuraxial - not peripheral - blocks."},{"id":"floc02","domain":"Local/Regional","q":"A dog needs several extractions along the right maxillary (upper) arcade, including the fourth premolar (carnassial, tooth 108). Which block or blocks will desensitize this arcade?","options":["Inferior alveolar (mandibular) block","Infraorbital or maxillary block","Mental block","Auriculotemporal block"],"answer":1,"explain":"The maxillary (upper) arcade is desensitized by the infraorbital block or, for more caudal teeth such as the carnassial, the maxillary block (a caudal approach to the maxillary nerve). The inferior alveolar and mental blocks serve the mandibular arcade, and the auriculotemporal block targets the ear."},{"id":"fer01","domain":"Emergency/CPR","q":"You are performing chest compressions on a 12 kg Beagle in lateral recumbency. To generate adequate forward blood flow per RECOVER, each compression should depress the chest by:","options":["One-quarter of the chest width","Two-thirds to three-quarters of the chest width","One-third to one-half of the chest width","Only as deep as needed to feel a femoral pulse"],"answer":2,"explain":"RECOVER recommends compressing one-third to one-half of the chest width at 100-120/min with full recoil. One-quarter is too shallow to generate adequate output; two-thirds to three-quarters risks injury; and titrating to a palpable femoral 'pulse' is unreliable during CPR (often reflects venous, not arterial, flow) and is not the depth target."},{"id":"fer02","domain":"Emergency/CPR","q":"Why does allowing complete chest recoil between compressions improve CPR effectiveness?","options":["Chest re-expansion creates negative intrathoracic pressure that promotes venous return and refilling of the heart before the next compression","It slows the compression rate back into the recommended range","It creates a window to deliver a breath between each compression","It reduces the chance of fracturing ribs"],"answer":0,"explain":"Full recoil lets the chest re-expand, generating negative intrathoracic pressure that draws blood back into the thorax and refills the heart, so the next compression ejects an adequate volume. Leaning on the chest (incomplete recoil) reduces venous return and lowers output. Recoil is not about setting the rate, timing breaths, or preventing fractures."},{"id":"fcalc01","domain":"Calculations","q":"A 33-lb dog is anesthetized for a TPLO. You give cefazolin at 22 mg/kg IV about 30-60 minutes before incision. The reconstituted vial is 100 mg/mL. What volume do you administer?","options":["1.65 mL","3.3 mL","6.6 mL","7.26 mL"],"answer":1,"explain":"Convert: 33 lb ÷ 2.2 = 15 kg. Dose = 15 kg × 22 mg/kg = 330 mg. Volume = 330 mg ÷ 100 mg/mL = 3.3 mL. The 7.26 mL trap treats 33 lb as 33 kg; 6.6 mL doubles the mg/kg; 1.65 mL halves it. Give the first dose 30-60 min pre-incision and redose every ~90-120 minutes during long procedures."},{"id":"fcalc02","domain":"Calculations","q":"You add 3 mL of 2% lidocaine to a 1-liter bag of crystalloid to make a CRI. What is the resulting lidocaine concentration in the bag?","options":["0.006 mg/mL","0.06 mg/mL","0.6 mg/mL","6 mg/mL"],"answer":1,"explain":"A 2% solution = 20 mg/mL, so 3 mL supplies 3 × 20 = 60 mg. Concentration = 60 mg ÷ 1000 mL = 0.06 mg/mL. The 0.6 mg/mL trap divides by 100 mL instead of 1000 (forgetting a liter is 1000 mL); the others are further decimal slips. Confirm the final bag concentration before setting the infusion rate."},{"id":"fsp01","domain":"Species-Specific","q":"A 3-year-old Pug is recovering from anesthesia. It is beginning to swallow but is not yet fully awake. What is the most important airway-management action during this recovery?","options":["Remove the tube as soon as the first swallow reflex returns to avoid the dog chewing the tube","Leave the endotracheal tube in place until the dog is alert enough to actively and strongly reject it, monitoring closely with oxygen ready","Place the dog in dorsal recumbency to keep the airway axis straight","Give additional sedation to keep the dog quiet and motionless during recovery"],"answer":1,"explain":"Brachycephalic airways collapse and obstruct readily as anesthesia wears off, so the endotracheal tube is deliberately left in LATE, until the patient is awake enough to actively (often vigorously) reject it, with continuous monitoring and oxygen available. Extubating at the first swallow (fine for a normal dog) is the classic trap here. Dorsal recumbency and extra sedation both worsen airway risk; sternal positioning with the head and neck extended is preferred."},{"id":"fsp02","domain":"Species-Specific","q":"Preanesthetic fasting in rabbits differs fundamentally from fasting in dogs. Which statement correctly gives BOTH the reason a long fast is unhelpful AND the harm it causes?","options":["Rabbits cannot vomit, so a long fast does not meaningfully reduce aspiration risk, while it promotes GI stasis and hypoglycemia","Rabbits cannot vomit, so a long fast is unhelpful for aspiration risk but is otherwise harmless and therefore still routinely done","Rabbits vomit readily, so a long fast is essential to empty the stomach and prevent aspiration","A long fast is avoided mainly because an empty gut predisposes rabbits to gastric dilatation-volvulus"],"answer":0,"explain":"Rabbits are physically unable to vomit, so prolonged fasting confers little aspiration protection, yet it readily causes gastrointestinal stasis (ileus) and hypoglycemia, both serious in this species; hence only brief fasting to clear the mouth is used. The trap option shares the true premise but wrongly calls a long fast harmless. Rabbits do not vomit, and the risk is GI stasis/hypoglycemia, not GDV."},{"id":"fcx01","domain":"Complications","q":"A 25 kg dog on 3.5% isoflurane for an orthopedic repair has a mean arterial pressure of 52 mmHg. There is no hemorrhage and the patient appears deeply anesthetized. The most appropriate first step is to:","options":["Increase the IV crystalloid rate as the first step, then reassess","Decrease the vaporizer setting, since excessive inhalant depth is the most common cause of this hypotension","Give an ephedrine bolus before adjusting the vaporizer","Administer atropine to raise the blood pressure"],"answer":1,"explain":"Volatile inhalants cause dose-dependent vasodilation and myocardial depression, and a 3.5% setting with signs of over-depth makes excessive anesthetic depth the leading cause of this hypotension. Decreasing the vaporizer is the first corrective step, followed by fluids and, if needed, an inotrope/vasopressor. Fluids or ephedrine before reducing depth only mask the cause, and atropine raises heart rate rather than addressing vasodilation and myocardial depression."},{"id":"fcx02","domain":"Complications","q":"An anesthetized patient develops a rapidly rising body temperature, climbing ETCO2, and generalized muscle rigidity. This classic triad should raise immediate concern for:","options":["Exhausted CO2 absorbent causing rebreathing","An isolated light plane of anesthesia","Malignant hyperthermia — a hypermetabolic crisis","An acute anaphylactic reaction"],"answer":2,"explain":"Rapidly rising temperature and ETCO2 together with muscle rigidity is the classic presentation of malignant hyperthermia, a hypermetabolic crisis. Management includes stopping triggering agents, aggressive cooling, ventilatory support, and dantrolene. Exhausted absorbent would raise ETCO2 but not cause rigidity or a rapid temperature spike; a light plane alone does not explain the triad; anaphylaxis presents with hypotension, edema, and bronchospasm."},{"id":"fvf01","domain":"Ventilation/Fluids","q":"During an open thoracotomy, spontaneous ventilation fails and positive-pressure ventilation becomes mandatory. What is the precise physiologic reason?","options":["Opening the pleural space abolishes the positive intrapleural pressure that normally expands the lungs, so they collapse","Opening the pleural space abolishes the negative (subatmospheric) intrapleural pressure that normally holds the lungs expanded, so they collapse","Inhalant anesthetics completely abolish central respiratory drive during thoracic procedures","The surgeon requires the lungs to be held fully inflated and motionless throughout"],"answer":1,"explain":"Normal spontaneous breathing depends on a NEGATIVE (subatmospheric) intrapleural pressure that keeps the lungs expanded and becomes more negative during inspiration. Opening the chest equalizes pleural pressure with atmosphere, eliminating that gradient so the lungs collapse, mandating positive-pressure ventilation to maintain gas exchange. Intrapleural pressure is negative, not positive (the trap); inhalants depress but do not wholly abolish drive; and surgeons do not need the lungs statically inflated."},{"id":"fvf02","domain":"Ventilation/Fluids","q":"A clinic updates its anesthesia protocol, lowering the default intraoperative crystalloid rate for healthy patients from the older 10 mL/kg/hr toward roughly 3-5 mL/kg/hr, titrated to blood pressure. What is the primary rationale for this shift?","options":["Lower rates reduce the risk of volume overload and pulmonary edema while still supporting perfusion","Anesthetized patients no longer lose fluid via evaporation or urine, so maintenance fluid is unnecessary","Inhalant anesthetics make the body retain sodium and water, so less fluid must be given to compensate","Lower rates prevent dilution of injectable anesthetic drug concentrations in the blood"],"answer":0,"explain":"Evidence links liberal intraoperative fluids to volume overload, interstitial/pulmonary edema, and worse outcomes, especially in cardiac/renal patients, so modern guidance uses conservative rates (~3-5 mL/kg/hr) titrated to blood pressure and perfusion rather than fixed high rates. Anesthetized patients DO still have ongoing losses (so fluids are not unnecessary), inhalants do not drive the sodium/water retention claimed, and fluid rate is not about 'diluting' drugs."},{"id":"fap01","domain":"Anesthetic Principles","q":"Two clinics both perform preanesthetic exams and history-taking. Clinic A uses the findings to choose drugs and monitoring for each individual patient; Clinic B records the findings but then anesthetizes every patient with the same fixed protocol. Which approach reflects the actual purpose of the preanesthetic assessment, and why?","options":["Clinic A, because the assessment exists to identify individual risk factors and tailor the anesthetic plan accordingly","Clinic B, because a single validated protocol applied uniformly is safest and the exam is mainly for records","Neither, because the exam's real purpose is to determine each patient's exact minimum alveolar concentration beforehand","Both are equivalent, because the exam is primarily to meet legal and insurance documentation requirements"],"answer":0,"explain":"The preanesthetic assessment exists to detect patient-specific risk factors (cardiac, renal, hepatic, hydration, age) and to INDIVIDUALIZE drug choice and monitoring, which is Clinic A's approach. Gathering findings only to apply one identical protocol to everyone (Clinic B) wastes the assessment's purpose. The exam does not yield a numeric MAC, and while documentation matters, it is not the primary reason."},{"id":"fap02","domain":"Anesthetic Principles","q":"Which patient is most correctly classified as ASA physical status II?","options":["A 7-year-old dog with well-controlled, stable early-stage endocrine disease presenting for a routine dental","A 7-year-old dog with severe, activity-limiting but non-life-threatening cardiac disease presenting for a dental","A healthy 2-year-old dog with entirely normal history, exam, and bloodwork presenting for an elective spay","A collapsed dog with a bleeding splenic mass and hypovolemic shock"],"answer":0,"explain":"ASA II is MILD, well-controlled systemic disease that does not limit normal function (e.g., stable early-stage endocrinopathy, mild obesity, well-controlled early disease). Severe disease that limits activity but is not a constant threat to life is ASA III (the near-twin trap), a truly normal patient is ASA I, and a shocky patient with a bleeding mass is ASA IV (with an E modifier). The key to II is 'mild and controlled.'"}];
const EXAM_SETS = [["adv19","mon01","adv21","mon03","nap02","mon05","nap04","adv06","nap06","nmon01","fap01","nmon03","fcalc01","npn07","neq07","neq09","adv01","feq03","np04","np10","adv20","mon02","nap01","mon04","nap03","mon06","nap05","adv07","nap07","nmon02","fap02","nmon04","fcalc02","npn08","nmon08","phr18","feq02","nphy11","fphy03","np17"],["calc01","pn01","calc03","pn03","ncalc01","adv13","ncalc03","npn01","ncalc05","npn03","ncalc07","npn05","ncx07","phr13","floc02","nmon09","nphy06","fmon03","nphy14","np12","calc02","pn02","calc04","pn04","ncalc02","adv14","ncalc04","npn02","ncalc06","npn04","ncalc08","npn06","ncx08","phr14","fpn02","nphy05","fmon02","np03","np09","np19"],["cx01","phr01","cx03","phr03","adv17","phr05","ncx01","phr07","ncx03","phr09","ncx05","phr11","ner08","adv12","nmon07","phr17","feq01","adv05","np06","np14","cx02","phr02","cx04","phr04","adv18","phr06","ncx02","phr08","ncx04","phr10","ncx06","phr12","ner09","nphy01","phr16","neq12","adv04","nphy13","fphy05","np21"],["er01","phy01","er03","phy03","adv16","phy05","ner02","phy07","ner04","phy09","ner06","adv10","neq05","fvf02","fpn01","nphy04","fmon01","nphy10","fphy02","np16","er02","phy02","er04","phy04","ner01","phy06","ner03","phy08","ner05","phy10","ner07","adv11","neq06","fcx02","nphy03","nmon12","nphy09","np05","np11","fp01"],["eq01","sp01","eq03","sp03","eq05","nsp02","adv08","nsp04","neq01","nsp06","neq03","fsp01","nloc07","fcx01","phr15","neq11","adv03","np02","np08","np18","eq02","sp02","eq04","nsp01","eq06","nsp03","adv09","nsp05","neq02","nsp07","neq04","fsp02","floc01","fer02","neq10","adv02","feq04","fphy01","np13","fp03"],["loc01","vf01","loc03","vf03","loc05","adv22","nloc01","nvf02","nloc03","nvf04","nloc05","nvf06","nmon05","fer01","nphy02","nmon11","nphy08","nphy12","fphy04","np20","loc02","vf02","loc04","vf04","adv15","nvf01","nloc02","nvf03","nloc04","nvf05","nloc06","fvf01","nmon06","neq08","nmon10","nphy07","np01","np07","np15","fp05"]];
const MOCK_POOL = [{"id":"mp01","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"A 4-year-old, 5-kg Yorkshire Terrier with a congenital portosystemic shunt (low albumin, low BUN, elevated pre- and post-prandial bile acids) is presented for surgical attenuation. You want an IV induction agent whose recovery after a single titrated dose depends least on the compromised liver. Which is the best choice?","options":["Diazepam","Alfaxalone","Propofol","Ketamine"],"answer":2,"explain":"Propofol has a very high total-body clearance that exceeds hepatic blood flow, indicating substantial extrahepatic metabolism, and after a single dose its effect terminates mainly by rapid redistribution. That makes recovery less dependent on hepatic function than diazepam (hepatic metabolism to active metabolites that accumulate in liver disease), ketamine (hepatic biotransformation), or alfaxalone (rapidly redistributed but cleared hepatically). In a shunt patient with poor hepatic function, propofol titrated to effect gives the most predictable recovery."},{"id":"mp02","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"A 32-kg Greyhound is maintained with repeated intravenous boluses of thiopental during a lengthy procedure. Recovery is far more prolonged than you would expect from the single induction dose alone. What best explains why repeated dosing behaves so differently from a single bolus?","options":["Repeated dosing saturates the muscle and fat compartments, so redistribution can no longer terminate the effect and recovery now depends on slow hepatic metabolism","Greyhounds have very little body fat, so there is no adipose depot for the drug to redistribute into","Thiopental is eliminated only by renal excretion, which becomes saturated with repeated dosing","Repeated boluses form an inactive metabolite that is spontaneously reconverted to active drug during recovery"],"answer":0,"explain":"A single thiobarbiturate dose is terminated by redistribution to muscle and fat. With repeated dosing those depots saturate, so redistribution can no longer end the effect and the patient must rely on slow hepatic metabolism, producing a cumulative, prolonged recovery. The low body fat of sighthounds does contribute to slow recovery, but that applies even to a single dose and does not explain why repeated dosing is disproportionately worse."},{"id":"mp03","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"A 10-year-old, 28-kg Labrador Retriever with stage B2 myxomatous mitral valve disease (ASA III) receives a pure mu-opioid premedication. You find you need noticeably less propofol to induce and can maintain a surgical plane at a lower isoflurane vaporizer setting. What is the primary reason?","options":["The opioid behaves as a volatile agent, adding directly to the alveolar anesthetic concentration","The opioid competitively inhibits hepatic metabolism of propofol and isoflurane, raising their plasma concentrations","The opioid enhances GABA-A receptor chloride conductance, directly synergizing with the induction agent","The opioid provides sedation and analgesia and is MAC-sparing, lowering induction-agent and inhalant requirements"],"answer":3,"explain":"Opioids act at opioid receptors to provide sedation and analgesia and are MAC-sparing, so less induction agent and less inhalant are needed to reach and hold a surgical plane. This dose-sparing is a core principle of balanced anesthesia and improves cardiovascular stability, which is especially valuable in a cardiac patient. Opioids are not inhalants, do not act at GABA-A receptors, and their benefit is not from inhibiting anesthetic metabolism."},{"id":"mp04","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"A 25-kg dog sedated with intramuscular dexmedetomidine for radiographs has pale mucous membranes and a heart rate of 45 bpm; the study is finished and sedation is no longer needed. Your technician draws up atipamezole. What is the best reason to give it intramuscularly rather than as a rapid IV bolus?","options":["Rapid IV administration abruptly abolishes alpha-2-mediated vasoconstriction, precipitating hypotension, reflex tachycardia, and excitement; the IM route gives a smoother reversal","The IM route reaches peak effect faster, restoring tissue perfusion more quickly","The IM route preserves the analgesia the dexmedetomidine was providing","Given IV, atipamezole undergoes extensive first-pass metabolism and is inactivated"],"answer":0,"explain":"The bradycardia and pale membranes reflect the alpha-2 agonist's peripheral vasoconstriction and reflex bradycardia. Antagonizing this abruptly with IV atipamezole can cause sudden vasodilation and hypotension, reflex tachycardia, and CNS excitement; IM administration reverses more gradually and smoothly, which is why it is the recommended route. Atipamezole reverses analgesia regardless of route, IM is not faster than IV, and IV atipamezole is not inactivated by first-pass metabolism."},{"id":"mp05","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"A 9-year-old, 30-kg dog with chronic osteoarthritis is discharged on an oral analgesic, but two weeks later the owner reports little improvement in comfort or mobility. The prescribed drug's opioid analgesia depends on hepatic conversion to an active metabolite (M1) that dogs generate in only small amounts. Which drug was most likely prescribed?","options":["Methadone","Hydromorphone","Tramadol","Fentanyl"],"answer":2,"explain":"Tramadol's opioid analgesia depends largely on hepatic conversion to its active O-desmethyl metabolite (M1); dogs produce very little M1, so its opioid effect is unreliable in that species, a frequently tested pharmacogenetic point that explains the poor response. Methadone, hydromorphone, and fentanyl are active as the parent compound and do not depend on this conversion."},{"id":"mp06","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"A 6-kg cat is being evaluated as a feline blood donor and is fractious; a colleague suggests acepromazine to facilitate handling and collection. Setting aside its hypotensive potential, why is acepromazine a poor choice specifically before blood donation (and in anemic patients)?","options":["It promotes splenic contraction, transiently raising the measured PCV and masking anemia","It relaxes the splenic capsule and sequesters red cells in the spleen, transiently lowering the PCV and reducing collectable red-cell mass","It causes oxidative hemolysis of red cells, dropping the PCV","It has no direct hematologic effect; the only concern is its alpha-1-mediated hypotension"],"answer":1,"explain":"Acepromazine relaxes the splenic capsule and causes splenic sequestration of red blood cells, transiently lowering the measured PCV and the red-cell mass available for donation. It does not cause hemolysis and does not raise the PCV; while it does cause alpha-1-mediated hypotension, the claim that it has no hematologic effect is incorrect."},{"id":"mp07","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"You induce a 20-kg dog with ketamine alone and observe marked skeletal muscle rigidity and a hypertonic, rough recovery. On the next case you combine midazolam with the ketamine. What is the rationale for adding the benzodiazepine?","options":["Midazolam competitively inhibits ketamine's hepatic biotransformation, deliberately deepening and prolonging anesthesia","The benzodiazepine supplies the analgesia that ketamine itself cannot provide","The benzodiazepine adds centrally mediated muscle relaxation, reducing ketamine-induced rigidity and smoothing induction and recovery","Ketamine antagonizes residual benzodiazepine sedation, preventing excessive CNS depression"],"answer":2,"explain":"Ketamine alone causes muscle rigidity and can produce rough, excitatory recoveries. A benzodiazepine (midazolam or diazepam) provides central muscle relaxation that offsets the rigidity and smooths induction and recovery, the basis of the classic ketamine-benzodiazepine co-induction. Ketamine, not the benzodiazepine, supplies analgesia via NMDA antagonism; midazolam does not inhibit ketamine metabolism, and ketamine does not reverse benzodiazepines."},{"id":"mp08","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"A 12-year-old, 4-kg cat with concurrent chronic kidney disease and hepatic lipidosis needs an intraoperative opioid CRI for a prolonged procedure. You want an agent whose offset will not be prolonged by the organ dysfunction or by the duration of the infusion. Which opioid is most appropriate?","options":["Morphine","Remifentanil","Fentanyl","Hydromorphone"],"answer":1,"explain":"Remifentanil is hydrolyzed by nonspecific plasma and tissue esterases independent of hepatic and renal function, and its context-sensitive half-time stays essentially flat regardless of infusion duration, making it ideal for a titratable CRI in an organ-compromised patient. Morphine's active metabolite accumulates in renal failure; fentanyl's context-sensitive half-time lengthens with prolonged infusion and depends on hepatic clearance; hydromorphone is hepatically cleared."},{"id":"mp09","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"At the end of a procedure maintained with nitrous oxide and isoflurane in oxygen, you turn off the nitrous oxide. Why should you continue 100% oxygen for several minutes rather than immediately returning the patient to room air?","options":["Large volumes of nitrous oxide rapidly diffuse out of the blood into the alveoli, diluting alveolar oxygen and CO2 and risking transient hypoxemia","As it is discontinued, nitrous oxide diffuses from the alveoli into the blood, causing alveolar collapse that oxygen prevents","Nitrous oxide is nephrotoxic on emergence, and a high oxygen flow accelerates its renal elimination","Residual alveolar nitrous oxide provokes laryngospasm during extubation unless washed out with oxygen"],"answer":0,"explain":"When nitrous oxide is discontinued, the large reservoir dissolved in blood rapidly diffuses back into the alveoli, transiently diluting alveolar oxygen and CO2 (diffusion hypoxia). Supplying 100% oxygen for several minutes after discontinuation fills the alveoli with oxygen and prevents hypoxemia. The gradient runs from blood into alveoli, not the reverse, and nitrous oxide is neither nephrotoxic nor a cause of laryngospasm here."},{"id":"mp10","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"A 7-year-old, 22-kg dog maintained on long-term fluoxetine for separation anxiety is presented for a dental prophylaxis with extractions. Which analgesic adjunct most increases the risk of serotonin syndrome and therefore warrants caution or avoidance?","options":["Hydromorphone","Ketamine","Tramadol","Lidocaine"],"answer":2,"explain":"Tramadol inhibits serotonin (and norepinephrine) reuptake and has serotonergic activity; combined with a serotonergic drug such as the SSRI fluoxetine, it raises the risk of serotonin syndrome. Hydromorphone (mu agonist), ketamine (NMDA antagonist), and lidocaine (sodium-channel blocker) do not carry comparable serotonergic risk, so a medication history is essential before adding tramadol."},{"id":"mphy01","domain":"Physiology","q":"A 6-year-old, 32-kg Labrador (ASA II) is 40 minutes into an exploratory laparotomy in dorsal recumbency on 100% oxygen. An arterial blood gas shows PaO2 55 mmHg, PaCO2 41 mmHg, and SpO2 88%; breath sounds are diminished in the dependent lung fields, and the tube and circuit check out. Which derangement best explains these numbers?","options":["Anesthetic-induced hypoventilation is lowering the PaO2","Venous admixture from V/Q mismatch or right-to-left shunt, such as dependent atelectasis","This is an expected PaO2 for a healthy anesthetized dog breathing 100% oxygen","A pure diffusion barrier that will resolve once the FiO2 is reduced"],"answer":1,"explain":"On 100% oxygen the alveolar PO2 is ~600 mmHg and a healthy patient's PaO2 should exceed 400-500. A PaO2 of only 55 with a NORMAL PaCO2 (41) means the low oxygen is not from hypoventilation (which would raise PaCO2); it reveals a large A-a gradient from venous admixture — V/Q mismatch or right-to-left shunt, classically dependent atelectasis in a large dog in dorsal recumbency. Alveolar recruitment/PEEP, not a higher vaporizer setting, is the fix; lowering FiO2 would worsen it."},{"id":"mphy02","domain":"Physiology","q":"A 5-year-old male cat with a 48-hour urethral obstruction is dull but breathing deeply and rapidly on room air before you induce. Venous blood gas: pH 7.19, HCO3- 11 mmol/L, PaCO2 25 mmHg. Which statement best explains the low PaCO2 and its anesthetic significance?","options":["Compensatory hypoventilation to retain CO2 and buffer the acid load","Appropriate respiratory compensation — hyperventilation blowing off CO2 to defend pH — which anesthesia will blunt, risking rapid decompensation","Rapid renal bicarbonate generation over the last few minutes has normalized the gas","No ventilatory change is occurring; the pH is defended entirely by hemoglobin buffering"],"answer":1,"explain":"Metabolic acidosis with intact ventilatory control drives increased alveolar ventilation (Kussmaul-type breathing) that lowers PaCO2 to defend pH; this cat's PaCO2 of 25 is appropriate respiratory compensation, not hypoventilation or a lab quirk. Renal (bicarbonate) compensation takes hours to days, not minutes. Critically, anesthetics and controlled ventilation blunt this compensation, so PaCO2 can climb and pH crash after induction — correct the acidosis and support ventilation."},{"id":"mphy03","domain":"Physiology","q":"A 3-year-old, 24-kg spontaneously breathing dog under isoflurane is hemodynamically stable (HR 90, MAP 78) but its ETCO2 has drifted from 40 to 62 mmHg over 20 minutes. The endotracheal tube is patent and correctly placed, the CO2 absorbent is fresh and cool, and the capnograph baseline returns to zero on inspiration. What is the most likely cause?","options":["Rebreathing from exhausted CO2 absorbent","Anesthetic-induced hypoventilation from depressed respiratory drive and tidal volume","Hyperventilation from too light an anesthetic plane","Reduced CO2 production because the patient has become hypothermic"],"answer":1,"explain":"A fresh, cool absorbent and a capnograph that returns to zero on inspiration exclude rebreathing (which would elevate the inspired baseline). With a patent tube and stable hemodynamics, a steadily rising ETCO2 reflects alveolar hypoventilation from anesthetic depression of respiratory drive and tidal volume. Hyperventilation and hypothermia would LOWER, not raise, ETCO2. The remedy is assisted/controlled ventilation plus reassessing depth."},{"id":"mphy04","domain":"Physiology","q":"A 7-year-old cat with immune-mediated hemolytic anemia (PCV 12%, hemoglobin 4 g/dL) is anesthetized for a bone-marrow biopsy. On 100% oxygen the pulse oximeter reads SpO2 99%, yet the cat is tachycardic and its lactate is rising. How should you interpret the oxygenation status?","options":["Oxygen delivery is adequate — a 99% SpO2 confirms sufficient oxygen-carrying capacity","Oxygen content and delivery may be critically low: SpO2 reports the percentage of the scarce hemoglobin that is saturated, not the amount of oxygen carried","The rising lactate must be a sampling error, since a 99% SpO2 rules out tissue hypoxia","Breathing 100% oxygen has restored oxygen content through oxygen dissolved in plasma"],"answer":1,"explain":"SpO2 reports the percentage of AVAILABLE hemoglobin that is saturated, not total oxygen carried. CaO2 approx = 1.34 x Hb x SaO2 + 0.003 x PaO2; with Hb only 4 g/dL, arterial oxygen content is roughly a third of normal even at 99% saturation, so delivery hinges on cardiac output — hence the compensatory tachycardia and rising lactate. Dissolved oxygen adds only ~0.3 mL/dL per 100 mmHg of PaO2 and cannot replace hemoglobin. This is why SpO2 looks falsely reassuring in profound anemia."},{"id":"mphy05","domain":"Physiology","q":"A 30-kg dog with a bleeding splenic mass (HR 150, MAP 60, thready pulses, not yet volume-resuscitated) is induced and placed on mechanical ventilation. Immediately after positive-pressure breaths begin, the arterial pressure falls further to a MAP of 40. What is the most likely mechanism?","options":["Raised intrathoracic pressure impedes venous return, dropping preload and cardiac output","Positive-pressure breaths augment venous return, so the hypotension must be anesthetic overdose alone","The breaths acutely raised pulmonary vascular resistance and caused right-heart failure","Improved alveolar oxygenation triggered a baroreflex bradycardia and hypotension"],"answer":0,"explain":"Positive-pressure ventilation raises intrathoracic pressure, reducing the pressure gradient for systemic venous return; in a hypovolemic patient with almost no preload reserve, this abruptly cuts right-heart filling, stroke volume, and cardiac output. Spontaneous (negative-pressure) breathing normally AIDS venous return, so the opposite claim is false. High airway pressures can raise RV afterload, but the dominant, immediate cause in acute hypovolemia is preload reduction. Treat with volume resuscitation and lower airway pressures."},{"id":"mphy06","domain":"Physiology","q":"A 2.5-kg Chihuahua finishing a 3-hour dental has a core temperature of 33.5°C at extubation and is slow to recover, staying deeply obtunded on an isoflurane wash-out that normally produces a brisk recovery. Which mechanism best explains the delayed, deeper-than-expected recovery?","options":["Hypothermia accelerates hepatic clearance, so the drug is gone but the brain is simply cold","Hypothermia slows drug metabolism and lowers MAC, so agents persist and the patient is relatively more deeply anesthetized at any given level","Hypothermia raises MAC, so more drug was needed and the plane deepened","Hypothermia increases cardiac output, speeding redistribution and shortening recovery"],"answer":1,"explain":"Hypothermia both slows enzymatic (hepatic/renal) drug metabolism and clearance AND lowers anesthetic requirement — MAC falls substantially (on the order of ~5% per °C) — so agents linger and the patient is relatively more deeply anesthetized than the wash-out timeline predicts, producing a prolonged, rough recovery. Metabolism is slowed (not accelerated) and MAC decreases (not increases). Active warming shortens recovery and should be prioritized in small patients prone to heat loss."},{"id":"mphy07","domain":"Physiology","q":"A 25-kg dog with acute traumatic brain injury (obtunded, anisocoria) is anesthetized for a CT scan. Left on spontaneous ventilation, its ETCO2 climbs to 60 mmHg. Why is permitting this hypercapnia especially hazardous in this patient?","options":["CO2 is a potent cerebral vasodilator; hypercapnia increases cerebral blood volume and raises ICP, worsening herniation risk","Hypercapnia constricts cerebral vessels, reducing cerebral blood flow and causing cerebral ischemia","Hypercapnia has little cerebral effect; the real danger is the mild respiratory acidosis on the myocardium","Hypercapnia lowers ICP by driving CSF reabsorption, masking the true injury"],"answer":0,"explain":"Cerebral vessels dilate as PaCO2 rises (roughly linearly across the physiologic range), increasing cerebral blood volume; in a cranium with already-elevated ICP and poor compliance, this can sharply raise ICP and precipitate herniation. The relationship is vasodilation, not vasoconstriction, so the ischemia option inverts the physiology, and hypercapnia does not lower ICP. Maintaining normocapnia (with brief, targeted mild hypocapnia only for acute herniation) via controlled ventilation is central to neuroprotection."},{"id":"mphy08","domain":"Physiology","q":"You are planning anesthesia for a 14-year-old, 5-kg cat (ASA III, early chronic kidney disease, grade II/VI murmur) for a mass removal. Compared with a healthy young adult, why should induction and maintenance drugs be reduced and carefully titrated to effect?","options":["Reduced hepatic and renal function, lower MAC, decreased cardiopulmonary reserve, and altered body composition/protein binding slow clearance and heighten drug effect","Geriatric patients have a higher basal metabolic rate that intensifies and prolongs drug effect","Increased lean muscle mass expands the volume of distribution, so larger doses are needed","Elevated cardiac output speeds drug delivery to the brain, so standard doses act faster but clear normally"],"answer":0,"explain":"Geriatric patients have diminished hepatic and renal drug handling, reduced cardiovascular and respiratory reserve, a lower MAC/anesthetic requirement, and altered body composition (less lean mass and total body water, relatively more fat) with changed protein binding — together increasing sensitivity and slowing clearance. Metabolic rate and cardiac output fall rather than rise, and lean mass decreases, so the higher-dose rationales are wrong. Conservative, titrated dosing with multimodal/regional techniques is safest."},{"id":"meq01","domain":"Equipment","q":"A 2.8 kg, 6-month-old domestic shorthair (ASA I) is anesthetized for castration on a Bain (Mapleson D) non-rebreathing circuit. A student asks why you set oxygen flow much higher per kilogram (about 200-300 mL/kg/min) than the 1 L/min low-flow you run on the 30 kg dog's circle system next door. The best explanation is:","options":["The Bain circuit's CO2 absorber needs high flow to regenerate between breaths","The circuit's unidirectional valves add resistance that only high flow can overcome","With no CO2 absorbent, the circuit relies on high fresh gas flow to flush exhaled CO2 and prevent rebreathing","High flow is needed to conserve the cat's airway heat and humidity"],"answer":2,"explain":"Non-rebreathing (Mapleson) circuits have no CO2 absorber, so they depend on high fresh gas flows (commonly ~200-300 mL/kg/min, roughly 2-3x minute ventilation) to wash exhaled CO2 out of the circuit and prevent rebreathing. Their low resistance and lack of unidirectional valves suit small patients, but the high flows waste gas and actually worsen airway heat and humidity loss - the opposite of conservation."},{"id":"meq02","domain":"Equipment","q":"Midway through a canine dental on a circle system the reservoir bag is partially collapsed, and a new assistant presses the oxygen flush valve while the pop-off (APL) valve is closed and the patient stays connected. Within seconds, the GREATEST immediate danger is:","options":["A surge of high isoflurane concentration causing anesthetic overdose","A rapid rise in circuit and airway pressure causing barotrauma and impaired venous return","Dilution of inspired oxygen producing acute hypoxemia","A gradual lightening of anesthetic depth from vaporizer bypass"],"answer":1,"explain":"The oxygen flush delivers 35-75 L/min of pure O2 directly into the circuit, bypassing the vaporizer. With the pop-off closed and the patient connected, pressure rises almost instantly, risking pulmonary barotrauma, reduced venous return, and cardiovascular collapse. The flush does bypass the vaporizer (which can lighten anesthesia over time), but the immediate life threat is the pressure spike, not overdose, hypoxemia, or light plane."},{"id":"meq03","domain":"Equipment","q":"A 25 kg Labrador on a circle system develops a capnograph baseline that no longer returns to zero (inspired CO2 ~8 mmHg) with a slowly climbing ETCO2. You inspect the absorbent: the soda lime is still white, soft, and warm. The most likely mechanism of the hypercapnia is:","options":["An incompetent (stuck-open) unidirectional valve allowing exhaled CO2-rich gas to be rebreathed","Exhausted CO2 absorbent that can no longer scrub CO2","Anesthetic-induced hypoventilation causing CO2 retention","Increased apparatus dead space in the Y-piece connector"],"answer":0,"explain":"A raised inspired-CO2 baseline that fails to return to zero signals rebreathing. With fresh, warm, functioning absorbent, an incompetent one-way valve is the culprit - loss of unidirectional flow lets exhaled gas be re-inhaled. Exhausted absorbent would give the same pattern but the granules would be discolored, hard, and cool; hypoventilation raises the peak ETCO2, not the inspired baseline."},{"id":"meq04","domain":"Equipment","q":"A relief technician accidentally fills an isoflurane-keyed precision vaporizer with sevoflurane (saturated vapor pressure ~157 mmHg for sevo vs ~240 mmHg for iso) and sets the dial to 2%. Why is this dangerous?","options":["The two agents react chemically to form a toxic byproduct","It is harmless because both are halogenated ethers with the same MAC","It is safe as long as you lower the dial, because sevoflurane is more volatile than isoflurane","The vaporizer is calibrated to one agent's vapor pressure, so the wrong agent delivers an inaccurate, unpredictable concentration"],"answer":3,"explain":"A variable-bypass precision vaporizer splits fresh gas flow based on one specific agent's saturated vapor pressure. Filling it with a different agent (different SVP and different potency/MAC - iso ~1.3% vs sevo ~2.4%) makes the delivered concentration no longer match the dial, producing an unpredictable over- or under-dose. Sevoflurane is actually LESS volatile than isoflurane, and the agents do not react - which is exactly why agent-specific keyed fillers exist to prevent cross-filling."},{"id":"meq05","domain":"Equipment","q":"You are setting up a circle system for a 30 kg dog (tidal volume ~10 mL/kg). Applying the guideline that the reservoir bag should hold roughly six times the tidal volume (~60 mL/kg), which bag best allows a full manual breath without excessive circuit compliance?","options":["0.5 L","1 L","2 L","5 L"],"answer":2,"explain":"Reservoir bag volume should be about 6x tidal volume (~60 mL/kg). For a 30 kg dog that is ~1.8 L, so a 2 L bag is most appropriate. A 1 L bag (~33 mL/kg) is too small to deliver a full sigh or manual breath, while a 5 L bag adds so much compliance that spontaneous breathing is hard to see and anesthetic concentration changes are slow."},{"id":"meq06","domain":"Equipment","q":"During your pre-anesthetic machine check (pop-off closed, Y-piece occluded) the circuit pressure will not rise past 10 cmH2O and slowly falls. Your next case is a healthy elective spay due to start in 10 minutes. The most appropriate action is:","options":["Proceed, since the patient is healthy and the case is short","Systematically check connections, the reservoir bag, the absorbent-canister seal, and the hoses to find and fix the leak before use","Raise the oxygen flow high enough to keep the circuit pressurized and proceed","Increase the vaporizer setting to ensure adequate depth despite the leak"],"answer":1,"explain":"A failed leak test must be resolved before use - a leak risks inadequate anesthetic/gas delivery, inability to ventilate, and waste-gas pollution. Methodically inspect all connections, the bag, canister gaskets/seals, and hoses to locate and correct it. Masking the leak with high flows (or turning up the vaporizer) does not fix the underlying safety problem."},{"id":"meq07","domain":"Equipment","q":"On an active (vacuum-driven) scavenging system, the circle-system reservoir bag repeatedly collapses and the patient's breaths look shallow despite appropriate fresh gas flow; the scavenger interface shows no reservoir bulb and the wall-vacuum gauge reads high. The most likely cause and its risk is:","options":["Excessive scavenger suction is evacuating the breathing circuit, applying negative pressure that impairs ventilation","The scavenger hose is kinked and obstructed, causing back-pressure and barotrauma","The CO2 absorbent is exhausted, reducing circuit volume","A puncture in the reservoir bag is venting the fresh gas"],"answer":0,"explain":"A collapsing bag with a high wall vacuum and no interface reservoir indicates excessive active suction pulling gas out of the circuit and applying negative airway pressure, which impairs ventilation. The opposite fault - obstruction - causes pressure buildup and bag distension, not collapse. Scavengers must be checked so they neither obstruct nor over-evacuate the circuit."},{"id":"mmon01","domain":"Monitoring","q":"An 8-year-old cat with feline asthma is maintained on isoflurane. Its previously square capnograph now shows a prolonged, sloping expiratory upstroke with no clear plateau ('shark-fin' shape), and ETCO2 is climbing. The most likely cause is:","options":["Acute hyperventilation","Esophageal intubation","Rebreathing from an incompetent expiratory valve","Lower-airway obstruction or bronchospasm causing prolonged, uneven alveolar emptying"],"answer":3,"explain":"A sloping shark-fin expiratory upstroke reflects uneven, obstructed alveolar emptying - bronchospasm (fitting this asthmatic cat), a kinked or partially obstructed ET tube, or lower-airway disease. An incompetent valve raises the inspired baseline rather than sloping the upstroke; hyperventilation lowers ETCO2; esophageal placement produces no sustained waveform at all."},{"id":"mmon02","domain":"Monitoring","q":"During a canine mass removal, the continuous tone from your Doppler probe over the metatarsal artery abruptly goes silent. The ECG still shows normal sinus rhythm at 90 bpm. The MOST appropriate immediate action is:","options":["Begin chest compressions for presumed cardiac arrest","Give atropine for presumed bradycardia","Check probe position and contact while simultaneously assessing pulse quality, mucous membranes/CRT, and blood pressure","Bolus IV fluids to treat presumed hypotension"],"answer":2,"explain":"A normal ECG with a lost Doppler tone is far more often a displaced probe or a perfusion change than arrest. Verify probe contact and immediately assess pulse, mucous-membrane color/CRT, and blood pressure before escalating. Starting CPR, giving atropine (HR 90 is normal), or bolusing fluids based on one silent probe with a normal rhythm is premature."},{"id":"mmon03","domain":"Monitoring","q":"After a difficult intubation in a mask-preoxygenated brachycephalic dog, you must confirm the tube is tracheal, not esophageal. Which finding is the MOST reliable confirmation?","options":["A sustained, repeating normal capnograph waveform over several breaths","A single square capnograph waveform on the very first breath","An SpO2 reading of 99%","Fogging (condensation) inside the tube on exhalation"],"answer":0,"explain":"A sustained, repeating capnograph waveform over several breaths is the most reliable confirmation of tracheal placement - the esophagus cannot generate consistent CO2 waveforms breath after breath. A single early waveform can be produced by CO2 previously forced into the stomach; SpO2 lags and can stay high after preoxygenation even with esophageal placement; tube fogging is nonspecific."},{"id":"mmon04","domain":"Monitoring","q":"A 2 kg geriatric cat under anesthesia repeatedly returns error messages on the oscillometric (NIBP) monitor, yielding no values, yet you still need blood pressure data. The single best troubleshooting step is:","options":["Apply a wider cuff to force a reading","Confirm a correctly sized cuff (~40% of limb circumference) with proper placement and minimal motion, and switch to Doppler if it stays unreliable","Deepen the anesthetic plane to eliminate movement artifact","Discontinue blood pressure monitoring for the rest of the case"],"answer":1,"explain":"Oscillometric devices are least reliable in very small and hypotensive patients. First optimize technique - a correctly sized cuff (~40% of limb circumference), correct placement, and minimal motion - and if it remains unreliable, use Doppler, which performs better in tiny patients. A too-wide cuff reads falsely low, deepening anesthesia is dangerous, and abandoning monitoring is never appropriate."},{"id":"mmon05","domain":"Monitoring","q":"A 5 kg male cat with a 3-day urethral obstruction is anesthetized for de-obstruction. The ECG shows tall, tented (peaked) T waves, a widening QRS, loss of visible P waves, and a heart rate of 70 bpm. The technician should immediately suspect and treat:","options":["Hypocalcemia","Hypothermia","Hyperkalemia","An excessively light anesthetic plane"],"answer":2,"explain":"Tall tented T waves, QRS widening, loss of P waves (atrial standstill), and bradycardia are the classic progression of hyperkalemia - expected in a blocked cat with obstructive uropathy. It is a life-threatening emergency: cardioprotect with calcium gluconate and lower potassium (dextrose +/- insulin, fluids, relieve the obstruction). Hypocalcemia prolongs the QT interval; hypothermia produces Osborn/J waves - neither gives tented T waves."},{"id":"mmon06","domain":"Monitoring","q":"Over 15 minutes an anesthetized dog's systolic Doppler pressure reads 95, then 88, then 82, then 76 mmHg, while heart rate, ETCO2, and SpO2 stay stable. Compared with reacting only to the single current value of 76 mmHg, why is recognizing this SEQUENCE more clinically valuable?","options":["Because any single blood pressure value is inherently inaccurate","Because 76 mmHg is normal, so the sequence proves no action is needed","Because trending requires no additional monitoring equipment","Because the downward trend reveals the direction the patient is heading and separates a real developing problem from a single artifact, prompting earlier intervention"],"answer":3,"explain":"Anesthetic monitoring is about trajectory. A steady downward trend in blood pressure reveals a developing problem and distinguishes genuine change from an isolated artifactual reading, enabling earlier and more appropriate intervention than reacting to any one number. The value comes from direction over time, not from the convenience of the method or from any single value's accuracy."},{"id":"mmon07","domain":"Monitoring","q":"A dog with acute hemorrhage (PCV 15%) is anesthetized on 100% oxygen. The pulse oximeter reads SpO2 100%, yet the mucous membranes are pale and CRT is 3 seconds. How should you interpret this SpO2?","options":["It confirms that oxygen delivery to the tissues is adequate","Hemoglobin is well saturated, but oxygen DELIVERY may still be inadequate because of low hemoglobin and poor perfusion - SpO2 does not measure delivery","The 100% value indicates the patient is hyperventilating","The reading is a motion artifact and can be ignored"],"answer":1,"explain":"SpO2 measures the saturation of the hemoglobin that is present, not oxygen delivery. Delivery (DO2) depends on saturation AND hemoglobin concentration AND perfusion/cardiac output. With a PCV of 15% and poor perfusion, arterial oxygen content and delivery are low despite 100% saturation, so SpO2 must be interpreted alongside PCV/Hb, pulse, CRT, and blood pressure."},{"id":"mpn01","domain":"Pain Management","q":"A 3-year-old, 26-kg intact female Labrador (ASA I) is at a stable surgical plane on isoflurane (ETiso 1.3%) for an ovariohysterectomy. As the surgeon exteriorizes and applies traction to the right ovarian pedicle, HR climbs from 85 to 140 bpm and MAP from 70 to 105 mmHg, while jaw tone and eye position are unchanged. What is the most appropriate response?","options":["Increase the isoflurane vaporizer setting alone until the heart rate and blood pressure normalize","Give esmolol to directly bring the heart rate and blood pressure back down","Treat it as a nociceptive response and give a rescue analgesic such as a fentanyl bolus (± a local block), not simply more inhalant","Lighten the plane, since tachycardia and hypertension indicate the patient is too deep"],"answer":2,"explain":"A sympathetic surge (tachycardia and hypertension) that coincides with a noxious surgical stimulus, in a patient whose reflex depth signs (jaw tone, eye position) are unchanged, indicates inadequate antinociception rather than a change in hypnotic depth. The correct response is additional analgesia (opioid bolus, local/regional technique). Simply increasing inhalant deepens cardiovascular depression, esmolol only masks the autonomic sign while leaving the patient in pain, and the picture is the opposite of an excessively deep plane."},{"id":"mpn02","domain":"Pain Management","q":"A 5-year-old, 32-kg male Golden Retriever (ASA II) is scheduled for a tibial plateau leveling osteotomy (TPLO). You are designing an analgesic plan built on pre-emptive, multimodal principles. Which plan best embodies this approach?","options":["Methadone in the premedication, a sciatic-femoral (or epidural) block placed before incision, and carprofen once the dog is confirmed normotensive and normovolemic","Methadone premedication with the sciatic-femoral block, but omit any NSAID because NSAIDs are contraindicated whenever a regional block is used","Rely on a higher isoflurane setting for intraoperative pain control and give a single methadone dose in recovery","Withhold analgesia until surgery is finished, then combine an NSAID and an opioid in recovery"],"answer":0,"explain":"Pre-emptive, multimodal analgesia targets the pain pathway at multiple sites before and during injury: an opioid in the premed, a regional/local block placed before incision to blunt nociceptive input and wind-up, and an NSAID added once perfusion is confirmed normal (normotensive/normovolemic) to protect renal blood flow. NSAIDs are not contraindicated by regional blocks; leaning on inhalant or waiting until recovery is reactive rather than pre-emptive."},{"id":"mpn03","domain":"Pain Management","q":"A 22-kg, 6-year-old Boxer (ASA II) is undergoing a 4-hour maxillectomy for oral tumor resection. You elect a fentanyl CRI rather than intermittent hydromorphone boluses. What is the principal advantage of the infusion in this setting?","options":["It reaches therapeutic plasma levels instantly, so no loading dose is needed","It holds plasma analgesic concentrations steady, preventing the breakthrough pain and sympathetic surges that recur as intermittent boluses fall to trough levels","It removes the need for continuous intraoperative monitoring during the long procedure","It is guaranteed to cost less than intermittent boluses over the case"],"answer":1,"explain":"A CRI maintains a stable plasma concentration, avoiding the peaks and troughs of intermittent dosing and thus the recurrent breakthrough pain and sympathetic responses that appear as each bolus wears off — particularly valuable across a long, painful procedure. A loading dose is still required to reach steady state promptly, and a CRI neither eliminates monitoring nor guarantees lower cost."},{"id":"mpn04","domain":"Pain Management","q":"A 4-kg, 3-year-old DSH cat is 6 hours out from femoral fracture repair. She sits hunched at the back of the cage, has not groomed, guards and flinches when the surgical limb is approached, and her Feline Grimace Scale score is 6/10. She received a pure-mu opioid at extubation. What is the best interpretation and action?","options":["Expected opioid dysphoria; withhold further analgesia until it wears off","Normal postoperative behavior for a cat; no intervention is needed","The Feline Grimace Scale is not validated, so base the decision on heart rate alone","Likely unrelieved pain; reassess, provide additional analgesia, and re-score to confirm the response"],"answer":3,"explain":"A hunched posture, failure to groom, guarding of the surgical limb, and an elevated score on the validated Feline Grimace Scale together indicate ongoing pain. The correct action is to reassess, give additional analgesia, and then re-score to confirm efficacy. These signs are not typical opioid dysphoria (which is not treated by withholding analgesia), are not normal postoperative behavior, and the FGS is a validated tool."},{"id":"mloc01","domain":"Local/Regional","q":"You are placing an inferior alveolar (mandibular) nerve block with bupivacaine in a 9-kg, 8-year-old dog for caudal dental extractions. On aspiration before injection you obtain a flash of blood in the syringe hub. What is the correct next step?","options":["Withdraw and reposition the needle, then re-aspirate; inject only after aspiration is negative","Inject slowly in small increments while watching for toxicity, since the calculated dose is within the safe maximum","Proceed, because a small blood flash is normal with mandibular blocks","Switch to lidocaine, which is safer intravascularly, and inject at that site"],"answer":0,"explain":"A positive blood aspirate means the needle tip is intravascular; injecting there risks acute systemic local anesthetic toxicity, which is especially dangerous with cardiotoxic bupivacaine. The needle must be withdrawn, repositioned, and re-aspirated until negative before any injection. Staying within the dose maximum, dosing incrementally, or switching agents does not make an intravascular injection safe."},{"id":"mloc02","domain":"Local/Regional","q":"A 30-kg, 9-year-old Rottweiler with an osteosarcoma of the distal radius is scheduled for a forelimb (thoracic limb) amputation. Which regional technique best provides intraoperative and postoperative analgesia for this limb?","options":["Lumbosacral epidural with morphine and bupivacaine","Combined femoral and sciatic nerve block","Brachial plexus block","Intercostal nerve blocks"],"answer":2,"explain":"The thoracic (front) limb is innervated by the brachial plexus (roughly C6–T2), so a brachial plexus block provides regional analgesia for a forelimb amputation. Epidurals and femoral/sciatic blocks desensitize the pelvic limbs, and intercostal blocks target the thoracic body wall — none covers the forelimb despite the 'thoracic limb' name."},{"id":"mloc03","domain":"Local/Regional","q":"During a large mass removal on a 5-kg, 13-year-old cat (ASA III) you have already infiltrated the maximum calculated dose of lidocaine as a line block. The surgeon now asks for a bupivacaine block at a second incision. What is the correct approach?","options":["Give the full bupivacaine block; lidocaine and bupivacaine act at different sites, so their toxicities do not summate","Give a reduced bupivacaine dose calculated only against bupivacaine's own maximum, since each agent has an independent toxicity ceiling","Proceed with the full dose, because systemic toxicity is only a concern with intravascular injection, not tissue infiltration","Recognize that local anesthetic toxicity is additive; total the combined dose across both agents and keep it under the safe maximum — meaning little or no additional bupivacaine can be given safely"],"answer":3,"explain":"Local anesthetic systemic toxicity is additive across different agents and across routes because they share the same mechanism of systemic toxicity. With lidocaine already at its maximum, the combined total must be recalculated and kept below the safe ceiling, so essentially no further local anesthetic can be given safely — a margin made even tighter in a small, geriatric cat. Toxicity ceilings are not independent per drug, the agents' toxicities do summate, and infiltrated (not only intravascular) drug is absorbed systemically."},{"id":"mloc04","domain":"Local/Regional","q":"A 25-kg, 7-year-old German Shepherd (ASA II) is having a hindlimb procedure and you plan an epidural with morphine for prolonged postoperative analgesia. Which formulation requirement is essential before injecting into the epidural space?","options":["Any standard morphine formulation is acceptable as long as the epidural dose is reduced","Preservative-free morphine must be used, because preservatives can be neurotoxic to neural tissue","The morphine must contain epinephrine to be safe for epidural use","The morphine must be diluted in 50% dextrose to set the correct baricity"],"answer":1,"explain":"Any drug placed in the neuraxial (epidural) space must be preservative-free, because common preservatives can be neurotoxic to spinal tissues. Preservative-free morphine provides prolonged segmental analgesia with minimal motor block. The epidural dose is indeed lower than systemic routes, but that does not address preservative neurotoxicity, and neither added epinephrine nor dextrose baricity is a requirement for epidural morphine."},{"id":"mer01","domain":"Emergency/CPR","q":"A 6-year-old, 28-kg Labrador (ASA III, septic peritonitis) is under isoflurane for an exploratory laparotomy. During abdominal lavage the ETCO2 abruptly drops from 38 to 4 mmHg, the Doppler signal is lost, and the femoral pulse is absent. The most appropriate immediate action is to:","options":["Draw up and give epinephrine and atropine first, since drugs are what restart the heart","Turn off the isoflurane and immediately begin high-quality chest compressions and ventilation while calling for help","Confirm the arrest with an arterial blood pressure and a 12-lead ECG before intervening","Lighten the anesthetic plane, deliver two manual breaths, and reassess in 30 seconds"],"answer":1,"explain":"Near-zero ETCO2 with an absent Doppler signal and pulse indicates cardiopulmonary arrest. Per RECOVER, basic life support — uninterrupted high-quality chest compressions plus ventilation — is started immediately, the vaporizer is turned off, and help is summoned; drugs and additional monitoring follow BLS, not precede it. Confirming with more monitoring or waiting only delays perfusion of the heart and brain."},{"id":"mer02","domain":"Emergency/CPR","q":"During CPR on an anesthetized cat, a 2-minute BLS cycle ends and compressions are paused for a rhythm check. The ECG shows a coarse, chaotic, irregular waveform with no organized QRS complexes and no palpable pulse. The intervention indicated for THIS rhythm that would NOT be appropriate for asystole is:","options":["Immediate electrical defibrillation","Epinephrine at 0.01 mg/kg","Atropine at 0.04 mg/kg","Resuming uninterrupted chest compressions"],"answer":0,"explain":"A coarse, chaotic, irregular waveform without a pulse is ventricular fibrillation, a shockable rhythm whose defining treatment is electrical defibrillation — not used for the non-shockable rhythms asystole and PEA. Epinephrine and chest compressions are used across all arrest rhythms, and atropine is considered chiefly for asystole/PEA with high vagal tone; only defibrillation distinguishes management of VF from asystole."},{"id":"mer03","domain":"Emergency/CPR","q":"Twelve minutes into CPR on a 22-kg dog, the team keeps running long rhythm/pulse checks and swaps the compressor slowly, leaving compressions paused for 15-20 seconds at a time. The leader insists each pause stay under 10 seconds. The primary physiologic reason RECOVER emphasizes minimizing these interruptions is that:","options":["The resuscitation attempt is completed sooner, improving the odds of success","Continuous compressions progressively bruise the myocardium, so minimizing total time limits injury","Coronary and cerebral perfusion pressures fall rapidly during each pause and take many compressions to rebuild","Pauses interrupt ETCO2 monitoring and mask a rising trend"],"answer":2,"explain":"The coronary perfusion pressure generated by compressions collapses within seconds of stopping and requires many compressions to re-establish; the same is true of cerebral perfusion. Minimizing interruptions — short rhythm checks, rapid compressor changes — sustains perfusion to the heart and brain and improves the chance of ROSC. Finishing faster, myocardial 'bruising,' and monitoring artifact are not the rationale."},{"id":"mer04","domain":"Emergency/CPR","q":"A 4-kg cat in cardiopulmonary arrest is receiving high-quality CPR with continuous compressions and ventilation. The ETCO2 has been steady at 10-14 mmHg for several minutes, then abruptly rises to 34 mmHg and holds there, with no change in ventilation or compression technique. This change most likely indicates:","options":["Deepening of the arrest with worsening pulmonary perfusion","Return of spontaneous circulation (ROSC)","Inadvertent esophageal intubation","Developing hyperthermia raising metabolic CO2 production"],"answer":1,"explain":"During CPR, ETCO2 reflects pulmonary blood flow. An abrupt, sustained rise toward normal without a change in ventilation signals a surge in pulmonary perfusion from return of spontaneous circulation, and should prompt a pulse/rhythm check and transition to post-arrest care. Worsening arrest lowers ETCO2, esophageal intubation drives it toward zero, and hyperthermia produces a gradual rise rather than an abrupt step."},{"id":"mcalc01","domain":"Calculations","q":"A 12 kg, 7-year-old Beagle (ASA II, well-controlled hypothyroidism) is premedicated for a dental. You elect propofol 4 mg/kg IV from a 10 mg/mL vial, drawing up the full calculated dose so it is ready before you titrate slowly to effect. What volume equals that full 4 mg/kg dose?","options":["2.4 mL","4.8 mL","9.6 mL","1.2 mL"],"answer":1,"explain":"Dose = 12 kg × 4 mg/kg = 48 mg; volume = 48 mg ÷ 10 mg/mL = 4.8 mL. 2.4 mL is the trap for reflexively halving the dose in a premedicated patient (the stem asks for the full 4 mg/kg volume), 9.6 mL doubles it, and 1.2 mL comes from dividing by the wrong factor. Draw the full dose but administer slowly to effect to avoid apnea."},{"id":"mcalc02","domain":"Calculations","q":"A 20 kg, 5-year-old mixed-breed dog (ASA III) undergoing a forelimb amputation is started on an intraoperative ketamine CRI at 10 mcg/kg/min for adjunctive analgesia. Charting the anesthetic record, what mass of ketamine is the patient receiving per hour?","options":["6 mg/hr","12 mg/hr","120 mg/hr","1.2 mg/hr"],"answer":1,"explain":"10 mcg/kg/min × 20 kg = 200 mcg/min; ×60 = 12,000 mcg/hr = 12 mg/hr. 6 mg/hr comes from using half the weight, 120 mg/hr from an incomplete mcg-to-mg conversion (dropping a factor of 10), and 1.2 mg/hr from an extra ÷10. The two-step mcg/min-to-mg/hr conversion (×60, ÷1000) is the classic CRI error point."},{"id":"mcalc03","domain":"Calculations","q":"A 5 kg, 3-year-old DSH cat under isoflurane develops sinus bradycardia (68 bpm) with hypotension. You elect atropine 0.04 mg/kg IV from a 0.54 mg/mL vial. What volume do you draw up?","options":["0.07 mL","0.2 mL","0.37 mL","0.74 mL"],"answer":2,"explain":"Dose = 5 kg × 0.04 mg/kg = 0.2 mg; volume = 0.2 mg ÷ 0.54 mg/mL ≈ 0.37 mL. 0.07 mL results from forgetting to multiply by body weight, 0.2 mL is the milligram dose mistaken for a volume, and 0.74 mL is double (0.08 mg/kg). Small anticholinergic volumes in cats demand precise measurement."},{"id":"mcalc04","domain":"Calculations","q":"A 25 kg, 6-year-old German Shepherd (ASA IV-E) is in hemorrhagic shock from a bleeding splenic mass. You resuscitate in increments, beginning with one-quarter of a full crystalloid shock dose (one blood volume = 80 mL/kg) and reassessing perfusion between boluses. What is that first one-quarter bolus?","options":["200 mL","500 mL","2000 mL","100 mL"],"answer":1,"explain":"Full shock dose = 25 kg × 80 mL/kg = 2000 mL; one-quarter = 500 mL, given over ~15 min with perfusion reassessed before the next bolus. 200 mL is one-tenth rather than one-quarter, 2000 mL is the entire (dangerous) shock volume at once, and 100 mL comes from using 4 mL/kg. Incremental bolusing avoids over-resuscitation."},{"id":"mcalc05","domain":"Calculations","q":"You are compounding a fentanyl CRI for a 10 kg, 8-year-old Cocker Spaniel (ASA III, mitral valve disease). You want a syringe pump set to exactly 1 mL/hr to deliver 3 mcg/kg/hr. To what concentration must you compound the fentanyl solution?","options":["10 mcg/mL","30 mcg/mL","50 mcg/mL","3 mcg/mL"],"answer":1,"explain":"Target delivery = 3 mcg/kg/hr × 10 kg = 30 mcg/hr; to give that in 1 mL/hr the bag must be 30 mcg/mL. 50 mcg/mL is the trap — it is the stock vial concentration, not the compounded solution. 3 mcg/mL forgets the body weight and 10 mcg/mL drops a factor. Working backward from dose and pump rate to concentration is the key skill."},{"id":"msp01","domain":"Species-Specific","q":"A 3-year-old, 15 kg English Bulldog with a known elongated soft palate is recovering after elective castration. He has just begun to swallow and shows a weak palpebral reflex but is not yet lifting his head. Which recovery action is most important?","options":["Extubate now, because return of the swallow reflex is the standard cue and leaving the tube in risks the dog chewing through it","Keep him intubated as long as he tolerates the tube, with oxygen and staff immediately at hand, removing it only once he is awake enough to actively reject it","Extubate and place him in dorsal recumbency so the tongue and soft palate fall clear of the laryngeal opening","Extubate promptly and give an alpha-2 agonist to keep him calm and motionless through recovery"],"answer":1,"explain":"Brachycephalic breeds obstruct easily in recovery because of redundant pharyngeal tissue and an elongated soft palate. Unlike a normal dog (where extubation at return of swallowing is acceptable), brachycephalics benefit from delayed extubation until awake enough to actively reject the tube, with oxygen and personnel ready. Sedation and dorsal recumbency both worsen obstruction risk, so option B is the key recovery precaution."},{"id":"msp02","domain":"Species-Specific","q":"A 2 kg, 4-year-old pet rabbit is scheduled for a dental procedure. A new technician wants to fast it overnight the way she would a dog. What is the best explanation for the fasting plan you recommend instead?","options":["Fast for 12 hours as for a dog; aspiration of gastric contents is the primary anesthetic danger in every species, rabbits included","Withhold food only briefly to clear the oral cavity; rabbits cannot vomit, so prolonged fasting does not lower aspiration risk but does promote dangerous GI stasis and hypoglycemia","Fast for 6-8 hours to partly empty the stomach and cecum, since the improved diaphragmatic excursion justifies the mild hypoglycemia risk","Do not withhold food at all and feed right up to induction, because fasting of any duration is contraindicated in an obligate continuous feeder"],"answer":1,"explain":"Rabbits (and rodents) cannot vomit, so a prolonged fast does not meaningfully reduce aspiration risk, yet it does invite GI stasis and hypoglycemia. Only a brief withholding to clear the mouth is appropriate. Option C accepts the can't-vomit fact but draws the wrong trade-off, and option D over-reaches: a short fast to clear the oral cavity (especially for dental work) is still appropriate."},{"id":"msp03","domain":"Species-Specific","q":"A 9 kg, 6-year-old domestic shorthair with a body condition score of 9/9 (estimated lean weight ~5 kg) presents for anesthesia. When calculating doses of lipophilic induction and maintenance agents, which approach best avoids a relative overdose?","options":["Dose every drug on the full 9 kg total body weight to be certain of an adequate anesthetic plane","Dose many lipophilic and dose-sensitive agents on the ~5 kg lean/ideal weight and titrate to effect, because adipose contributes little to the active volume of distribution","Dose water-soluble drugs on the ~5 kg lean weight but lipophilic drugs on the full 9 kg, since fat avidly takes up lipophilic agents","Average the total and lean weights (~7 kg) for every drug as a universal safety compromise"],"answer":1,"explain":"Dosing an obese patient on total body weight overdoses many agents, because the effect-site dose relates more to lean mass and cardiac output than to fat. The board-standard approach is to base many lipophilic/dose-sensitive drugs on lean (ideal) body weight and titrate to effect. Option C sounds pharmacologically plausible but would overdose the initial (lean) compartment; averaging weights (D) is arbitrary."},{"id":"mcx01","domain":"Complications","q":"A 3-year-old, 30-kg Greyhound under isoflurane for femoral fracture repair develops a steadily rising ETCO2 (now 68 mmHg despite increased ventilation), a temperature climbing from 38.5 to 41.5°C over 20 minutes, sinus tachycardia, and generalized muscle rigidity. The circuit, soda lime, and ventilation are confirmed adequate. The priority is to:","options":["Increase the isoflurane vaporizer setting to deepen the plane and relax the muscles","Discontinue all triggering agents, begin aggressive active cooling, support ventilation/oxygenation, and treat the hypermetabolic crisis (dantrolene)","Reduce the oxygen flow and switch toward room air to lower delivered gas temperature","Give a nondepolarizing neuromuscular blocker to abolish the rigidity"],"answer":1,"explain":"Rapidly rising ETCO2 and core temperature with muscle rigidity and tachycardia, after equipment and ventilation are excluded, indicate a hypermetabolic crisis such as malignant hyperthermia. Management is to stop all triggering agents (volatile inhalants, succinylcholine), cool aggressively, support ventilation and oxygenation, and give dantrolene. Increasing the inhalant adds trigger, a neuromuscular blocker neither relieves the metabolic rigidity nor treats the crisis, and cutting oxygen flow risks hypoxemia."},{"id":"mcx02","domain":"Complications","q":"A 10-year-old, 25-kg spayed mixed-breed dog (ASA II) is 40 minutes into a mass removal on 2.5% isoflurane with a MAP of 48 mmHg. Depth is adequate-to-deep (absent palpebral reflex, central eye, relaxed jaw), heart rate is 70, and she has received only maintenance crystalloids. The most appropriate FIRST step is to:","options":["Increase the isoflurane to deepen the plane, assuming light anesthesia is driving the low pressure","Start a dobutamine infusion immediately without changing the vaporizer","Reduce the vaporizer setting and give a crystalloid fluid bolus, then reassess before adding an inotrope","Discontinue intravenous fluids to avoid dilutional hypotension"],"answer":2,"explain":"Dose-dependent vasodilation and myocardial depression from volatile inhalants is a leading cause of intraoperative hypotension, and the depth here is already adequate-to-deep. The first step is to reduce the vaporizer (treat the likely cause) and give a crystalloid bolus, then reassess. If hypotension persists despite a lighter plane and volume, an inotrope such as dobutamine is added — it is not the first step, and increasing the inhalant or stopping fluids would worsen perfusion."},{"id":"mcx03","domain":"Complications","q":"A 7-year-old, 32-kg dog under anesthesia for a TPLO passively regurgitates a moderate volume of green fluid that pools in the pharynx. The endotracheal tube cuff is confirmed inflated and the pharynx is suctioned. Beyond this, the step most important for preventing esophageal stricture is to:","options":["Leave the esophageal contents undisturbed to avoid provoking further regurgitation","Lavage the esophagus with water and suction it, keeping the head lowered to prevent aspiration","Lavage the esophagus with a sodium bicarbonate solution to chemically neutralize the acid","Extubate promptly and lower the head so the fluid drains out on its own"],"answer":1,"explain":"Retained acidic gastric material causes esophagitis that can progress to stricture. With the cuff inflated to protect the airway, lavage the esophagus with water and suction it to dilute and remove the acid, keeping the head lowered so fluid drains outward rather than being aspirated. Leaving the contents permits ongoing injury, routine bicarbonate lavage is not the established measure, and extubating removes airway protection while regurgitation may continue."},{"id":"mcx04","domain":"Complications","q":"A 5-year-old, 20-kg non-brachycephalic dog is extubated after a prolonged dental procedure that required several intubation attempts. Within minutes she develops loud inspiratory stridor, marked paradoxical inspiratory effort, and a falling SpO2. The most appropriate immediate response is to:","options":["Give an NSAID for laryngeal inflammation and continue to monitor","Support the airway and oxygenation, prepare to re-oxygenate/re-intubate, and identify and treat the cause such as laryngeal edema or spasm","Place the dog in dorsal recumbency to open the airway","Give an intravenous sedative to reduce the respiratory effort"],"answer":1,"explain":"Post-extubation stridor with increased/paradoxical effort and desaturation indicates upper-airway obstruction (e.g., laryngeal edema or laryngospasm), which repeated intubation attempts predispose to. The immediate response is to support the airway and oxygenation, be ready to re-oxygenate and re-intubate, and identify and treat the cause. An NSAID does not relieve acute obstruction, dorsal recumbency does not protect the airway, and simply sedating a hypoxemic, obstructing patient without securing oxygenation is unsafe."},{"id":"mvf01","domain":"Ventilation/Fluids","q":"A 25 kg dog is undergoing a lateral thoracotomy for a lung lobectomy. As the surgeon incises the pleura and the chest is opened, which ventilation strategy must the anesthetist ensure?","options":["Allow spontaneous ventilation as long as SpO2 stays above 95%, intervening only if it falls","Provide controlled positive-pressure ventilation, because opening the chest abolishes the negative intrapleural pressure the lungs need to inflate on their own","Apply high continuous PEEP with the pop-off valve closed to hold the lungs open without delivering breaths","Increase the inhalant and rely on oxygen flow-by, avoiding positive pressure to keep the surgical field still"],"answer":1,"explain":"An open chest eliminates the negative intrapleural pressure required for spontaneous lung inflation, so the lungs collapse. Controlled positive-pressure ventilation (IPPV) is mandatory to maintain gas exchange. Static PEEP alone does not ventilate (and a closed pop-off is dangerous), and flow-by cannot inflate collapsed lungs."},{"id":"mvf02","domain":"Ventilation/Fluids","q":"An 8-year-old, 6 kg cat with hypertrophic cardiomyopathy (ASA III) is anesthetized for a dental. You are setting the intraoperative crystalloid rate. Which plan is most appropriate?","options":["10 mL/kg/hr, to aggressively support blood pressure given the cardiac disease","A conservative rate near 3 mL/kg/hr for a cat, titrated to blood pressure and perfusion, to avoid precipitating volume overload and pulmonary edema","The standard 5 mL/kg/hr used for a healthy dog, since crystalloids redistribute out of the vasculature too fast to overload a cat","No IV fluids for the entire procedure, to eliminate any possibility of volume overload"],"answer":1,"explain":"Current guidance favors conservative anesthetic crystalloid rates (about 5 mL/kg/hr in dogs and 3 mL/kg/hr in cats), reduced over time and titrated to blood pressure and perfusion. A cat with HCM is especially vulnerable to volume overload and pulmonary edema, so ~3 mL/kg/hr titrated is best. The dog rate (C) is too high here, aggressive loading (A) is dangerous, and withholding all fluids (D) is an over-correction."},{"id":"mvf03","domain":"Ventilation/Fluids","q":"You are manually delivering breaths to a healthy, 20 kg anesthetized Labrador during a routine procedure, watching the pressure manometer and chest excursion. What peak inspiratory pressure should you target for each breath?","options":["2-4 cmH2O, keeping pressure minimal to eliminate any risk of barotrauma","About 10-15 cmH2O (occasionally up to ~20), producing a normal chest rise","About 20-25 cmH2O on every breath, to guarantee full alveolar recruitment","30-40 cmH2O, matching the pressure used for a lung recruitment maneuver"],"answer":1,"explain":"For healthy lungs, deliver breaths to roughly 10-15 cmH2O peak pressure (occasionally up to ~20), gauging by the manometer and chest excursion. 2-4 cmH2O will not inflate the lungs; routine 20-25 or 30-40 cmH2O risks barotrauma and reduced venous return. Always reopen the pop-off valve after manual breaths."},{"id":"map01","domain":"Anesthetic Principles","q":"A 12-year-old dog arrives in congestive heart failure with pulmonary edema. After oxygen and furosemide it stabilizes somewhat but remains fragile, and anesthesia cannot be postponed. You assign an ASA physical status of IV. What does the 'IV' designation communicate to the team?","options":["Severe systemic disease that limits function but is not currently a constant threat to life","Severe systemic disease that is a constant threat to life","A moribund patient not expected to survive 24 hours with or without the procedure","Mild to moderate systemic disease with no functional limitation"],"answer":1,"explain":"ASA IV denotes severe systemic disease that is a constant threat to life, such as decompensated heart failure. Option A describes ASA III, option C describes ASA V (moribund), and option D describes ASA II. Because this is also an emergency, an 'E' would be appended (ASA IVE)."},{"id":"map02","domain":"Anesthetic Principles","q":"Midway through a long orthopedic anesthetic you review the timed record and notice blood pressure has drifted down across three consecutive 5-minute entries while heart rate has crept up. A student asks why the written record matters when a monitor already shows live numbers. What is the best answer?","options":["The record is primarily a billing and legal document; the live monitor is what actually guides care","Serial, timed entries reveal trends and early deterioration that a single live value can hide, and they preserve continuity and accountability across the team","Its main value is that, once enough data points are logged, it can substitute for continuous hands-on monitoring","It matters only for unusual cases; routine, stable anesthetics do not require a written record"],"answer":1,"explain":"A detailed, timed anesthetic record lets the team recognize trends (like this gradual hypotension with compensatory tachycardia), detect deterioration early, maintain continuity across personnel, and provide a medico-legal account. It supports but never replaces vigilant hands-on monitoring, and it is a standard of care for all anesthetics, not just complex ones."},{"id":"map03","domain":"Anesthetic Principles","q":"During mask induction of an under-premedicated cat, the patient briefly paddles, vocalizes, and shows exaggerated limb movement and reflexes before settling. Which anesthetic stage is this, and what is the best management?","options":["Stage I (voluntary excitement); back off the vaporizer and let the cat calm before continuing","Stage II (involuntary excitement); this reflects light premedication, and the goal is a smooth, prompt passage through it to a stable surgical plane","Stage III, plane 2; the movement is surgical-plane nystagmus, so the procedure can begin","Stage IV; the excitement signals impending overdose, so discontinue all anesthetic and prepare to resuscitate"],"answer":1,"explain":"Involuntary paddling, vocalizing, and exaggerated reflexes after loss of consciousness are hallmarks of Stage II excitement. Good premedication and a smooth, prompt induction minimize time spent here, reducing injury, arrhythmias, and aspiration as the patient transitions into a stable surgical plane (Stage III). Option A mislabels the stage, and this is neither surgical plane nor Stage IV."},{"id":"map04","domain":"Anesthetic Principles","q":"Under isoflurane, a dog's eyeball has rotated ventromedially (down and in) with a sluggish but still-present palpebral reflex and relaxed jaw tone, and there is no purposeful response to surgical stimulation. How should the anesthetist interpret these signs?","options":["A light plane; the persisting palpebral reflex means the dog is inadequately anesthetized and needs urgent deepening","An adequate surgical plane for a typical inhalant anesthetic","An excessively deep (Stage IV) plane, with the ventromedial rotation warning of impending overdose","Early emergence; the eye rotates ventromedially as animals begin to wake"],"answer":1,"explain":"With most inhalant anesthetics, a ventromedially rotated eye with a diminished (but present) palpebral reflex and relaxed jaw indicates an adequate surgical plane. At a very deep plane the eye rotates back to central and reflexes are lost; at a light plane reflexes are brisk. (Dissociatives such as ketamine keep the eye central, so signs are agent-dependent and read in context.)"},{"id":"mc01","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"A fractious 4-kg feral cat cannot be safely restrained for IV catheter placement, so you plan intramuscular chemical restraint and choose alfaxalone. Which property of its formulation makes a relatively low-volume, non-irritating IM injection feasible?","options":["It is solubilized in a cyclodextrin vehicle, giving a relatively non-irritating, concentrated solution suitable for low-volume IM injection","It is formulated in propylene glycol, which buffers the injectate and prevents IM irritation","It is an egg-lecithin lipid emulsion like propofol, which is non-irritating in muscle","It is supplied as a lyophilized powder reconstituted with saline, eliminating any carrier"],"answer":0,"explain":"Alfaxalone is solubilized in a cyclodextrin (2-hydroxypropyl-beta-cyclodextrin) carrier rather than propylene glycol or cremophor, making it relatively non-irritating and concentrated enough for practical IM injection when IV access is not possible, though IV titration to effect remains the standard route. Propylene glycol is itself irritating and is the diazepam vehicle, alfaxalone is not a lipid emulsion, and it is supplied as a ready-made solution."},{"id":"mc02","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"A 14-year-old, 4.5-kg cat with hypertrophic cardiomyopathy and left-sided congestive heart failure requires induction for an emergency procedure. You choose etomidate. What is the primary hemodynamic rationale?","options":["It is a potent negative inotrope that lowers cardiac work and myocardial oxygen demand","It causes minimal myocardial depression, preserving contractility and blood pressure during induction","It inhibits adrenal cortisol synthesis, blunting the stress response and thereby stabilizing the heart","It relieves dynamic left ventricular outflow obstruction through direct coronary vasodilation"],"answer":1,"explain":"Etomidate is chosen in severe cardiac disease because it causes minimal cardiovascular depression, preserving contractility and blood pressure at induction. It is not a negative inotrope. Although etomidate does suppress adrenocortical cortisol synthesis, that is a drawback (along with myoclonus and pain on injection), not the hemodynamic rationale, and it does not relieve outflow obstruction by coronary vasodilation."},{"id":"mc03","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"A near-term pregnant Bulldog undergoing an emergency cesarean develops intraoperative bradycardia, and you need an anticholinergic while minimizing effects on the fetuses. Why is glycopyrrolate often preferred over atropine in this setting?","options":["It readily crosses the placenta and directly raises the fetal heart rate, protecting the neonates","It is more lipid-soluble than atropine, giving a faster onset that is safer for the dam","It relaxes uterine smooth muscle, easing fetal extraction","As a quaternary amine it does not appreciably cross the placenta or the blood-brain barrier, sparing the fetuses central and cardiac anticholinergic effects"],"answer":3,"explain":"Glycopyrrolate is a quaternary ammonium compound that does not readily cross the placenta or the blood-brain barrier, so it treats the dam's bradycardia while limiting fetal and central anticholinergic effects; its onset is slower than atropine's. Atropine (a tertiary amine) does cross the placenta, but glycopyrrolate's inability to cross is why it is preferred here; it is less lipid-soluble (not more) and has no useful uterine-relaxant action."},{"id":"mc04","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"A 12-year-old, 9-kg dog with chronic degenerative mitral valve disease has been on enalapril for a year and is anesthetized with isoflurane for dental extractions. The mean arterial pressure falls to 55 mmHg and improves only slightly after a 10 mL/kg crystalloid bolus. What best explains this?","options":["Chronic enalapril blunts the renin-angiotensin-aldosterone compensatory response, so anesthetic vasodilation produces hypotension that is often refractory to fluids alone and may need a vasopressor or inotrope","ACE inhibitors sensitize the myocardium to circulating catecholamines, so the low reading reflects catecholamine-driven vasoconstriction","Long-term ACE inhibition causes chronic volume overload, so additional crystalloid predictably worsens the pressure","ACE inhibitors raise anesthetic requirements, so the dog is simply too lightly anesthetized"],"answer":0,"explain":"ACE inhibitors blunt the renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system's compensatory vasoconstriction, so patients on chronic therapy are prone to anesthetic hypotension that may not respond fully to fluids and often requires a vasopressor or inotrope (e.g., dopamine, norepinephrine, or dobutamine). They do not cause catecholamine-driven hypertension, chronic volume overload, or increased anesthetic requirements."},{"id":"mc05","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"A 25-kg dog recovering from a TPLO received a hydromorphone premedication and an intraoperative fentanyl CRI. In recovery he is deeply sedate with a respiratory rate of 6 and shallow excursions, and SpO2 drifts to 90% on room air. Which opioid effect is the priority to monitor and manage?","options":["Mydriasis reducing vision and delaying return of protective reflexes","Opioid-induced panting leading to respiratory alkalosis and hypocapnia","Respiratory depression and sedation: support ventilation, provide oxygen, and titrate naloxone if severe","Opioid-induced diuresis producing hypovolemia and hypotension"],"answer":2,"explain":"The hypoventilation (rate of 6, shallow breaths) with falling SpO2 and deep sedation is opioid-induced respiratory depression, which can persist into recovery and is the priority concern: provide oxygen, support ventilation, and titrate naloxone if depression is significant. Opioids can cause panting in some dogs, but that does not fit this hypoventilating picture; mydriasis and diuresis are not the safety priority here."},{"id":"mc06","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"A 5-kg cat received buprenorphine for postoperative analgesia but shows moderate breakthrough pain. You add a full mu agonist (hydromorphone), yet the additional analgesia is blunted, and a later dose of naloxone only partially reverses the effect. Which property of buprenorphine best explains these observations?","options":["It has low mu-receptor affinity and is rapidly displaced, so its effect is brief and easily overridden","It is a pure mu antagonist, so any analgesia present comes only from the added full agonist","It is a full mu agonist whose short duration of action explains the breakthrough pain","It binds mu receptors with high affinity but produces only a sub-maximal (ceiling) effect, so it can limit the added full agonist's response and resist reversal"],"answer":3,"explain":"Buprenorphine is a partial mu agonist: it binds with high affinity but produces a sub-maximal (ceiling) effect, giving long duration yet limited maximal analgesia. Its high affinity means it can blunt the effect of a subsequently added full agonist and resist antagonism by naloxone. It is not low-affinity, not a pure antagonist, and not a full agonist."},{"id":"mc07","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"A healthy 3-year-old, 18-kg dog needs about 10 minutes of sedation to measure and photograph several skin masses before same-day discharge. You select dexmedetomidine partly for one practical advantage in a brief outpatient case. What is it?","options":["It reaches surgical anesthetic depth on its own, so no additional agents are required","Its sedation can be antagonized with atipamezole, allowing a rapid, controlled recovery and prompt discharge","It has negligible cardiovascular effects, so close monitoring can be skipped for a quick case","Its effect self-terminates within about five minutes, making procedure timing unnecessary"],"answer":1,"explain":"A key practical advantage of an alpha-2 agonist like dexmedetomidine for brief procedures is that its sedation can be antagonized with atipamezole, giving a rapid, controlled recovery ideal for outpatient work. It does not by itself provide surgical anesthesia, it has marked cardiovascular effects (vasoconstriction, hypertension, reflex bradycardia) that demand monitoring, and its effect does not self-terminate in five minutes."},{"id":"mc08","domain":"Pharmacology","q":"A 30-kg dog on chronic carprofen for osteoarthritis is presented with acute pruritic allergic dermatitis, and a colleague suggests adding oral prednisone for rapid relief. What is the primary concern with giving an NSAID and a corticosteroid together, and what is advised?","options":["The two provide additive renal protection, so the combination is safe with routine monitoring","Concurrent use markedly increases the risk of gastrointestinal ulceration and perforation and should be avoided; a washout is advised when switching classes","The combination yields a stronger anti-inflammatory effect with no meaningful increase in risk","The corticosteroid pharmacologically reverses the NSAID, neutralizing the effects of both"],"answer":1,"explain":"Combining an NSAID (carprofen) with a corticosteroid (prednisone) markedly increases the risk of gastrointestinal ulceration and perforation and is contraindicated; an appropriate washout period is advised when transitioning between the classes. The combination is not renally protective, does not carry no added risk, and the drugs do not neutralize each other."},{"id":"mc09","domain":"Physiology","q":"During a long procedure on a septic dog, a working muscle capillary bed is hypercarbic (high local PCO2), acidotic (low pH), and warm. At this tissue capillary, how is hemoglobin's oxygen affinity affected, and what is the benefit?","options":["Affinity increases (left shift), holding oxygen on hemoglobin to protect reserves","Affinity decreases (right shift), so hemoglobin offloads more oxygen to the metabolically active tissue — the Bohr effect","No change occurs, because temperature and pH do not influence the dissociation curve","Affinity decreases only if 2,3-DPG is simultaneously reduced"],"answer":1,"explain":"Acidosis, hypercarbia, hyperthermia, and increased 2,3-DPG all right-shift the oxyhemoglobin dissociation curve, lowering hemoglobin's O2 affinity so more oxygen is released to metabolically active tissues (the Bohr effect). A left shift (increased affinity) accompanies alkalosis, hypocarbia, hypothermia, and DECREASED 2,3-DPG — so reduced 2,3-DPG causes the opposite of a right shift, and temperature/pH clearly do affect the curve."},{"id":"mc10","domain":"Physiology","q":"An anesthetized dog is hypotensive with a low CVP and small, underfilled-looking ventricles on the monitor. After a 10 mL/kg isotonic crystalloid bolus, the arterial pressure and pulse pressure both improve. Within physiologic limits, which mechanism best explains the improvement?","options":["Increased preload stretches the myocardium, raising contractile force and stroke volume (Frank-Starling)","Increased preload reflexively lowers stroke volume to protect the ventricle","The bolus simply raised heart rate, and rate alone accounts for the higher pressure","The added fluid increased afterload, and higher afterload directly augments stroke volume"],"answer":0,"explain":"By the Frank-Starling mechanism, greater end-diastolic volume (preload) stretches myocardial fibers, increasing contractile force and stroke volume — up to a physiologic limit beyond which further filling does not help. The WIDENED pulse pressure signals improved stroke volume, not merely a faster rate, and increased afterload would reduce, not raise, stroke volume. This underlies the cardiovascular response to appropriate fluid loading."},{"id":"mc11","domain":"Physiology","q":"Before a rapid-sequence induction in a 20-kg, term-pregnant English Bulldog, you deliver 3-5 minutes of 100% oxygen by a well-fitting mask. Physiologically, what does this accomplish, and why does it matter specifically in this patient?","options":["It denitrogenates and fills the functional residual capacity with oxygen, creating a reservoir that delays desaturation during the apnea of induction — vital because pregnancy and brachycephalic conformation reduce FRC","It maximizes the forced expiratory volume the patient can generate, improving CO2 clearance during induction","It expands anatomic dead space so more oxygen is stored in the conducting airways","It raises plasma-dissolved oxygen enough to meet whole-body demand for several minutes without hemoglobin"],"answer":0,"explain":"Preoxygenation denitrogenates the lungs and fills the functional residual capacity (the gas remaining at end-expiration) with oxygen, forming a reservoir that sustains arterial oxygenation through the apnea of induction/intubation. It matters most when FRC is reduced and oxygen demand is high — a gravid uterus displaces the diaphragm cranially and brachycephalic/obese conformation shrinks FRC, both hastening desaturation. FRC is not forced expiratory volume or dead space, and dissolved plasma oxygen is far too little to meet demand."},{"id":"mc12","domain":"Physiology","q":"A young dog with a chronic pyloric outflow obstruction has vomited gastric fluid for several days and presents lethargic and dehydrated before surgery. Which acid-base and electrolyte disturbance do you most expect, and what should be corrected before induction?","options":["Hyperchloremic metabolic acidosis from bicarbonate-rich losses","Hypochloremic, hypokalemic metabolic alkalosis from loss of gastric hydrochloric acid","Primary respiratory acidosis from vomiting-related hypoventilation","Metabolic acidosis from gastric acid accumulating in the circulation"],"answer":1,"explain":"Vomiting of gastric contents — especially with pyloric outflow obstruction, where acidic gastric fluid is selectively lost — depletes hydrogen and chloride and produces a hypochloremic (often hypokalemic) metabolic alkalosis. Lower-GI/diarrheal losses cause a hyperchloremic acidosis instead, and the acid is LOST from the body rather than accumulating in blood. Correct with a chloride-rich isotonic fluid and potassium supplementation before anesthesia."},{"id":"mc13","domain":"Physiology","q":"A dog develops significant atelectasis of one lung lobe under anesthesia; in that hypoxic, poorly ventilated region the local pulmonary arterioles constrict. What is the purpose of this hypoxic pulmonary vasoconstriction, and how can anesthesia undermine it?","options":["It diverts blood away from the poorly ventilated region toward better-ventilated lung, improving V/Q matching and limiting shunt; potent inhalants can blunt this response","It increases blood flow to the collapsed region to speed its re-expansion","It lowers systemic arterial pressure to reduce myocardial workload","It is a systemic vasoconstriction that raises afterload to defend perfusion pressure"],"answer":0,"explain":"Hypoxic pulmonary vasoconstriction is a local response that constricts arterioles supplying poorly ventilated (hypoxic) alveoli, redirecting blood toward better-ventilated regions; this improves ventilation-perfusion matching and limits venous admixture/shunt. It raises resistance in the affected area, so it does NOT boost flow to the collapsed lobe, and it is a pulmonary — not systemic — phenomenon. Volatile anesthetics attenuate HPV in a dose-dependent way, which can worsen oxygenation."},{"id":"mc14","domain":"Equipment","q":"Two hours into an orthopedic procedure on a circle system, the capnograph baseline has risen to 6 mmHg and is climbing. You palpate the absorbent canister: the granules are hard and brittle, the canister is cool, and the indicator is uniformly pale with no color change. The correct interpretation is:","options":["The absorbent is exhausted and must be replaced to stop CO2 rebreathing","The absorbent is fresh, because it shows no color change","The granules simply need water added to rehydrate them","A stuck expiratory valve is causing the rebreathing"],"answer":0,"explain":"Exhausted absorbent becomes hard and brittle, stops the exothermic CO2 reaction (so the canister goes cool), and no longer changes color (the indicator can also revert to pale on resting), letting inspired CO2 rise - it must be replaced. A pale canister alone can fool you, but combined with hard, brittle, cool granules and a rising inspired baseline, exhaustion is the answer, not fresh lime, rehydration, or a valve fault."},{"id":"mc15","domain":"Equipment","q":"You are choosing a breathing system for a 4-hour procedure on a 35 kg dog and specifically want to minimize airway heat and moisture loss. Which choice best supports that goal?","options":["A non-rebreathing (Bain) circuit run at high oxygen flows","A circle system flushed frequently with the oxygen flush to keep the bag full","A rebreathing (circle) system at low fresh gas flows, recycling warmed, humidified exhaled gas","A circle system run at high fresh gas flows for the whole case"],"answer":2,"explain":"A rebreathing/circle system recycles exhaled gas - already warmed and humidified by the patient - through the absorber, conserving heat and moisture, especially at low fresh gas flows. Running the same circle at high flows, or repeatedly using the oxygen flush, washes out that warmed, humidified gas and defeats the purpose; a high-flow non-rebreathing circuit is the least conserving option of all."},{"id":"mc16","domain":"Equipment","q":"On your pre-use check you inflate an endotracheal tube's cuff and it slowly self-deflates. If you used this tube for a canine dental with the mouth full of water and debris, the GREATEST specific risk would be:","options":["The tube sliding out of the trachea (accidental extubation)","Aspiration of water and debris plus gas leakage causing inadequate ventilation, because the cuff cannot seal the airway","Pressure necrosis of the tracheal mucosa","Higher anesthetic gas costs from leakage"],"answer":1,"explain":"A cuff that will not hold air cannot seal the airway, so lavage water and debris can be aspirated and anesthetic gas leaks around the tube, impairing ventilation and increasing pollution. Aspiration is the greatest specific danger in a wet dental field. Mucosal pressure necrosis comes from OVER-inflation (the opposite problem), and gas cost is trivial by comparison."},{"id":"mc17","domain":"Equipment","q":"After manually ventilating a patient on a circle system, you believe you reopened the pop-off (APL) valve. A few minutes later, the EARLIEST sign that it was actually left closed will be:","options":["A rapidly deflating, empty reservoir bag","An immediate drop in ETCO2","A gradual lightening of anesthetic depth","A progressively distending reservoir bag with rising circuit pressure"],"answer":3,"explain":"With the pop-off closed, exhaled gas has nowhere to vent, so the reservoir bag progressively overfills and circuit/airway pressure climbs - the earliest warning before barotrauma. The valve must be reopened immediately. A deflating, empty bag indicates the opposite problem (a leak or excess scavenging), not a closed pop-off."},{"id":"mc18","domain":"Monitoring","q":"Under stable isoflurane anesthesia with adequate ventilation, you examine the capnogram to confirm it is normal. Which pattern represents a NORMAL steady-state capnogram?","options":["A near-square wave with a sharp expiratory upstroke, an alveolar plateau (peak = ETCO2), and a return to a zero baseline during inspiration","A square wave with an alveolar plateau but a baseline that stays elevated and never returns to zero","A steadily rising line with no distinct plateaus","A flat line at zero"],"answer":0,"explain":"A normal capnogram is a near-square waveform: a sharp expiratory upstroke, an alveolar plateau whose peak equals ETCO2, and a return to a zero baseline on inspiration. A baseline that never reaches zero signals rebreathing; a flat line at zero means apnea or disconnection; a continuously rising line is abnormal."},{"id":"mc19","domain":"Monitoring","q":"A small dog becomes hypothermic (34C) during a long procedure, and the pulse oximeter now drops out and reads erratically on both the tongue and a toe web. The most likely reason is:","options":["Cold has lowered the blood's hemoglobin concentration","Hypothermia has shifted the oxyhemoglobin curve so saturation can no longer be measured","Peripheral vasoconstriction and poor perfusion have weakened the pulsatile arterial signal the oximeter needs","Interference from the overhead surgical lamp"],"answer":2,"explain":"Pulse oximeters require a pulsatile arterial signal. Hypothermia causes peripheral vasoconstriction and low perfusion, weakening that signal and causing dropout or erratic values across multiple sites - a reason to prevent and correct hypothermia. Temperature does left-shift the oxyhemoglobin curve, but that does not stop the device from reading; ambient light can interfere but does not fit this hypothermic, multi-site pattern."},{"id":"mc20","domain":"Monitoring","q":"An anesthetized dog premedicated with dexmedetomidine has an ECG with a regular P-wave rate, but intermittently a P wave is not followed by a QRS; the conducted beats have normal QRS morphology. This rhythm is best classified as:","options":["Third-degree (complete) AV block","Second-degree AV block - some P waves fail to conduct to the ventricles","Atrial fibrillation","Ventricular premature complexes"],"answer":1,"explain":"Second-degree AV block is intermittent failure of atrial impulses to reach the ventricles - some P waves are not followed by a QRS, while others conduct normally. Dexmedetomidine (an alpha-2 agonist) raises vagal tone and commonly causes it. In complete (third-degree) block, P waves and QRS are entirely dissociated; atrial fibrillation has no discrete P waves; VPCs are wide, bizarre QRS complexes."},{"id":"mc21","domain":"Monitoring","q":"Your Doppler reads 180 mmHg systolic on a stable anesthetized cat that has a strong pulse and a normal heart rate. You realize the cuff you applied has a width only about 25% of the limb circumference. This cuff size will make the reading:","options":["Accurate - cuff width does not affect Doppler pressures","Falsely LOW, because a narrow cuff underestimates pressure","Unpredictable in direction","Falsely HIGH, because a cuff narrower than ~40% of limb circumference overestimates blood pressure"],"answer":3,"explain":"Cuff width should be about 40% of limb circumference. A cuff that is too narrow requires more pressure to occlude the artery and therefore reads falsely high, whereas a too-wide cuff reads falsely low. A ~25% cuff on an otherwise stable cat is the classic cause of a spuriously high 180 mmHg, so the value is artifactually elevated - correct sizing is essential."},{"id":"mc22","domain":"Pain Management","q":"A 6-year-old, 30-kg dog recovering from a hemilaminectomy flinches and vocalizes when a nurse lightly strokes intact skin lateral to the incision — an area that should not itself be painful. This finding is best described as:","options":["Wind-up — progressive escalation of dorsal horn neuron firing with repeated identical noxious input","Hyperalgesia — an exaggerated pain response to a stimulus that is itself normally painful","Allodynia — pain evoked by a normally non-noxious stimulus, reflecting central sensitization","Nociceptive (physiologic) pain — a normal, protective, stimulus-appropriate response"],"answer":2,"explain":"Allodynia is pain produced by a stimulus that is not normally painful — here, light stroking of intact skin — and is a hallmark of central sensitization/maladaptive pain. Hyperalgesia is an amplified response to a stimulus that is already noxious (the decisive difference), wind-up describes a specific dorsal-horn mechanism under repeated noxious input, and physiologic nociceptive pain is stimulus-appropriate — none fits pain from light touch."},{"id":"mc23","domain":"Pain Management","q":"During a mastectomy on a 20-kg dog you add local anesthetic infiltration along the incision line as part of a balanced protocol. Which statement best explains the primary anesthetic benefit of adding this regional technique?","options":["It interrupts nociceptive transmission at its source, lowering inhalant and systemic opioid requirements and limiting central sensitization","It abolishes nociception so completely that systemic analgesia becomes unnecessary for the procedure","Its chief value is the deep sedation it adds, sparing injectable induction agent","It reliably raises arterial blood pressure, which is its main intraoperative benefit"],"answer":0,"explain":"Local/regional techniques block nociceptive input at or near its origin, which reduces systemic anesthetic and opioid requirements and limits central sensitization — the core rationale for including them in a balanced, multimodal plan. They do not by themselves guarantee complete analgesia (systemic drugs remain part of the plan), provide no sedation, and do not reliably raise blood pressure (systemic absorption can actually lower it)."},{"id":"mc24","domain":"Local/Regional","q":"A 12-kg dog is sedated but not anesthetized for a bupivacaine intercostal block before chest-tube placement. Within a minute of injection the dog develops muscle twitching and facial tremors that progress toward a seizure. What is the most likely explanation?","options":["A localized allergic reaction to the amide local anesthetic","Inadvertent intravascular injection causing acute systemic local anesthetic toxicity","The expected neurologic response as the sensory block takes effect","Hypoglycemia from prolonged preoperative fasting"],"answer":1,"explain":"CNS excitation — twitching, tremors, and seizures — within a minute of a local anesthetic injection is the classic early presentation of systemic local anesthetic toxicity from inadvertent intravascular delivery, and with bupivacaine can progress to cardiovascular collapse. Amide local anesthetic allergy is rare and would not produce this immediate excitatory picture, a functioning block does not cause seizures, and the tight temporal link to the injection points away from fasting hypoglycemia. Aspiration and incremental dosing reduce this risk."},{"id":"mc25","domain":"Local/Regional","q":"A 3.5-kg, 1-year-old cat is scheduled for a bilateral forelimb onychectomy (declaw). Which regional anesthetic technique is most appropriate to provide analgesia for the procedure?","options":["A lumbosacral epidural, to desensitize the distal limbs bilaterally","Sciatic and femoral nerve blocks of each affected limb","Systemic opioids alone; a regional block is unnecessary for onychectomy","A four-point (ring) block of the distal forelimb with local anesthetic, kept within the cat's maximum safe dose"],"answer":3,"explain":"Onychectomy is a painful distal forelimb (digit) procedure, best served by a distal four-point or ring block that desensitizes the paw while sparing systemic anesthetic — provided the local anesthetic stays within the cat's low maximum safe dose. Epidurals and sciatic/femoral blocks target the pelvic limbs, and relying on systemic opioids alone under-treats this notably painful surgery."},{"id":"mc26","domain":"Emergency/CPR","q":"A 15-kg dog arrests under anesthesia and is already intubated; the team is delivering chest compressions. A newer team member asks how ventilation should be coordinated with compressions. The correct RECOVER approach for this intubated patient is:","options":["Pause compressions briefly to deliver each breath, then resume","Deliver continuous, uninterrupted compressions at 100-120/min with simultaneous ventilation at about 10 breaths/min","Give 30 compressions followed by 2 breaths, pausing for each ventilation","Hyperventilate at 20-30 breaths/min to maximize oxygen delivery"],"answer":1,"explain":"Once the airway is secured with an endotracheal tube, RECOVER recommends continuous, uninterrupted chest compressions at 100-120/min with simultaneous ventilation at roughly 10 breaths/min. Pausing for breaths or using 30:2 cycles belongs to the non-intubated setting, and hyperventilation (20-30/min) raises intrathoracic pressure and impairs venous return and perfusion."},{"id":"mc27","domain":"Emergency/CPR","q":"A few minutes into CPR on a dog, a team member draws up high-dose epinephrine (0.1 mg/kg) as the first dose; the anesthetist redirects to low-dose (0.01 mg/kg). The best reason to prefer the low dose early in the arrest is that:","options":["Low-dose epinephrine is less expensive to use","High-dose epinephrine reverses more predictably once ROSC is achieved","High-dose epinephrine causes excessive vasoconstriction and increased myocardial oxygen demand, worsening post-arrest myocardial function and outcomes","High-dose epinephrine is more likely to trigger a shockable rhythm that then cannot be defibrillated"],"answer":2,"explain":"RECOVER recommends low-dose epinephrine (0.01 mg/kg) every other BLS cycle early in CPR. High doses cause excessive vasoconstriction and raise myocardial oxygen demand, contributing to worse post-resuscitation myocardial dysfunction and outcomes; high dose is reserved only for prolonged efforts. Cost is irrelevant, epinephrine is not 'reversed,' and its benefit is not about defibrillation."},{"id":"mc28","domain":"Calculations","q":"A 30 kg, 4-year-old Labrador (ASA II) is anesthetized for a TPLO. You give surgical prophylaxis with cefazolin 22 mg/kg IV about 45 minutes before incision, from a reconstituted 100 mg/mL vial. What volume delivers the dose?","options":["3.3 mL","6.6 mL","13.2 mL","0.66 mL"],"answer":1,"explain":"Dose = 30 kg × 22 mg/kg = 660 mg; volume = 660 mg ÷ 100 mg/mL = 6.6 mL. 3.3 mL is half the dose (≈11 mg/kg), 13.2 mL is double, and 0.66 mL is a decimal (÷1000) slip. Cefazolin is best given ~30–60 min before incision and redosed every 90–120 min for long procedures."},{"id":"mc29","domain":"Calculations","q":"A 40 kg, 9-year-old Rottweiler (ASA II) is anesthetized for a lipoma removal and placed on a conservative intraoperative crystalloid rate of 3 mL/kg/hr. What hourly fluid volume do you set on the pump?","options":["80 mL/hr","120 mL/hr","160 mL/hr","40 mL/hr"],"answer":1,"explain":"40 kg × 3 mL/kg/hr = 120 mL/hr. 80 mL/hr uses 2 mL/kg/hr, 160 mL/hr uses the older 4 mL/kg/hr rate (a tempting near-miss), and 40 mL/hr is body weight alone. Conservative intraoperative rates are titrated to blood pressure and perfusion to avoid volume overload."},{"id":"mc30","domain":"Calculations","q":"You draw up 2 mg of hydromorphone from a 2 mg/mL vial for a 20 kg dog and plan to give it as a slow IV push in a total volume of 1 mL. How much saline diluent must you add to reach that 1 mL total?","options":["0.5 mL of saline","1 mL of saline","None — 2 mg already equals 1 mL of drug, which matches the 1 mL target, so no diluent is added","2 mL of saline"],"answer":2,"explain":"2 mg ÷ 2 mg/mL = 1 mL of drug, and the desired total volume is 1 mL, so diluent = 1 mL − 1 mL = 0 mL. 0.5 mL assumes the drug volume is only 0.5 mL (mis-reading concentration), 1 mL reflects the habit of always adding an equal volume of diluent, and 2 mL over-dilutes to a larger total. Recognizing when the drawn volume already equals the target prevents dilution errors."},{"id":"mc31","domain":"Species-Specific","q":"A 400 g parrot under isoflurane is placed in dorsal recumbency with a snug body wrap for an imaging-guided procedure. Within minutes ETCO2 climbs and its body-wall excursions diminish. What is the most likely mechanism, and the principle it illustrates?","options":["Birds have large lung reserves, so this is transient and will self-correct without intervention","Restraint limiting sternal/keel movement impairs the air-sac ventilation birds depend on, quickly causing hypoventilation; assisted or controlled ventilation is often required","Isoflurane is poorly effective in birds, so the rising CO2 reflects inadequate depth rather than a ventilation problem","Birds lack a diaphragm but ventilate through true alveoli like mammals, so positioning cannot affect gas exchange"],"answer":1,"explain":"Birds have no diaphragm and ventilate their flow-through air-sac system by movement of the sternum/keel and body wall. Dorsal recumbency and a tight wrap restrict that movement and rapidly cause hypoventilation and CO2 retention, so assisted or controlled ventilation is frequently needed. Option D is anatomically wrong (birds use parabronchi, not alveoli) and its conclusion that positioning is irrelevant is exactly backward."},{"id":"mc32","domain":"Species-Specific","q":"A 500 kg, 8-year-old Warmblood gelding has undergone 2 hours of general anesthesia for colic surgery, and the team is planning recovery. Which factor makes this phase among the most dangerous of equine anesthesia?","options":["Horses cannot be monitored once disconnected from the anesthetic machine, leaving recovery essentially blind","The horse's large body mass and flight instinct make a coordinated return to standing hazardous, risking long-bone fractures, myopathy, and injury","Horses are uniquely resistant to hypotension, so the only real danger is that they wake too quickly for staff to react","Inhalant anesthetic accumulates in the large muscle mass and causes prolonged re-sedation hours after standing"],"answer":1,"explain":"Recovery is the highest-mortality phase of equine anesthesia: the horse's mass and flight instinct make regaining its feet hazardous, risking catastrophic long-bone fractures, myopathy, and other injury. Assisted or quiet recovery techniques aim to reduce this. Horses are not resistant to hypotension, and myopathy stems from positioning and perfusion, not delayed inhalant re-sedation."},{"id":"mc33","domain":"Complications","q":"A 6-kg cat on mechanical ventilation at fixed settings shows an abrupt, sustained fall in ETCO2 from 36 to 12 mmHg. The endotracheal tube position and patency are confirmed and the ventilator settings are unchanged. The next consideration is:","options":["The anesthetic plane has become too light","A fall in cardiac output and pulmonary blood flow (e.g., hypotension, pulmonary embolism, or impending arrest)","Excessive analgesia depressing metabolism","Rising body temperature increasing CO2 production"],"answer":1,"explain":"With ventilation and airway confirmed unchanged, an abrupt sustained ETCO2 fall reflects a drop in pulmonary blood flow — from falling cardiac output, hypotension, pulmonary thromboembolism, or impending cardiac arrest — so circulation and perfusion must be assessed urgently. A light plane or analgesia does not cause this, and increased CO2 production (e.g., hyperthermia) would raise, not lower, ETCO2."},{"id":"mc34","domain":"Complications","q":"A 2.2-kg cat is being prepared for a 90-minute procedure and the team wants to keep her normothermic. Given her high surface-area-to-volume ratio and anesthesia-abolished thermoregulation, the most effective strategy is to:","options":["Wait until the temperature drops below 37°C, then begin active warming","Begin active warming (forced warm air, warmed IV fluids) at induction and minimize heat loss throughout","Withhold warming and rely on the patient's own metabolic heat production under anesthesia","Apply generous volumes of room-temperature surgical scrub to reduce shivering"],"answer":1,"explain":"Anesthesia abolishes thermoregulation and small patients lose heat rapidly, so hypothermia is far easier to prevent than to reverse. Active warming (forced warm-air devices, warmed IV fluids), insulation, and minimizing exposure and wet fur should begin at induction and continue throughout. Waiting for the temperature to fall, relying on suppressed metabolic heat, or applying room-temperature scrub (which increases evaporative loss) all permit avoidable hypothermia."},{"id":"mc35","domain":"Ventilation/Fluids","q":"During an intraocular procedure, a dog is given a non-depolarizing neuromuscular blocking agent to center the globe. Immediately after administration, which is the single most important anesthetic management change?","options":["Reduce the inhalant, since the neuromuscular blocker also contributes to unconsciousness and anesthetic depth","Institute controlled positive-pressure ventilation, because the paralyzed patient cannot breathe spontaneously","Increase the IV fluid rate to speed clearance of the drug and shorten the period of paralysis","Discontinue capnography, because ETCO2 readings are unreliable during neuromuscular blockade"],"answer":1,"explain":"A neuromuscular blocking agent paralyzes the respiratory muscles, so the patient cannot ventilate on its own and controlled positive-pressure ventilation becomes mandatory. Critically, these agents provide no anesthesia or analgesia, so reducing the inhalant (A) risks awareness; fluids do not meaningfully shorten paralysis, and capnography remains essential."},{"id":"mc36","domain":"Ventilation/Fluids","q":"A hypoproteinemic dog (albumin 1.5 g/dL) stays hypotensive despite crystalloid boluses, and the clinician considers a synthetic colloid such as hetastarch. Compared with an equal volume of crystalloid, what property explains the colloid's effect?","options":["Its molecules are small enough to distribute rapidly into the interstitium, hydrating the tissues directly","Its large molecules stay intravascular longer, expanding plasma volume more per milliliter infused","It carries oxygen the way whole blood does, correcting perfusion by raising blood oxygen content","It supplies free water that shifts into cells and expands total body water"],"answer":1,"explain":"Colloids contain large molecules that remain in the vasculature longer than crystalloids, expanding plasma volume more efficiently per milliliter. They carry no oxygen and do not primarily hydrate the interstitium or cells. Because of coagulation and kidney concerns, crystalloids remain first-line, with colloids used selectively, but the mechanism asked here is intravascular volume expansion."},{"id":"mc37","domain":"Anesthetic Principles","q":"After two near-misses (a mislabeled syringe and an almost-empty oxygen tank), a busy surgical service considers adopting a standardized pre-induction time-out. What is the primary value of this practice?","options":["It slows the team down, and the delay by itself is what reduces errors","It systematically verifies patient, procedure, equipment, drug doses, and plan, catching omissions before they cause harm","It shifts legal responsibility for any error from the anesthetist onto the whole team","It lets the team reduce intraoperative monitoring, since problems are caught beforehand"],"answer":1,"explain":"A preanesthetic time-out/checklist systematically confirms patient identity, procedure, equipment readiness (including oxygen supply), drug labeling and doses, and the anesthetic plan, catching exactly the kinds of omissions in this scenario before they reach the patient. Its value is error prevention, not merely slowing down, reassigning liability, or reducing the vigilant monitoring that must continue throughout."}];

const DOMAINS = [...new Set(PRACTICE_POOL.map(q => q.domain))].sort();

// ── Shuffle helpers ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
function shuffle(arr) {
  const a = [...arr];
  for (let i = a.length - 1; i > 0; i--) {
    const j = Math.floor(Math.random() * (i + 1));
    [a[i], a[j]] = [a[j], a[i]];
  }
  return a;
}

// Shuffle a question's answer options while tracking the new correct index
function shuffleOptions(q) {
  const idxs = shuffle([0, 1, 2, 3]);
  return {
    ...q,
    options: idxs.map(i => q.options[i]),
    answer: idxs.indexOf(q.answer),
  };
}

// Build a fresh randomized set: pick N questions from a pool, shuffle their options
function buildSet(pool, n) {
  return shuffle(pool).slice(0, n).map(shuffleOptions);
}

